WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:24.760
I do not remember my name. This is the first

00:24.760 --> 00:28.040
thing that I think when I wake and I look

00:28.040 --> 00:32.720
around nervously, confused by the dark and by the thick

00:32.720 --> 00:36.120
fog which surrounds me. I raise a hand

00:36.120 --> 00:39.860
to my face and feel a short nose and a

00:39.860 --> 00:44.660
small mouth. I try to remember my face. I try

00:44.660 --> 00:45.100
to remember

00:45.100 --> 00:47.660
the color of my hair or what my eyes look

00:47.660 --> 00:54.060
like. I try to remember anything. But I cannot. I

00:54.060 --> 00:54.340
have

00:54.340 --> 00:58.400
no idea who I am. I am on the ground,

00:58.940 --> 01:02.640
lying on cold grass which is wet from the fog.

01:03.840 --> 01:07.560
And I am alone. Why am I here? I ask

01:07.560 --> 01:11.380
myself. But I have no answer. I do not even

01:11.380 --> 01:12.060
know where

01:12.060 --> 01:15.380
this is because the fog is so thick that I

01:15.380 --> 01:18.240
can only see for a few meters in any direction.

01:18.950 --> 01:21.960
I try to stand but then I realize that my

01:21.960 --> 01:25.820
head hurts and that there's a sharp pain behind my

01:25.820 --> 01:29.580
right ear. I carefully lift my hand and touch the

01:29.580 --> 01:32.800
large lump which is there. It hurts to touch

01:33.310 --> 01:36.480
and I shout in the fog, the sound lost in

01:36.480 --> 01:39.100
the dark of the night. When I pull my fingers

01:39.100 --> 01:39.400
away

01:39.400 --> 01:42.920
they are wet and even with no light the blood

01:42.920 --> 01:46.780
is bright and easy to see. I begin to feel

01:46.780 --> 01:47.180
more

01:47.180 --> 01:51.760
than nervous now. I begin to feel scared. I imagine

01:51.760 --> 01:54.420
I can see shapes and figures in the fog

01:54.420 --> 01:57.400
and I want to run. I feel that I need

01:57.400 --> 02:00.200
to run, that there is somewhere I must be,

02:00.520 --> 02:04.020
somewhere I must remember. But before I move I need

02:04.020 --> 02:07.080
to know something. So I push myself up and

02:07.080 --> 02:10.560
sit on the ground. I look carefully at my clothes.

02:11.580 --> 02:15.240
But they mean nothing. The jeans are new.

02:16.080 --> 02:20.300
But now they're dirty. Muddy stains cover the legs from

02:20.300 --> 02:20.960
the wet grass.

02:21.960 --> 02:25.980
The t-shirt is not familiar either, just simple and

02:25.980 --> 02:28.980
black. So I empty my pockets and at first

02:28.980 --> 02:32.380
there is nothing helpful there, no wallet, no keys and

02:32.380 --> 02:35.040
no phone. But then I see the picture

02:35.660 --> 02:39.400
and I stop. It's a woman and even in the

02:39.400 --> 02:42.100
dark and the fog I recognize her.

02:42.100 --> 02:48.220
Her long blonde hair is beautiful and her kind friendly

02:48.220 --> 02:50.020
blue eyes are perfect.

02:50.800 --> 02:55.500
Yes, I know her. And the thought is so strong

02:55.500 --> 02:58.240
that I smile despite the pain in the back of

02:58.240 --> 02:58.640
my head.

02:59.440 --> 03:03.300
But what's her name? I pull the last item from

03:03.300 --> 03:12.080
my pocket. It's a red serviette with a single

03:12.080 --> 03:15.320
I say quietly into the fog and the sound of

03:15.320 --> 03:17.780
my voice seems strange and cold.

03:19.520 --> 03:23.200
Catherine, I am sure that I know her. But I

03:23.200 --> 03:27.340
still do not remember why. Is she my wife? My

03:27.340 --> 03:31.500
girlfriend? I think that she is. And I suddenly feel

03:31.500 --> 03:32.620
afraid for her.

03:34.000 --> 03:37.560
Catherine, I shout into the dark. But there is no

03:37.560 --> 03:41.180
reply. I'm about to shout again when suddenly

03:41.180 --> 03:45.040
I remember something. I remember Catherine's face.

03:45.800 --> 03:48.260
But she's not smiling like she is in the picture

03:48.260 --> 03:51.200
and her blue eyes look scared and desperate.

03:51.940 --> 03:55.080
I try to remember the image and I see that

03:55.080 --> 03:56.900
there's a piece of cloth in her mouth

03:56.900 --> 04:00.060
so that she cannot speak and that she's tied to

04:00.060 --> 04:03.220
a large grey stone by thick white ropes.

04:04.280 --> 04:08.020
No! I cry out and I push myself to my

04:08.020 --> 04:09.960
feet to spite the pain in my head.

04:10.620 --> 04:12.940
I do not know what to do for a moment.

04:13.500 --> 04:16.640
I only know that I must find her. That I

04:16.640 --> 04:17.580
must help her.

04:18.340 --> 04:19.980
I think about the lump on the back of my

04:19.980 --> 04:22.100
head and the fresh blood on my fingers.

04:22.760 --> 04:26.960
Is there somebody in the fog? Somebody who has Catherine.

04:28.040 --> 04:29.460
Someone who wants to hurt her.

04:29.460 --> 04:33.780
Who wants to kill her? I want to shout again.

04:34.540 --> 04:38.020
But then I do not. If the person who has

04:38.020 --> 04:38.580
Catherine

04:38.580 --> 04:43.260
hears me, she is in danger. And another image comes

04:43.260 --> 04:47.540
to me. It's the face of a man. An ordinary

04:47.540 --> 04:52.820
face with small dark eyes and dirty brown hair. There's

04:52.820 --> 04:54.980
nothing cruel about the face but I know

04:54.980 --> 04:59.100
instantly that this is the man that has Catherine and

04:59.100 --> 05:01.720
I hate that face with all of my heart.

05:02.680 --> 05:06.200
I begin to walk slowly at first, unsure of the

05:06.200 --> 05:07.520
direction that I must go.

05:08.120 --> 05:11.960
It seems like the ground is moving slowly up and

05:11.960 --> 05:14.520
I believe that this is right. The image I

05:14.520 --> 05:17.300
remember of Catherine tied to the grey stone is in

05:17.300 --> 05:19.580
less fog and I think that it must be on

05:19.580 --> 05:19.880
higher

05:19.880 --> 05:24.100
ground. I begin to walk faster but I'm soon running.

05:24.920 --> 05:27.040
The fog surrounds me and the dark is

05:27.040 --> 05:31.140
without end. I try not to think of anything but

05:31.140 --> 05:33.740
the direction I'm moving in but I'm starting

05:33.740 --> 05:38.480
to remember things now. I remember Catherine. She has a

05:38.480 --> 05:41.100
black uniform which she always wears at

05:41.100 --> 05:43.780
work in the restaurant and on the uniform is a

05:43.780 --> 05:47.260
badge with her name. Hello handsome. She always

05:47.260 --> 05:51.060
says to me. Another day at the office and I

05:51.060 --> 05:54.080
never say much but I do not have to. We

05:54.080 --> 05:54.320
understand

05:54.320 --> 05:58.280
each other without words and I remember that after I

05:58.280 --> 06:00.900
eat I wait for her in the car park until

06:00.900 --> 06:01.180
she

06:01.180 --> 06:04.800
finishes work and she's surprised to see me there but

06:04.800 --> 06:06.500
I suppose that's just who I am.

06:07.220 --> 06:12.480
A romantic. Suddenly there's a sound like a gunshot and

06:12.480 --> 06:14.940
I fall. For a moment I think that I'm

06:14.940 --> 06:17.920
dead and that Catherine is alone tied to the grey

06:17.920 --> 06:21.060
stone in the fog but then I see the light

06:21.060 --> 06:23.880
in the sky and I realize that the shot was

06:23.880 --> 06:27.580
a flare. I watch the light fall and illuminate

06:27.580 --> 06:31.140
the hillside. Is it the man with the dark eyes

06:31.140 --> 06:35.020
and dirty brown hair? Does he know I'm here? Good.

06:35.660 --> 06:38.460
If he looks for me he's not with Catherine I

06:38.460 --> 06:41.620
think and I get up again and run faster now.

06:42.080 --> 06:45.480
Do I hear voices in the fog behind me? I

06:45.480 --> 06:48.360
try to turn to look but the fog behind me

06:48.360 --> 06:48.940
is too thick

06:49.600 --> 06:52.440
and I only see the occasional light in the distance

06:52.440 --> 06:55.400
but in front of me the fog seems to be

06:55.400 --> 06:55.700
thinner

06:56.420 --> 07:00.460
and I begin to slow. I'm scared now because I

07:00.460 --> 07:03.520
know that I'm near and in the dark I begin

07:03.520 --> 07:04.260
to see

07:04.260 --> 07:08.080
large grey stones standing like giants on the top of

07:08.080 --> 07:11.660
the hill. In amazement I think that I

07:11.660 --> 07:19.000
recognize this circle of ancient stones. Stonehenge I say. Yes

07:19.000 --> 07:22.720
a voice replies and this is where it

07:22.720 --> 07:26.560
ends and a tall man steps from behind one of

07:26.560 --> 07:30.560
the silent giants. I expect him to have dark eyes

07:30.560 --> 07:34.680
and dirty hair but he does not. His hair is

07:34.680 --> 07:38.140
blonde, his eyes light and I think that this is

07:38.140 --> 07:38.680
not the

07:38.680 --> 07:42.400
man who has Catherine. Maybe he's his friend, his partner

07:42.400 --> 07:45.900
and I'm about to run when I see the

07:45.900 --> 07:51.300
small gun in his hand. I just want Catherine I

07:51.300 --> 07:53.960
say but I can see the hate in the man's

07:53.960 --> 07:54.200
eyes

07:54.200 --> 07:56.280
and I know that the only thing I can do

07:56.280 --> 07:58.580
now is run to the stone where I know she's

07:58.580 --> 07:58.840
tied

07:58.840 --> 08:02.320
and try to escape into the fog with her. Don't

08:02.320 --> 08:05.660
says the man as if he can see my intention

08:05.660 --> 08:06.140
in my

08:06.140 --> 08:10.020
eyes but I have to. At first I think that

08:10.020 --> 08:13.900
maybe I'm quick enough but then I hear the snap

08:13.900 --> 08:14.280
of the

08:14.280 --> 08:17.260
gun and feel the explosion in my back. For a

08:17.260 --> 08:20.060
moment more I run and I can see the shape

08:20.060 --> 08:20.640
of the stone

08:20.640 --> 08:22.940
where Catherine is tied and I fall to the floor

08:22.940 --> 08:27.160
in front of it. Catherine I shout but there is

08:27.160 --> 08:27.480
no

08:27.480 --> 08:31.520
reply. When I look to see why I see that

08:31.520 --> 08:34.700
she is not there the white ropes are still tied

08:34.700 --> 08:34.900
to

08:34.900 --> 08:39.280
the stone but she is not. Catherine I say again

08:39.280 --> 08:43.000
smiling because she's all that matters and I can

08:43.000 --> 08:46.300
rest now because I know that she is safe. You

08:46.300 --> 08:49.280
got him detective? A voice says behind me.

08:49.860 --> 08:53.860
Yeah that's him. The tall man says. He matches the

08:53.860 --> 08:56.680
girl's description perfectly. Dirty brown hair,

08:56.680 --> 09:00.160
small dark eyes and look the blood behind his ear

09:00.160 --> 09:01.720
is where she hit him before she escaped.

09:02.360 --> 09:06.460
Good for her. Yeah we think she's his third victim

09:06.460 --> 09:09.920
this year so why didn't he run? Why wait

09:09.920 --> 09:12.820
here for us? The tall man is silent for a

09:12.820 --> 09:17.380
moment. Who knows? I don't want to understand the mind

09:17.380 --> 09:17.580
of

09:17.580 --> 09:23.840
these psychopaths. I'm just happy. Catherine is okay. Catherine is

09:23.840 --> 09:26.860
okay. Catherine is okay.

09:28.600 --> 09:31.920
I do not understand anything else that they say but

09:31.920 --> 09:34.640
I do understand these three words and I

09:34.640 --> 09:44.180
smile again. Catherine is okay. Rob from the rich.

09:46.160 --> 09:51.880
The sun is high above Canary Wharf, high and hot

09:51.880 --> 09:54.700
and looking down on the crowds of people which

09:54.700 --> 09:58.140
wait on both sides of the empty road. We are

09:58.140 --> 10:01.200
standing there, the three of us in front of the

10:01.200 --> 10:01.400
bank.

10:02.300 --> 10:04.520
We are standing there in front of the glass doors

10:04.520 --> 10:14.160
and no one is looking at us. They are all

10:14.160 --> 10:17.240
that the race is starting soon. I look at our

10:17.240 --> 10:20.960
reflections. We all have the same white and orange

10:20.960 --> 10:26.920
uniforms, the same caps, the same silver sunglasses. I almost

10:26.920 --> 10:29.700
do not recognize the two men beside me

10:29.700 --> 10:32.400
and I think that from a distance people cannot see

10:32.400 --> 10:36.180
that I am a woman. Okay this is it. 10

10:36.180 --> 10:36.380
minutes

10:36.380 --> 10:41.520
exactly. Remember your jobs and remember no real names. I'm

10:41.520 --> 10:42.720
Robin, your little John,

10:43.320 --> 10:45.580
one of the men says to the other. And your

10:45.580 --> 10:49.080
Marion, he says to me, the only woman and he

10:49.080 --> 10:49.480
gives me a

10:49.480 --> 10:53.700
quick smile. Little John looks up. The camera is still

10:53.700 --> 10:56.200
in position. You cannot see us enter or leave.

10:56.980 --> 11:00.160
I feel sweat running down my neck. Here he comes.

11:00.720 --> 11:02.720
Remember the music Marion? Robin says,

11:02.720 --> 11:05.540
and then the guard is at the door, a short

11:05.540 --> 11:08.460
fat man who looks at us, smiles and then opens

11:08.460 --> 11:08.700
it

11:08.700 --> 11:12.920
without a single question. Your quick, the air conditioning only

11:12.920 --> 11:13.800
broke this morning.

11:14.520 --> 11:19.400
We know, little John says. We broke it. And the

11:19.400 --> 11:22.740
guard's smile disappears, but it's too late.

11:23.620 --> 11:26.300
Robin pushes him back into the bank and John follows

11:26.300 --> 11:27.620
with the ladders on his shoulders.

11:28.240 --> 11:31.060
I can see Robin's gun appear in his hand and

11:31.060 --> 11:33.340
then I'm inside too and I pull the door shut.

11:34.420 --> 11:39.020
Music Marion? Robin says, there is no stopping now. So

11:39.020 --> 11:40.900
I pull the small stereo from one of the

11:40.900 --> 11:44.820
black bags on my shoulder and I press play. Beethoven's

11:44.820 --> 11:47.800
piano concerto number two fills the marble

11:47.800 --> 11:51.580
stairs. We run up the stairs together, Robin with his

11:51.580 --> 11:54.000
gun at the guard's back. Then little John

11:54.000 --> 11:56.720
stops to cover the first camera. He climbs up the

11:56.720 --> 11:58.640
ladder in a second and we run into the main

11:58.640 --> 12:01.920
room of the bank. It's a large room with oak

12:01.920 --> 12:05.680
tables, a dark marble counter and expensive leather

12:05.680 --> 12:09.660
sofers. Behind the counter there are two women. Out here,

12:09.900 --> 12:12.920
now, I shout at them. To my left I see

12:12.920 --> 12:15.300
the short fat man sit down on the floor with

12:15.300 --> 12:18.320
his hands on his head. Then Robin runs to the

12:18.320 --> 12:18.560
office

12:18.560 --> 12:21.900
and kicks open the door. The two women move but

12:21.900 --> 12:24.400
slowly. One of them looks down at the counter

12:24.400 --> 12:27.520
where I know there is a secret alarm. Not if

12:27.520 --> 12:31.480
you want to live. I shout, on the sofa. I

12:31.480 --> 12:32.040
pull two

12:32.040 --> 12:35.520
blindfolds from a bag and cover their eyes. Then I

12:35.520 --> 12:37.480
tie their hands and I look at my watch.

12:38.220 --> 12:41.340
Seven minutes. I shout to little John and he covers

12:41.340 --> 12:42.760
the last camera with plastic.

12:43.640 --> 12:46.920
I take a deep breath. The music is so loud

12:46.920 --> 12:50.760
and the bank so hot. Can we do this? Can

12:50.760 --> 12:52.180
we really do this?

12:53.060 --> 12:55.520
Then Robin leaves the office and he has the manager,

12:55.940 --> 12:59.300
Mr Charles M. Hastings. Hastings.

13:00.540 --> 13:04.080
I hate the name and I hate the man. Tall,

13:04.800 --> 13:08.260
arrogant, dressed in his expensive suit with a watch that

13:08.260 --> 13:11.480
costs more than most people make in a year. What

13:11.480 --> 13:14.300
is this? He says and he looks nervous

13:14.740 --> 13:18.700
but not nervous enough. What do you think? Robin asks

13:18.700 --> 13:20.240
and he tells him to sit at one of the

13:20.240 --> 13:20.540
tables.

13:21.440 --> 13:26.180
Hastings looks around. You can't be serious. A bank robbery.

13:27.220 --> 13:28.600
And for a moment he looks surprised.

13:29.800 --> 13:34.160
But then he laughs. You idiots. This is an investment

13:34.160 --> 13:38.120
bank. There's no money here. Everything is done

13:38.120 --> 13:41.600
by transfer. And he looks at us all like we're

13:41.600 --> 13:44.800
children with that arrogant expression on his face.

13:45.600 --> 13:48.900
Good Lord. You should leave now before the police get

13:48.900 --> 13:50.660
here and maybe you can still escape.

13:51.280 --> 13:55.040
He laughs again. But I doubt it. Little John puts

13:55.040 --> 13:58.240
a blindfold on the guard. Only Hastings can see now.

13:59.020 --> 14:01.700
But we stand behind him. And for a few seconds

14:01.700 --> 14:04.080
there is only the sound of Beethoven as the music

14:04.080 --> 14:08.620
begins to reach its moto allegro. That's okay. Robin says

14:08.620 --> 14:10.720
and he picks up one of the bags and

14:10.720 --> 14:13.480
puts it on the table. We brought our own money.

14:13.760 --> 14:18.800
£20,000 in small notes. Banks are difficult to rob

14:18.800 --> 14:23.840
but houses aren't. Even big houses with alarms and safes.

14:24.580 --> 14:28.420
Like yours. What? Hastings says.

14:29.240 --> 14:33.220
And then he looks at the bag. My house. My

14:33.220 --> 14:37.780
money. You robbed my house. I can see sweat on

14:37.780 --> 14:37.960
Hastings

14:37.960 --> 14:41.460
face now. But it's on mine too. I look at

14:41.460 --> 14:46.020
my watch. Four minutes. But what do you want? You

14:46.020 --> 14:46.800
have my money.

14:49.400 --> 14:54.120
Robin laughs. We don't want it. Not that. We're not

14:54.120 --> 14:57.540
common thieves. And he throws the bag to little

14:57.540 --> 15:01.860
John. Get it ready. He says. And little John takes

15:01.860 --> 15:04.200
the ladders back down the stairs to the glass

15:04.200 --> 15:10.120
doors. Then what? shouts Hastings. And this is my part.

15:11.260 --> 15:13.580
I take the laptop from the bag and put it

15:13.580 --> 15:16.100
in front of him and open it. Do you know

15:16.100 --> 15:20.340
what this is? He looks. It's a bank account. A

15:20.340 --> 15:20.620
transfer.

15:20.620 --> 15:25.780
So? He says arrogantly. So we need you to enter

15:25.780 --> 15:28.920
your details and then transfer £240,000

15:28.920 --> 15:32.740
to this account. Do it. And then we go. And

15:32.740 --> 15:36.100
he looks more than nervous now. He looks scared.

15:36.960 --> 15:39.180
No, I can't. I don't have that sort of money.

15:39.340 --> 15:42.280
I can't. I put the newspaper down on the computer.

15:43.040 --> 15:46.340
Really? He looks at the newspaper for a moment that

15:46.340 --> 15:46.940
says nothing.

15:47.700 --> 15:53.500
One minute. Says little John. Read it. Robin shouts. Hastings

15:53.500 --> 15:55.820
is silent. But Robin points the

15:55.820 --> 16:00.160
gun at him. Read it. He shouts again. Okay. Okay.

16:00.500 --> 16:04.240
Bank manager receives £240,000 salary despite

16:04.240 --> 16:07.980
bank failure. He stops and tries to turn to look

16:07.980 --> 16:10.680
at us. But Robin pulls the trigger back on the

16:10.680 --> 16:10.880
gun.

16:11.420 --> 16:16.300
You don't understand. Hastings shouts. It's more complicated than that.

16:17.020 --> 16:20.700
We understand that hundreds of local businesses are in serious

16:20.700 --> 16:22.160
trouble because of you and this

16:22.160 --> 16:25.420
bank, I say. And you now have a decision to

16:25.420 --> 16:27.860
make because we have no time to enter the details

16:27.860 --> 16:28.340
or,

16:28.640 --> 16:32.300
I say, and I know that this is it. It

16:32.300 --> 16:36.280
has to be now. Beethoven fills the silence again.

16:36.280 --> 16:38.920
And I look at Robin and see that there's sweat

16:38.920 --> 16:41.980
on his face too. But Hastings does not move.

16:42.760 --> 16:47.260
Then goodbye, Mr Hastings. Robin says. And he moves the

16:47.260 --> 16:49.740
gun. But no, please look.

16:50.420 --> 16:54.160
And Hastings enters his details. I do not believe it.

16:54.840 --> 16:56.040
And I take the computer.

16:56.920 --> 17:02.540
Well, Robin says, it's done. It's gone. Direct. No one

17:02.540 --> 17:04.680
can trace it. Then the music stops.

17:05.260 --> 17:07.420
And I want to smile that there is no time.

17:07.860 --> 17:09.780
In the distance I hear the sound of a gun

17:09.780 --> 17:10.180
and the

17:10.180 --> 17:14.740
crowd outside cheers. Robin takes the last blindfold from the

17:14.740 --> 17:16.820
bag and puts it over Hastings' eyes.

17:17.620 --> 17:21.080
And what now? Hastings says. You think you can just

17:21.080 --> 17:23.060
walk out of here? Robin laughs.

17:23.980 --> 17:28.500
Something like that? He says quietly. The police are out

17:28.500 --> 17:30.000
there. They'll see you. They'll stop you.

17:30.000 --> 17:33.020
Robin then puts his mouth to Hastings' ear.

17:33.680 --> 17:36.680
Not if there's a big enough distraction, he says.

17:37.300 --> 17:39.220
Oh, and just to let you know, there are no

17:39.220 --> 17:40.500
bullets in any of our guns.

17:41.460 --> 17:45.140
Hastings starts to shout, but we do not listen. This

17:45.140 --> 17:47.620
is it. We have to go now.

17:48.420 --> 17:50.800
We take our uniforms off and put them in the

17:50.800 --> 17:52.780
bag. Then we're at the doors.

17:53.620 --> 17:56.140
Outside we hear the crowd cheer and we see the

17:56.140 --> 17:57.460
first runners pass by.

17:58.160 --> 18:02.740
Then there are more. Many more. Hundreds more. Thousands more.

18:03.320 --> 18:06.720
And now we start to smile because we know we're

18:06.720 --> 18:07.320
nearly out.

18:08.140 --> 18:11.800
Now says Robin. And little John presses the control on

18:11.800 --> 18:12.300
the air conditioning.

18:13.200 --> 18:16.140
For a moment there is nothing. Then the fans start.

18:17.200 --> 18:22.400
And then money fills the air outside. 20,000 pounds.

18:23.360 --> 18:25.160
It flies over the heads of the crowd

18:25.160 --> 18:28.600
into the runners and into the road. And then there

18:28.600 --> 18:30.180
is nothing but chaos.

18:31.440 --> 18:34.460
And no one sees us walk slowly from the bank.

18:35.380 --> 18:36.900
And no one remembers us later.

18:37.920 --> 18:40.000
And maybe you want to know what we plan to

18:40.000 --> 18:44.280
do with the money. Unfortunately, this I can never tell

18:44.280 --> 18:44.500
you.

18:46.640 --> 18:48.320
The lock and the monster.

18:50.400 --> 18:53.460
No darlings. She means nothing to me. Less than nothing.

18:53.800 --> 18:54.360
I hate her.

18:54.840 --> 19:01.040
It's only you, Emily. I promise. What? Devorce her. That's

19:01.040 --> 19:02.420
impossible. Why?

19:02.800 --> 19:05.660
Because of the money, the house, the cars? No, Emily,

19:05.800 --> 19:07.240
of course. You're more important than them.

19:08.060 --> 19:10.760
No, no, listen. Don't go. Listen to me. When I

19:10.760 --> 19:13.040
return to London, everything is going to be different.

19:13.980 --> 19:17.020
I have a plan, darling. Darling, I have a plan.

19:17.700 --> 19:18.140
Emily?

19:19.040 --> 19:22.600
But there is no answer. And Oliver Stern puts his

19:22.600 --> 19:25.560
mobile back into his coat pocket and looks around.

19:26.420 --> 19:29.380
There is no one near to him to hear. He

19:29.380 --> 19:30.440
is alone on the jetty.

19:30.980 --> 19:33.320
Apart from the boat attendant at his chair 20 meters

19:33.320 --> 19:35.660
away, his feet on a boat and a cigarette in

19:35.660 --> 19:36.040
his mouth.

19:36.800 --> 19:40.680
And he cannot hear from there. Oliver is sure. But

19:40.680 --> 19:43.340
just to be safe, he decides not to phone Emily

19:43.340 --> 19:43.860
again.

19:44.740 --> 19:46.860
Perhaps the less she knows the better.

19:48.280 --> 19:54.160
A plan. Yes. He has a plan. A good plan.

19:55.120 --> 19:56.040
And a simple plan.

19:56.960 --> 20:00.880
He looks out across the horrible grey lock. The sun

20:00.880 --> 20:03.840
is almost down behind the green snowy mountains

20:03.840 --> 20:09.400
now. And it's colder than before. What sort of person

20:09.400 --> 20:11.480
wants to have a holiday in this remote,

20:11.480 --> 20:15.340
ugly part of the world? Then he hears the sound

20:15.340 --> 20:18.040
of his wife's laughter from the terrace bar of the

20:18.040 --> 20:22.320
hotel. And he shakes his head. The sort of person

20:22.320 --> 20:26.060
like my monster of a wife. He tries to picture

20:26.060 --> 20:30.240
Emily. Her eyes are so loving, her laugh so light

20:30.240 --> 20:33.020
and pretty. But when his wife laughs,

20:33.520 --> 20:36.600
she sounds like a donkey. He looks at the lock

20:36.600 --> 20:39.200
again at the jetty and the small boats waiting

20:39.200 --> 20:42.480
there for the tourists in the hotel. And he asks

20:42.480 --> 20:45.140
himself once more if he can do it.

20:48.480 --> 20:53.640
She bays again. And he knows that he can. It's

20:53.640 --> 20:57.120
10 to 6 now. The boats stop going out at

20:57.120 --> 20:57.360
6.

20:58.080 --> 21:01.220
And the sun is almost gone. She needs to come

21:01.220 --> 21:03.920
now, he knows, but he cannot shout for her.

21:04.420 --> 21:07.820
No, it's her idea to go on a boat. Everyone

21:07.820 --> 21:09.640
in the bar knows she wants to go.

21:10.100 --> 21:12.500
I just need to wait for her, like a good

21:12.500 --> 21:16.480
husband, he thinks. The type of husband who is happy

21:16.480 --> 21:16.980
to go

21:16.980 --> 21:20.120
out on the huge, horrible lock in the dark with

21:20.120 --> 21:23.580
his monster of a wife. But can she still swim?

21:24.480 --> 21:27.800
He's not sure. He thinks that with her clothes and

21:27.800 --> 21:30.080
her coat on, she'll be too heavy and that the

21:30.080 --> 21:33.160
cold grey water of the lock will pull her down.

21:33.960 --> 21:34.840
But is that enough?

21:35.840 --> 21:38.840
He looks at the bag by his feet, the romantic

21:38.840 --> 21:42.960
picnic, filled with all the food his wife loves

21:43.740 --> 21:46.440
and the bottle of champagne that he knows she cannot

21:46.440 --> 21:50.920
resist. Oliver smiles. It is a heavy bag.

21:51.760 --> 21:53.920
All he has to do is make her hold it

21:53.920 --> 21:57.620
for a second, perhaps quickly wrap the straps around her

21:57.620 --> 21:57.960
hands.

21:58.680 --> 22:04.660
Then, no more monster. But it's nearly six now. The

22:04.660 --> 22:06.580
attendant is about to finish for the night.

22:07.160 --> 22:11.440
Excuse me? Oliver shouts with a smile. He pulls his

22:11.440 --> 22:13.680
cigarette packet from his pocket and walks over.

22:14.420 --> 22:16.180
Sorry to bother you, but do you have a lighter?

22:17.080 --> 22:20.900
The attendant has a hard face and fierce red hair.

22:21.520 --> 22:25.320
He looks at Oliver for a moment. Nods pulls his

22:25.320 --> 22:27.240
lighter from his pocket and offers it.

22:27.960 --> 22:31.120
Look, continues, Oliver. My wife wants to take a boat

22:31.120 --> 22:32.500
out. She's going to be here in a second.

22:33.320 --> 22:36.640
The man looks at the sky. A boat, man. We

22:36.640 --> 22:37.420
want a boat.

22:38.380 --> 22:43.040
Dinner, can I boot that? Better than Marla. The idiot

22:43.040 --> 22:45.840
does not speak English. All of the things.

22:46.740 --> 22:51.160
Bloody country. I'm sorry. I don't understand. I'm from England.

22:52.100 --> 22:54.960
The man laughs, stands up and says

22:54.960 --> 22:58.740
nothing. Oliver tries to stay calm, but he knows there's

22:58.740 --> 22:59.660
too little time.

23:00.440 --> 23:02.980
Don't you speak English? My wife wants to go out

23:02.980 --> 23:04.860
now. She's only going to be one minute.

23:05.440 --> 23:08.240
He shouts and the attendant stops and gives him a

23:08.240 --> 23:11.400
long, hard look with his cold blue eyes.

23:12.100 --> 23:16.700
Oliver, here I am. A loud, cheerful voice says. And

23:16.700 --> 23:20.220
the two men turn to see Mrs. Sylvia Stern.

23:20.960 --> 23:25.520
She smiles that stupid cow-like smile at them. And

23:25.520 --> 23:28.340
Oliver sees the idiot attendant smile back.

23:29.040 --> 23:32.300
She is dressed in a horrible tartan skirt and woolen

23:32.300 --> 23:35.360
jumper. And in her arms she has the heavy

23:35.360 --> 23:41.600
wax coat. Good. Oliver thinks. Darling, he says with a

23:41.600 --> 23:44.900
smile. This good man wants to close. I think

23:44.900 --> 23:48.100
we must wait until tomorrow now. Oh, no, surely not.

23:48.560 --> 23:50.440
She turns to the man and smiles again.

23:51.000 --> 23:52.940
Can't we just go out for a few minutes, please?

23:53.660 --> 23:54.760
Just to enjoy the sunset.

23:55.660 --> 23:58.860
And the attendant ignores Oliver, but returns her smile.

23:59.780 --> 24:03.220
Aye. Well, just for a 10 minutes then. Oh, thank

24:03.220 --> 24:06.400
you, Sylvia says. And the attendant helps them

24:06.400 --> 24:09.500
into the small rowing boat and passes Oliver the picnic

24:09.500 --> 24:12.200
bag. He then gives him another long,

24:12.200 --> 24:15.220
hard look. But Oliver does not care.

24:16.300 --> 24:20.180
Bloody idiot. He says to Sylvia as they slowly move

24:20.180 --> 24:22.220
away from the jetty onto the dark water.

24:22.960 --> 24:26.040
I don't understand a thing, he says. But Sylvia does

24:26.040 --> 24:28.940
not seem to hear. And instead looks out

24:28.940 --> 24:34.300
at the dark lock. For five minutes, Oliver rose. And

24:34.300 --> 24:37.040
soon the jetty and the hotel look much smaller.

24:37.040 --> 24:40.520
While the attendant is almost impossible to see in the

24:40.520 --> 24:41.960
half light of the new evening.

24:43.200 --> 24:47.660
And so this is it. Oliver thinks about loving ironic

24:47.660 --> 24:50.880
Emily again. Then he looks at his monster

24:50.880 --> 24:55.040
of a wife. Oh yes, this has to be it.

24:55.780 --> 24:59.240
No more listening to that awful laugh. No more looking

24:59.240 --> 25:03.840
at her boring face. And perhaps more importantly, no more

25:03.840 --> 25:05.700
sharing his bank account with her.

25:06.460 --> 25:10.420
Darling, he says, shall we have a little drink? Oh

25:10.420 --> 25:11.480
yes, that would be very nice.

25:12.040 --> 25:14.400
She smiles, but in the half light Oliver thinks he

25:14.400 --> 25:16.700
sees something strange in her expression.

25:17.500 --> 25:19.180
Can you pass me over the bag? Then you can

25:19.180 --> 25:21.460
come and sit here next to me. He says as

25:21.460 --> 25:21.920
casually

25:21.920 --> 25:25.740
as he can. Of course. Sylvia says and she stands

25:25.740 --> 25:29.540
up. Which makes the boat rock. Oliver thinks

25:29.540 --> 25:32.960
that this is going to be very easy indeed. Just

25:32.960 --> 25:35.880
one push. And then he can shout for the attendant

25:35.880 --> 25:38.880
and pretend to help but really just watch the monster

25:38.880 --> 25:42.480
go down into the lock. Just one look back

25:42.480 --> 25:44.660
at the jetty to be sure no one can see,

25:45.160 --> 25:48.700
he thinks. And he turns his head. And then it

25:48.700 --> 25:49.120
happens.

25:50.120 --> 25:53.120
Pain explodes at the back of his head and his

25:53.120 --> 25:56.040
eyes go dark. For a second he does not know

25:56.040 --> 25:56.440
where he

25:56.440 --> 26:00.080
is. Then he feels hands on him. Pushing him and

26:00.080 --> 26:02.600
moving him. As he tries to say something,

26:02.700 --> 26:05.880
he sees the broken champagne bottle at his feet. Then

26:05.880 --> 26:08.960
he falls from the boat. And the ice cold water

26:08.960 --> 26:12.640
takes the words and the air from his mouth. For

26:12.640 --> 26:15.080
a moment he goes down, but then he kicks his

26:15.080 --> 26:15.340
legs

26:15.340 --> 26:17.540
and he comes to the surface and looks up at

26:17.540 --> 26:20.080
Sylvia in the boat. She has an oar in her

26:20.080 --> 26:20.560
hands and

26:20.560 --> 26:23.700
she's reaching it out to him. Yes, closer, help me.

26:24.120 --> 26:26.740
He shouts and it's then that he sees the strange

26:26.740 --> 26:32.140
expression in her face again. Sylvia, darling, don't you dare

26:32.140 --> 26:34.780
call me that. She says in a tone

26:34.780 --> 26:39.360
as cold as the water. You're a cheating, lying, horrible

26:39.360 --> 26:41.880
monster of a man. You can call that stupid

26:41.880 --> 26:46.060
girl of yours, darling, but not me. Never again, Oliver

26:46.060 --> 26:50.020
Stern, never again. And then the oar hits him

26:50.020 --> 26:52.820
on the head and he cannot think and he cannot

26:52.820 --> 26:57.020
swim and the water takes him. For a few moments

26:57.020 --> 27:01.680
he sinks slowly into the great lock. But then somehow,

27:02.380 --> 27:05.580
miraculously, he kicks again and he comes

27:05.580 --> 27:09.440
to the surface once more. Sylvia and the boat are

27:09.440 --> 27:13.340
gone. And the half light is complete darkness now.

27:14.040 --> 27:17.620
He tries to swim, but his clothes and his coat

27:17.620 --> 27:22.240
are too heavy. The jetty, the attendant. He has

27:22.240 --> 27:24.120
to still be there. If he hears me, he can

27:24.120 --> 27:27.820
bring a boat out. Help me. He shouts into the

27:27.820 --> 27:28.060
darkness.

27:28.740 --> 27:33.240
Help me. For the love of God, help me. And

27:33.240 --> 27:35.460
on the small jetty on the bank of Loch Ness,

27:35.960 --> 27:39.100
the attendant hears. He takes the cigarette from his mouth

27:39.100 --> 27:39.600
and smiles.

27:40.480 --> 27:45.260
Sorry, ladie. He says quietly to the lock. I can't

27:45.260 --> 27:47.060
understand the word you're seeing.

27:49.700 --> 27:50.820
Follow me.

27:53.400 --> 27:59.680
Follow me. Says Detective Branwell with a sigh. His shift

27:59.680 --> 28:01.300
finishes in five minutes,

28:01.300 --> 28:04.460
but there's no one around in Howarth's quiet police station.

28:05.240 --> 28:06.940
And so he leads the woman to the

28:06.940 --> 28:09.960
first interview room and tries to suppress the image of

28:09.960 --> 28:12.000
a pint of beer in the black bull pub.

28:12.920 --> 28:16.420
The interview room is cold, the light's weak and gray.

28:17.380 --> 28:19.380
But he offers the woman a seat and hopes

28:19.380 --> 28:22.780
that this will be quick. As she takes her coat

28:22.780 --> 28:27.320
off, Branwell watches her. She has long brown hair

28:27.320 --> 28:30.880
that right now looks a little untidy. And she has

28:30.880 --> 28:34.300
deep green eyes that at the moment are tired and

28:34.300 --> 28:38.080
nervous and shows something which he does not completely recognize.

28:39.000 --> 28:44.260
Right, he says, and tries to smile to relax her.

28:45.160 --> 28:46.680
What's all this about then?

28:47.480 --> 28:49.660
The officer at the front desk says you need to

28:49.660 --> 28:50.360
speak to someone.

28:51.160 --> 28:55.920
I do, she says, and her voice is thin and

28:55.920 --> 29:00.940
tense. About what? She waits for a moment, uncertain,

29:00.940 --> 29:06.140
and then she takes a breath. About a crime. Branwell

29:06.140 --> 29:08.620
pulls his notepad from his pocket and places

29:08.620 --> 29:11.380
it in front of him on the table. He has

29:11.380 --> 29:13.860
a bad feeling about his pint in the black bull

29:13.860 --> 29:14.100
pub.

29:15.260 --> 29:19.340
I see, he says. Maybe you can tell me your

29:19.340 --> 29:21.660
name first. You're addressed too.

29:22.860 --> 29:25.360
She puts her hands on the table and he sees

29:25.360 --> 29:27.940
that her red fingernails are chipped and bitten.

29:29.120 --> 29:33.540
Jane Thornton, I live at brow top cottage. Brow top?

29:34.220 --> 29:37.120
Oh yes, I remember. You have that little red

29:37.120 --> 29:41.580
sports card, don't you? Not now, no. She says and

29:41.580 --> 29:46.060
she picks up her handbag. Can I smoke? No, sorry

29:46.060 --> 29:49.660
love, rules and regulations. I can get you a tea

29:49.660 --> 29:52.420
if you like. But she shakes her head and puts

29:52.420 --> 29:52.620
the

29:52.620 --> 29:55.640
bag at her feet. And maybe you can tell me

29:55.640 --> 29:59.840
why you're here, he suggests. Again, she waits.

30:00.920 --> 30:04.180
And again, Branwell thinks that he sees something in her

30:04.180 --> 30:05.300
deep green eyes.

30:06.320 --> 30:10.340
There's a man who follows me. She begins. Every evening.

30:10.980 --> 30:13.560
Every evening when I return home from work.

30:14.800 --> 30:22.700
Branwell nods. I see. No, you don't. Every evening. Every

30:22.700 --> 30:26.340
single evening. For almost a year now,

30:26.780 --> 30:30.660
he's always there detective. Sometimes he's so close that I

30:30.660 --> 30:31.980
think he can touch me and other

30:31.980 --> 30:35.680
times he's far away. But I still know that he's

30:35.680 --> 30:40.060
there. And detective, you might think that I'm crazy,

30:40.060 --> 30:45.920
but I know what this man wants. What? Branwell says.

30:46.640 --> 30:47.760
What does he want?

30:48.680 --> 30:51.360
She pauses for a second and he sees her hands

30:51.360 --> 30:53.720
shake. He wants to kill me.

30:54.560 --> 30:59.580
Branwell says nothing but watches the woman's face. She is

30:59.580 --> 31:03.380
scared. Very scared. Does he speak

31:03.380 --> 31:07.740
to you, this man? No, never. And when I try

31:07.740 --> 31:09.300
to speak to him, me...

31:09.840 --> 31:15.340
Yes? He disappears. Branwell opens his notebook and takes his

31:15.340 --> 31:15.800
pen out.

31:16.600 --> 31:22.260
Where do you work, Mrs. Thorne? Miss Thorne. I work

31:22.260 --> 31:25.440
in Leeds. I have a small media company.

31:26.380 --> 31:30.320
In Leeds. Then where does this man follow you from?

31:31.200 --> 31:34.380
From the station at Keithley. You work in Leeds,

31:34.660 --> 31:37.980
but you don't drive. I think your sports car can

31:37.980 --> 31:40.020
get you there a lot faster than the bus to

31:40.020 --> 31:40.480
Keithley

31:40.480 --> 31:43.580
and then the train to Leeds. I told you, I

31:43.580 --> 31:48.040
don't drive it. Not now. Right. So he followed you.

31:48.900 --> 31:52.200
From Keithley. I see him at the train station sometimes.

31:53.020 --> 31:55.580
Then he's there again when I get off the bus

31:55.580 --> 31:57.600
in the town centre here in Arworth.

31:58.320 --> 32:01.560
And then he follows me to my cottage. You walk

32:01.560 --> 32:04.820
from here to brow top, up over the moors road,

32:05.460 --> 32:09.740
every evening. That's a dangerous road. And it must be

32:09.740 --> 32:11.280
more than three miles.

32:12.540 --> 32:16.300
Dangerous, yes. But she does not say anything else and

32:16.300 --> 32:17.200
Branwell continues.

32:18.100 --> 32:19.780
Can you describe the man?

32:20.720 --> 32:25.620
Easily, she says. But again she pauses and Branwell sees

32:25.620 --> 32:27.860
her turn quickly to look over her shoulder.

32:28.740 --> 32:32.300
His tall with dark hair, his skin is pale and

32:32.300 --> 32:33.200
his eyes cold.

32:34.060 --> 32:39.240
Dead, she says. He has dead eyes. And they watch

32:39.240 --> 32:41.740
me every day and I think that they watch me

32:41.740 --> 32:42.540
at night too.

32:43.940 --> 32:48.080
Branwell feels a shiver run over his back. You think

32:48.080 --> 32:49.980
that this man enters your premises.

32:51.180 --> 32:54.900
That he enters your cottage during the night. I do.

32:55.760 --> 32:58.180
Sometimes I wake and I know that he's there.

32:58.900 --> 33:00.680
I turn on the lights and I see nothing but

33:00.680 --> 33:03.120
when I go to the windows I can see him

33:03.120 --> 33:03.640
in the field.

33:04.520 --> 33:07.860
He stands there like a scarecrow in the dark and

33:07.860 --> 33:10.460
he accuses me every day.

33:11.340 --> 33:16.060
His cold dead eyes accuse me. Branwell shakes his head.

33:16.780 --> 33:19.900
Is she crazy or just terrified?

33:21.280 --> 33:25.840
Miss Thorne, if this man enters your house we can

33:25.840 --> 33:29.500
arrest him. But to do that we need evidence.

33:30.660 --> 33:33.840
As he broke in a window or entered the property

33:33.840 --> 33:38.240
by force she lets out a laugh, a laugh that

33:38.240 --> 33:38.380
is

33:38.380 --> 33:44.900
horrible to Branwell. No. Of course not. There's nothing. And

33:44.900 --> 33:46.420
he never says anything threatening.

33:47.000 --> 33:49.820
He never says that he wants to hurt you. She

33:49.820 --> 33:52.020
looks over her shoulder again quickly and

33:52.020 --> 33:54.740
automatically as if she does it a hundred times a

33:54.740 --> 33:57.420
day. No. He never says a thing.

33:58.720 --> 34:03.400
But I know. I know what he wants. I know

34:03.400 --> 34:05.880
what he wants. And she begins to cry.

34:06.820 --> 34:11.240
Branwell puts the notepad away. I'm sorry Miss Thorne but

34:11.240 --> 34:12.920
there's very little that we can do.

34:13.660 --> 34:15.540
Let me make you that tea. A nice tea to

34:15.540 --> 34:17.900
calm you down. Let me can start again and see

34:17.900 --> 34:18.220
if there

34:18.220 --> 34:21.720
are any other details. She seems to nod and he

34:21.720 --> 34:24.960
stands up and goes to the door. We need a

34:24.960 --> 34:25.220
better

34:25.220 --> 34:27.800
description you see if we want to identify the man.

34:28.360 --> 34:31.360
What? She says before he can open the door.

34:32.040 --> 34:34.560
Oh no no. You don't understand the detective. I know

34:34.560 --> 34:36.800
who the man is. I know his name. I know

34:36.800 --> 34:42.740
everything. Branwell stops. You mean? She continues. And if I

34:42.740 --> 34:44.480
tell you his name you can help me.

34:45.020 --> 34:49.700
You can stop this. She says desperately. You know his

34:49.700 --> 34:52.860
name. Do you promise? You can stop it.

34:53.660 --> 34:57.260
Branwell does not sit. He sees that expression in her

34:57.260 --> 35:00.240
eyes again. I can't promise love. No.

35:00.240 --> 35:03.940
But I can try. She nods and bites her red

35:03.940 --> 35:08.100
fingernails for a moment. His name is William Gray.

35:09.200 --> 35:16.320
William Gray. Branwell knows the name. William Gray. And he

35:16.320 --> 35:18.400
remembers something horrible from

35:18.400 --> 35:21.640
more than a year ago. An accident on the roads

35:21.640 --> 35:26.400
across the moors. William Gray. A local cyclist

35:26.400 --> 35:32.060
and a good man. William Gray. Miss Thornton. William Gray

35:32.060 --> 35:35.200
is dead. He was it by a car last year

35:35.200 --> 35:38.740
while he cycled across brow top road. We never found

35:38.740 --> 35:41.520
the driver but William died instantly they say.

35:42.240 --> 35:45.620
Oh I know. She says and he sees that something

35:45.620 --> 35:48.900
in her deep green eyes. And he thinks that he

35:48.900 --> 35:49.120
knows

35:49.120 --> 35:53.460
what it is now. I know detective because I am

35:53.460 --> 35:56.820
that driver. Then there is only the sound of

35:56.820 --> 36:00.860
her crying to fill the cold interview room. And Branwell

36:00.860 --> 36:03.240
sits down again and picks up his pen and

36:03.240 --> 36:08.160
notepad. I think you should tell me everything. He says

36:08.160 --> 36:10.660
and he can see clearly now the guilt

36:10.660 --> 36:15.780
that fills her deep green eyes. An hour later Branwell

36:15.780 --> 36:17.760
closes the door of the interview room

36:17.760 --> 36:21.820
and sighs. He does not feel any sympathy for her.

36:22.260 --> 36:24.840
He cannot. Not for someone who can do that.

36:25.940 --> 36:29.860
To leave someone on the gray moors to die. No

36:29.860 --> 36:33.180
he cannot feel any sympathy for her. But maybe

36:33.180 --> 36:37.620
now she can find some rest. Maybe now she can

36:37.620 --> 36:39.880
forget the ghost of William Gray.

36:41.020 --> 36:43.800
He walks up the corridor to the front desk and

36:43.800 --> 36:45.980
is about to shout for an officer when he sees

36:45.980 --> 36:46.280
the

36:46.280 --> 36:49.200
tall figure standing at the door of the police station.

36:50.140 --> 36:53.820
He stops. His heart suddenly beating faster.

36:55.960 --> 36:59.000
The man's dark hair is wet from the rain outside.

37:00.340 --> 37:03.220
His skin pale and his eyes cold and dead.

37:04.100 --> 37:09.480
It's him. Branwell knows it. But he cannot believe it.

37:10.780 --> 37:16.780
Do you have her confession? The figure says. What? Do

37:16.780 --> 37:18.320
you have Miss Thornton's confession?

37:19.280 --> 37:25.000
The figure repeats. Branwell nods. Yes I do. She's in

37:25.000 --> 37:27.720
the interview room now. The figure nods.

37:28.480 --> 37:34.340
Good. Then it's over. And the impossible figure turns to

37:34.340 --> 37:34.540
leave.

37:36.080 --> 37:40.340
Branwell still cannot believe it. Yet the similarity is perfect.

37:41.340 --> 37:44.520
Wait Mr. Gray. William, wait. I need to ask you.

37:45.100 --> 37:49.400
But the figure turns and smiles. It's a cold smile

37:49.400 --> 37:52.620
but Branwell sees that the man's eyes look a little

37:52.620 --> 37:57.800
more alive now. My name is Gray Detective but not

37:57.800 --> 38:02.640
William. My name is Matthew. Matthew Gray.

38:03.280 --> 38:08.000
William was my brother. He says as he opens the

38:08.000 --> 38:11.080
door to the rain. My twin brother.

38:15.640 --> 38:22.200
How far is far enough? Jerry pushes open the door

38:22.200 --> 38:25.820
of the small Australian pub and steps onto the

38:25.820 --> 38:28.340
terrace with a pint of cold beer in his hand.

38:29.520 --> 38:32.660
Inside the pub it's small and dark and the

38:32.660 --> 38:36.180
barman is rude and suspicious but Jerry has to agree

38:36.180 --> 38:38.680
that the view from the terrace is more than

38:38.680 --> 38:45.100
spectacular. Red sandy plains stretch out in almost every direction

38:45.100 --> 38:55.800
and only to the east are their

38:55.800 --> 38:58.940
down at one of the small wooden tables and places

38:58.940 --> 39:01.260
his bag carefully next to his feet.

39:02.320 --> 39:04.820
The rest of his luggage is in the pickup truck

39:04.820 --> 39:10.840
but not this bag. No. This one stays with him.

39:12.060 --> 39:14.900
He takes a cigarette from his packet, lights it and

39:14.900 --> 39:18.180
lets the hot evening sun shine down on his

39:18.180 --> 39:24.320
bald head. The outback. This is it. This is far

39:24.320 --> 39:28.200
enough. And for the first time in a week Jerry

39:28.200 --> 39:34.100
relaxes and lets his anxious pale face smile. You do

39:34.100 --> 39:37.480
not steal from Big Jones and stay in London.

39:38.460 --> 39:44.060
Everybody knows that and Jerry understands better than most people

39:44.060 --> 39:46.140
exactly how true that is.

39:46.860 --> 39:50.380
No. You either get out of the city for life

39:50.380 --> 39:55.700
or Big Jones finds you. And when Big Jones finds

39:55.700 --> 39:56.060
you,

39:56.400 --> 40:00.060
that is when you go see the world. In little

40:00.060 --> 40:04.300
pieces. Most people think it's just a story

40:04.960 --> 40:09.860
but not Jerry. No. Big Jones does not just kill

40:09.860 --> 40:13.500
you. He takes you to one of his old factories

40:13.500 --> 40:13.940
on

40:13.940 --> 40:16.900
the Thames and then he shows you the boxes and

40:16.900 --> 40:19.480
the addresses of all the different locations in

40:19.480 --> 40:24.680
the world. And then he starts to chop. Jerry feels

40:24.680 --> 40:28.980
sweat run down his back. But he laughs and takes

40:28.980 --> 40:33.360
a long drink of the cold beer. Well, Big Jones

40:33.360 --> 40:37.280
cannot chop me up if he cannot find me, he

40:37.280 --> 40:37.520
thinks.

40:38.120 --> 40:41.500
And he looks at the bag at his feet. It

40:41.500 --> 40:43.200
was easy to get it through customs.

40:44.440 --> 40:48.280
They look for drugs and weapons. They do not look

40:48.280 --> 40:51.460
for 60,000 pounds of uncut diamonds.

40:52.620 --> 40:55.720
And he smiles and looks up at the hot sun.

40:56.760 --> 40:58.960
Well, someone looks bloody happy.

41:00.040 --> 41:04.700
A voice says and Jerry jumps. He looks forwards but

41:04.700 --> 41:06.520
cannot see because of the sunlight.

41:07.520 --> 41:11.420
Then two tall, strangely dressed men walk into the shade

41:11.420 --> 41:12.140
of the terrace.

41:12.940 --> 41:15.880
One with three dead rabbits in one hand and a

41:15.880 --> 41:17.060
long rifle in the other.

41:18.200 --> 41:24.080
G'day! says the other one. They both look similar. Messy

41:24.080 --> 41:26.880
blonde hair and a hat that are the same

41:26.880 --> 41:31.260
color as their khaki shorts and shirts. And they are

41:31.260 --> 41:35.260
both dirty. Their skin, boots and clothes

41:35.260 --> 41:37.260
all covered in red sand.

41:38.340 --> 41:40.420
Even him? Jerry says.

41:41.360 --> 41:44.860
Huh, a bloody palm. Says the first and drops the

41:44.860 --> 41:45.780
rabbits on the table.

41:46.540 --> 41:48.140
Is that right? Are you a palm mate?

41:48.780 --> 41:50.340
A what? asks Jerry.

41:51.140 --> 41:53.780
A palm. You know, an English bloke.

41:54.360 --> 41:55.760
Oh, yes.

41:56.800 --> 42:00.720
Nice one. Says the first before he disappears into the

42:00.720 --> 42:00.940
bar.

42:01.580 --> 42:04.480
Jerry is not sure but he thinks that the man

42:04.480 --> 42:06.260
looked at the bag by his feet.

42:07.060 --> 42:10.180
Are you on holiday, mate? asks the other who sits

42:10.180 --> 42:11.080
down at the table.

42:11.800 --> 42:13.720
Yeah. Something like that.

42:14.460 --> 42:17.640
Yeah? Where are you staying? There are no hotels around

42:17.640 --> 42:17.980
here.

42:18.960 --> 42:23.120
Jerry considers lying. But Big Jones can never find him

42:23.120 --> 42:23.420
here.

42:24.260 --> 42:28.700
Upper of Farmer Hobbes Creek. Oh, is that right? Me

42:28.700 --> 42:29.920
and Darwin live near there.

42:29.920 --> 42:34.460
It looks like we're neighbors. Darwin? Yeah, my bloody brother.

42:35.080 --> 42:37.840
I'm Charles. He's Darwin. Here he is with the stubby's.

42:38.520 --> 42:41.000
And the brother called Darwin comes out of the bar

42:41.000 --> 42:42.920
with two small bottles of beer.

42:43.880 --> 42:46.400
The palm is staying at the old Hobbes farm, Darwin.

42:47.280 --> 42:50.100
Well, you're no worse then. Be careful up there, mate.

42:50.320 --> 42:51.640
That's salty territory now.

42:52.520 --> 42:56.900
And both of the brothers smile. Salty territory? What's that?

42:57.800 --> 43:01.020
Crocs, mate. Crocodiles. There are a lot of them up

43:01.020 --> 43:02.600
there in the creek. Best be careful.

43:03.520 --> 43:05.740
And they laugh again. And Jerry smiles.

43:06.860 --> 43:10.740
Yeah, sure. I'll be careful. He says and he thinks

43:10.740 --> 43:12.600
he sees one of the brothers look at his bag

43:12.600 --> 43:12.980
again.

43:13.960 --> 43:15.760
Well, it's nice to meet you both but I need

43:15.760 --> 43:17.380
to get up to the farm before dark.

43:18.280 --> 43:20.960
Sure, mate. No worries. Says Charles.

43:22.000 --> 43:24.540
Watch out for the salties, mate. They can chop you

43:24.540 --> 43:25.660
up into little pieces.

43:26.490 --> 43:29.660
Says Darwin and Jerry thinks about big Jones and the

43:29.660 --> 43:31.040
old factory on the Thames.

43:31.980 --> 43:35.160
I'll be okay. See you later. He says to the

43:35.160 --> 43:36.960
brothers, then he heads for the truck.

43:38.120 --> 43:42.940
A bloody palm. Says Charlie quietly. He seems to like

43:42.940 --> 43:44.140
that bag very much.

43:44.780 --> 43:48.580
Says Darwin. He sure does. You know, I don't think

43:48.580 --> 43:50.340
he believes us about the salties.

43:51.060 --> 43:53.800
Bloody palms never believe us about the salties.

43:54.760 --> 43:57.480
And the brothers laugh as they watch Jerry and the

43:57.480 --> 43:59.880
truck drive up the road to Hobbes Creek

43:59.880 --> 44:04.000
while the great Australian sun begins to fall behind the

44:04.000 --> 44:04.340
horizon.

44:05.660 --> 44:10.280
It's almost dark when Jerry reaches the farm. The building

44:10.280 --> 44:12.220
is old but in okay shape.

44:13.340 --> 44:15.840
And he turns the generator on and the electric lights

44:15.840 --> 44:19.280
start. For half an hour he unpacks his

44:19.280 --> 44:22.540
things. Then he sits down on the terrace with his

44:22.540 --> 44:24.900
bag at his feet and lights another cigarette.

44:26.260 --> 44:29.660
The creek is 20 meters from the farmhouse and the

44:29.660 --> 44:32.660
evening seems to be alive with insects and

44:32.660 --> 44:35.300
birds that live in the trees near the green water.

44:36.520 --> 44:41.080
Salties, he thinks, and he laughs. He does not

44:41.080 --> 44:44.940
believe the brothers, not for a moment. But just to

44:44.940 --> 44:47.780
be safe he pulls his new gun from the bag

44:47.780 --> 44:48.080
and

44:48.080 --> 44:51.520
checks it. Then he pulls a box from the bag,

44:52.040 --> 44:54.720
opens it carefully and looks at the diamonds.

44:55.860 --> 45:02.800
Beautiful, he thinks. Beautiful. And they belong to me. And

45:02.800 --> 45:04.400
he is about to laugh again

45:05.060 --> 45:09.380
when he hears a noise from the trees. The box

45:09.380 --> 45:12.700
shuts in an instant and then the gun is in

45:12.700 --> 45:13.120
his hand.

45:13.120 --> 45:17.720
He thinks he sees a dark shape but he does

45:17.720 --> 45:18.280
not shoot.

45:19.200 --> 45:24.160
Who's there? He says. But there is no answer. He

45:24.160 --> 45:26.600
picks the bag up and puts it on his shoulder.

45:27.540 --> 45:31.200
He takes a few steps towards the trees. I've got

45:31.200 --> 45:33.480
a gun. But there is silence.

45:34.800 --> 45:38.260
He tries to see what the dark shape is but

45:38.260 --> 45:41.900
the evening light is too weak. He moves a little

45:41.900 --> 45:42.380
closer.

45:43.120 --> 45:47.740
Maybe it's the brothers, he thinks. And he remembers the

45:47.740 --> 45:49.360
way one of them looked at the bag.

45:50.200 --> 45:53.900
Maybe they want to steal his bag. Well, they can

45:53.900 --> 45:57.660
try. He raises his gun and he's about to shoot

45:57.660 --> 46:02.980
when the dark shape moves again. And he laughs. It's

46:02.980 --> 46:06.520
just a small crocodile. A tiny thing.

46:07.340 --> 46:10.800
No bigger than his arm. He looks at it and

46:10.800 --> 46:11.620
laughs again.

46:12.460 --> 46:15.060
Well, you can't chop me in a little piece, can

46:15.060 --> 46:17.360
you? He says to the crocodile.

46:18.040 --> 46:20.760
And that is when he feels the knife at his

46:20.760 --> 46:21.040
neck.

46:21.780 --> 46:27.280
No, says a terrifyingly familiar voice. But I can, Jerry.

46:28.140 --> 46:31.260
Drop the gun. Jerry drops it and slowly

46:31.260 --> 46:34.020
turns. The knife still at his neck.

46:34.840 --> 46:41.560
Big Jones. But ow. Big Jones smiles. He is tall

46:41.560 --> 46:43.320
and extremely muscly.

46:44.060 --> 46:47.140
His face is bearded and his eyes are full of

46:47.140 --> 46:51.280
violence and pain. But it's his teeth, Jerry hates.

46:52.240 --> 46:58.220
Big white teeth as sharp as crocodiles. Ow. Do you

46:58.220 --> 47:00.440
think you can steal from me an escape?

47:01.260 --> 47:06.240
Jerry, you know me better than that. Please, Big Jones,

47:06.520 --> 47:07.980
I'm sorry. I have all the diamonds

47:07.980 --> 47:11.260
right here. Can't you let me go? You won't ever

47:11.260 --> 47:13.900
see me again, I promise. Jerry begs.

47:14.800 --> 47:18.020
I know I won't, Jerry. Because you're going to go

47:18.020 --> 47:21.020
on a little trip. All around the world.

47:21.960 --> 47:25.180
And Jerry remembers the old factory on the Thames and

47:25.180 --> 47:27.340
the boxes with the different addresses and

47:27.340 --> 47:30.540
the story about what Big Jones does when people steal

47:30.540 --> 47:31.200
from him.

47:32.240 --> 47:36.380
And Jerry opens his mouth to scream. But the screen

47:36.380 --> 47:38.480
he hears is not his own.

47:39.320 --> 47:43.280
The scream comes from Big Jones, who suddenly lets go

47:43.280 --> 47:46.360
of the knife. Jerry looks down and sees

47:46.360 --> 47:52.220
the small crocodile biting Big Jones's leg. Ha! Jerry laughs

47:52.220 --> 47:54.190
and he runs to his gun and

47:54.190 --> 47:56.770
points it at Big Jones, who falls to the floor

47:56.770 --> 47:58.590
and tries to kick the crocodile.

47:59.270 --> 48:02.050
Don't move, Big Jones. Let it chop you in a

48:02.050 --> 48:02.650
little pieces.

48:03.690 --> 48:05.850
And Big Jones looks up at him and is about

48:05.850 --> 48:08.690
to shout when suddenly he looks behind Jerry

48:08.690 --> 48:13.770
and the color disappears from his face. What? Says Jerry.

48:14.650 --> 48:17.010
And this is the last thing he ever says.

48:17.890 --> 48:22.410
Jerry's gun fires three times into the evening light and

48:22.410 --> 48:24.030
screams fill the creek,

48:24.890 --> 48:29.610
but there is no escape. Soon, all is quiet again,

48:30.350 --> 48:32.350
apart from the sound of three large

48:32.350 --> 48:36.990
crocodiles slowly creeping back to the green water. Their big

48:36.990 --> 48:39.130
mouths now full of dinner.

48:40.390 --> 48:43.990
And of sixty thousand pounds of uncut diamonds.

48:47.010 --> 48:53.730
The wrong bag. The sky is not there. In its

48:53.730 --> 48:56.850
place are a thousand adverts on a hundred

48:56.850 --> 49:01.870
television screens. A sea of lights that constantly move and

49:01.870 --> 49:04.110
change. Red, white,

49:04.430 --> 49:08.810
blue, green, orange, gold. Red, white, blue, green, orange, gold.

49:09.970 --> 49:10.810
They never stop.

49:11.790 --> 49:16.230
And on the television screens there are giant faces, clips

49:16.230 --> 49:18.170
from movies, news headlines,

49:18.630 --> 49:23.550
commercials for cars and perfume, chocolate and beer. The sounds

49:23.550 --> 49:26.550
never stop. The horns of

49:26.550 --> 49:29.690
the big yellow taxis, the music from the bars and

49:29.690 --> 49:34.810
the restaurants. And the voices. So many voices.

49:35.910 --> 49:40.670
So many that they are impossible to understand. And so

49:40.670 --> 49:43.870
many languages. English, Spanish,

49:44.390 --> 49:50.350
Chinese, Italian, German, Portuguese. They all mix together and are

49:50.350 --> 49:51.950
little more than noise to

49:51.950 --> 49:56.810
an onlooker. But the smells are the worst. One moment

49:56.810 --> 49:58.930
it's the scent of hot dogs, onions,

49:58.930 --> 50:04.750
tomatoes, fries or donuts. Delicious smells that make the stomach

50:04.750 --> 50:05.390
rumble.

50:06.430 --> 50:11.550
But then it's cigarettes, alcohol, garbage and vomit. And all

50:11.550 --> 50:13.690
of this mixes with the sweat of

50:13.690 --> 50:18.170
the thousands of people in one place. Jake begins to

50:18.170 --> 50:28.710
feel sick again and looks down at his dirty

50:28.710 --> 50:32.830
He always calls Jake Kidd. But he must be the

50:32.830 --> 50:35.210
same age as him, 12 or 13.

50:36.210 --> 50:40.870
It's okay. Jake says and looks up again. He has

50:40.870 --> 50:44.450
to be stronger, he knows. He has to be more

50:44.450 --> 50:44.750
like

50:44.750 --> 50:49.570
Nick. You're just hungry. After we eat, you will think

50:49.570 --> 50:51.490
this place is the best in the world.

50:52.470 --> 50:54.750
With a full belly, you can sit and watch this

50:54.750 --> 50:58.650
all day. It's just, well, why don't we come at

50:58.650 --> 51:03.090
night? Isn't it better at night, Nick? How dumb are

51:03.090 --> 51:06.090
you? His new friend says and he looks annoyed.

51:07.230 --> 51:11.350
At night they worry. At night everyone worries in New

51:11.350 --> 51:14.790
York. In the day when it's hot and sunny,

51:15.130 --> 51:18.530
like today, they don't worry about anything. They just watch

51:18.530 --> 51:20.770
those big screens take pictures,

51:21.150 --> 51:23.730
eat and drink. They don't even look at us twice.

51:25.070 --> 51:26.790
And Jake knows that he's right.

51:27.450 --> 51:30.430
Look, it's easy. You do what I say, no problem.

51:31.610 --> 51:33.190
And Nick looks at him for a moment.

51:34.230 --> 51:39.070
You look okay now. These new clothes aren't bad. The

51:39.070 --> 51:43.110
new clothes are not new, Jake knows. Not really.

51:44.110 --> 51:47.410
Nick steals clothes from the washing lines on the back

51:47.410 --> 51:50.010
streets. But they are better than the

51:50.010 --> 51:53.070
dirty old jeans and green jacket that are now in

51:53.070 --> 51:54.990
a bin behind the shop where they sit.

51:55.730 --> 51:59.910
You have to look good, kid. Remember that. You have

51:59.910 --> 52:02.310
to look like them, he says.

52:03.170 --> 52:06.250
Then they don't worry. You can get near to them.

52:06.710 --> 52:09.090
Be casual. Look up at the big screens.

52:09.310 --> 52:11.230
It's good if you get a camera out and pretend

52:11.230 --> 52:12.610
to take some snaps, you know.

52:13.230 --> 52:16.590
Then when you get the chance, you do it. You

52:16.590 --> 52:20.050
grab a bag. A woman's bag is the best. They

52:20.050 --> 52:20.410
have more

52:20.410 --> 52:24.810
things in them. But a guy's bag is easier. A

52:24.810 --> 52:26.990
guy's bag you can just walk away with.

52:27.850 --> 52:30.470
If you get a woman's bag, you sometimes have to

52:30.470 --> 52:33.390
run. Jake feels really sick now.

52:34.230 --> 52:37.590
The sun is somewhere up there above the skyscrapers of

52:37.590 --> 52:41.030
Times Square. And the afternoon is hot.

52:42.070 --> 52:46.230
The smells and sounds make a horrible mixture. He thinks

52:46.230 --> 52:49.550
about home for a moment. But that is

52:49.550 --> 52:53.450
too far away now and too long ago. You want

52:53.450 --> 52:55.970
to eat, don't you, kid? Jake nods.

52:56.990 --> 53:00.590
And you remember where the cameras are? The NYPD ones?

53:01.270 --> 53:02.630
The others are nothing.

53:03.470 --> 53:05.770
But don't let the NYPD ones see you or you're

53:05.770 --> 53:08.950
not coming back here, not with me. Jake nods again.

53:09.830 --> 53:12.130
So we do it now and we meet back on

53:12.130 --> 53:17.010
9th Avenue. You got it? Nick says. They both stand

53:17.010 --> 53:17.350
up.

53:18.010 --> 53:21.810
But before Nick moves into the crowds, Jake stops him.

53:22.630 --> 53:25.650
But what if someone sees me? What if they stop

53:25.650 --> 53:27.510
me? Nick smiles.

53:28.290 --> 53:31.630
No worries, just say it's the wrong bag. And then

53:31.630 --> 53:36.290
he goes. And Jake is alone. He moves out into

53:36.290 --> 53:39.530
the crowds of people. He knows where he has to

53:39.530 --> 53:43.370
go to the red stairs. He moves slowly.

53:44.250 --> 53:48.190
No one really sees him. No one really looks. But

53:48.190 --> 53:51.130
he sees. He looks. He watches.

53:52.210 --> 53:56.690
He sees kids his own age laughing and joking. He

53:56.690 --> 53:58.910
looks at the food on the small tables in front

53:58.910 --> 54:02.850
of the cafes and bars. He sees two policemen in

54:02.850 --> 54:05.110
the distance and he moves the other way,

54:05.570 --> 54:11.270
walking between families and couples, businessmen and tourists. When he

54:11.270 --> 54:12.570
reaches the red steps,

54:12.570 --> 54:16.890
he is hot and sweaty, hungry too. But you can't

54:16.890 --> 54:18.430
think about that, he tells himself.

54:19.510 --> 54:23.410
He needs to think clearly now. He needs to think

54:23.410 --> 54:25.910
like Nick. On the red steps,

54:26.290 --> 54:30.230
there is a group of maybe 30 Japanese tourists. They

54:30.230 --> 54:32.430
all have a camera and are all taking photos.

54:33.530 --> 54:36.270
But their bags are on their shoulders and there are

54:36.270 --> 54:37.550
too many of them, he knows.

54:38.310 --> 54:43.290
Most do not see anything, but one always sees something.

54:44.110 --> 54:47.110
And one is enough. So who?

54:48.190 --> 54:52.170
And then he sees the man. He looks like any

54:52.170 --> 54:56.010
other foreign tourist. He has a camera around his neck,

54:56.590 --> 54:59.270
sunglasses on his face and a map in his hand.

55:00.170 --> 55:02.810
Except Jake is not sure he is a tourist.

55:03.430 --> 55:07.150
There is something different about him. The man does not

55:07.150 --> 55:09.850
use the camera and does not look at the

55:09.850 --> 55:14.570
map. In fact, the man does nothing at all. Occasionally

55:14.570 --> 55:16.390
he just looks at his watch.

55:17.510 --> 55:21.510
But the bag is by his feet. It looks expensive,

55:22.490 --> 55:23.770
made from black leather.

55:24.630 --> 55:28.350
Nick calls them weekend bags. He says they are the

55:28.350 --> 55:31.150
best. Inside them there are wallets,

55:31.150 --> 55:33.450
phones, tablets, everything.

55:34.310 --> 55:39.770
Okay. Okay, you can do this. Jake tells himself. He

55:39.770 --> 55:41.530
just needs to be quick.

55:42.470 --> 55:45.290
The man never even looks at the bag, so Jake

55:45.290 --> 55:48.070
begins to move in his direction casually.

55:48.910 --> 55:51.450
He looks up at the lights and the television screens.

55:52.530 --> 55:55.390
Then he is near enough and he looks at

55:55.390 --> 55:58.570
the man. He thinks again that he is a strange

55:58.570 --> 56:02.430
tourist. From here Jake can see that he looks

56:02.430 --> 56:06.070
nervous. But then the man looks to the right and

56:06.070 --> 56:09.950
Jake knows it is his best chance. He grabs the

56:09.950 --> 56:13.690
bag and moves away. He expects to hear a shout,

56:14.510 --> 56:17.630
but there is nothing. So he moves into the crowds

56:17.630 --> 56:22.130
like Nick does. He wants to run, but he walks

56:22.130 --> 56:25.710
and notices that the bag is heavy, really heavy.

56:27.170 --> 56:30.330
And he begins to imagine Nick's face when he sees

56:30.330 --> 56:33.070
the bag and he already begins to imagine

56:33.070 --> 56:36.350
the food that he can buy. But the bag is

56:36.350 --> 56:41.290
heavy, he thinks again. So heavy. And he slows.

56:41.970 --> 56:45.690
Maybe he should look inside, he thinks, just to make

56:45.690 --> 56:48.550
sure. He looks around and steps into the

56:48.550 --> 56:52.030
doorway of a shop for a moment. Then he kneels

56:52.030 --> 56:55.670
down and opens the bag. And for a moment he

56:55.670 --> 56:55.890
does

56:55.890 --> 57:00.930
not understand. There is no wallet, no phone, no tablet,

57:01.350 --> 57:03.930
no clothes. There is only.

57:04.950 --> 57:08.210
Then he hears the man shout and he looks up

57:08.210 --> 57:11.090
and sees his angry face running towards him through

57:11.090 --> 57:14.410
the crowd. He has no time to think, but he

57:14.410 --> 57:17.990
must. Can he leave the bag? Can he just run

57:17.990 --> 57:18.270
away?

57:19.450 --> 57:22.670
Run away? When he knows what the man is going

57:22.670 --> 57:23.010
to do?

57:24.970 --> 57:28.990
No. Not this time. And then he is up and

57:28.990 --> 57:31.490
runs too and he has the bag in his hands.

57:32.450 --> 57:35.150
For a moment he has no idea what to do

57:35.150 --> 57:38.290
or where to go. He thinks that maybe Nick would

57:38.290 --> 57:38.850
know that

57:38.850 --> 57:42.930
Nick would have some advice. And then he realises that

57:42.930 --> 57:43.850
he does know.

57:44.910 --> 57:48.490
And you remember where the cameras are? The NYPD ones?

57:49.410 --> 57:53.690
Yes, I remember Jake thinks. But can he get there

57:53.690 --> 57:55.330
before the man catches him?

57:56.210 --> 57:59.170
There is another shout from behind him, but Jake keeps

57:59.170 --> 57:59.770
moving.

58:00.570 --> 58:04.470
Above the crowd he can see the NYPD camera on

58:04.470 --> 58:07.570
top of a tall post. And he pushes past the

58:07.570 --> 58:11.130
tourists to reach it. For a moment there are people

58:11.130 --> 58:12.210
all around him.

58:12.950 --> 58:15.830
And he thinks he will never get there. But then

58:15.830 --> 58:18.470
he pushes past some kids who shout at him and

58:18.470 --> 58:23.390
he is there, directly below the camera. And now? Now

58:23.390 --> 58:26.510
what? He hears another shout and knows that

58:26.510 --> 58:29.530
the man is nearly here. But the camera is not

58:29.530 --> 58:32.710
looking at him. It is turning slowly in the other

58:32.710 --> 58:36.730
direction. Hey! He shouts and he begins to jump up

58:36.730 --> 58:37.170
and down.

58:37.830 --> 58:41.450
Down here! Look down here! But he has no idea

58:41.450 --> 58:42.910
if anyone can hear him.

58:43.430 --> 58:45.910
He opens the bag for everyone to see and there

58:45.910 --> 58:47.890
is a cry from a woman near to him,

58:48.290 --> 58:51.670
followed by another and another. This must be why the

58:51.670 --> 58:55.110
camera turns. Jake holds up the bag,

58:55.110 --> 58:59.550
but he is scared, so scared, though he has to

58:59.550 --> 58:59.870
do it.

59:00.550 --> 59:04.550
That's mine. The man's voice says behind him. And there

59:04.550 --> 59:05.970
are more cries from the crowd,

59:06.250 --> 59:08.590
and everyone seems to know what is happening now.

59:09.190 --> 59:12.830
Give it to me, the man says. Jake looks at

59:12.830 --> 59:14.250
the bag one more time.

59:15.190 --> 59:18.230
What he sees inside looks just like from the movies.

59:19.170 --> 59:25.090
The clock, the wires, and the heavy

59:25.090 --> 59:26.910
lights to give it to the man because he is

59:26.910 --> 59:31.330
so scared. But he will not. No, he answers.

59:32.130 --> 59:34.670
Then someone in the crowd says something and the man

59:34.670 --> 59:37.750
looks around. The scared cries now

59:37.750 --> 59:42.130
become angry shouts. Jake is pushed and he falls and

59:42.130 --> 59:44.590
loses the bag. He thinks that the

59:44.590 --> 59:46.850
people are shouting at him and he wants to explain.

59:47.630 --> 59:49.470
But it was not the man who pushed

59:49.470 --> 59:53.610
Jake and took the bag. It was a policeman. The

59:53.610 --> 59:56.790
man is underneath four NYPD officers.

59:57.650 --> 01:00:02.050
Jake now realises that the crowd is not shouting. It

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:02.570
is cheering.

01:00:03.550 --> 01:00:06.210
And a police officer helps him to stand and says

01:00:06.210 --> 01:00:07.870
something about him being a hero.

01:00:08.630 --> 01:00:12.550
How did you know, kid? A voice says. But this

01:00:12.550 --> 01:00:13.890
time it's not Nick.

01:00:14.850 --> 01:00:20.810
I didn't, he manages to say. It's just the wrong

01:00:20.810 --> 01:00:21.250
bag.

01:00:22.510 --> 01:00:28.010
The perfect murder. The QM2 darling is the finest ocean

01:00:28.010 --> 01:00:29.050
liner in the world.

01:00:29.910 --> 01:00:32.130
Sure, there are one or two bigger than her but

01:00:32.130 --> 01:00:34.750
none of them has her romance or her luxury.

01:00:35.950 --> 01:00:39.690
Mrs Carolina Heath says as they enter the dining room.

01:00:40.490 --> 01:00:43.050
Her young new friend only smiles.

01:00:43.890 --> 01:00:48.030
She is a quiet young thing and beautiful too. And

01:00:48.030 --> 01:00:51.010
Carolina likes to have beautiful things around her.

01:00:51.690 --> 01:00:53.950
So she is more than happy to talk for both

01:00:53.950 --> 01:00:54.290
of them.

01:00:54.770 --> 01:00:58.250
This is your first cruise, you say? You're going to

01:00:58.250 --> 01:01:01.230
love it. Just look at the view out there.

01:01:02.090 --> 01:01:05.210
And from the large glass windows they can see the

01:01:05.210 --> 01:01:07.610
majestic figure of the Statue of Liberty

01:01:07.610 --> 01:01:11.090
as the ship slowly moves away from the port of

01:01:11.090 --> 01:01:13.850
New York and heads into the deep of the ocean.

01:01:15.150 --> 01:01:20.570
It's fantastic, Eleanor says. And again Carolina is very happy

01:01:20.570 --> 01:01:21.850
to have a new companion.

01:01:23.210 --> 01:01:27.910
The dining room is magnificent. The tables are covered in

01:01:27.910 --> 01:01:30.490
white and the lights are low and atmospheric.

01:01:31.830 --> 01:01:35.130
The band in the corner is playing soft classical music.

01:01:35.910 --> 01:01:37.910
Well I wonder what the other people at our table

01:01:37.910 --> 01:01:38.290
are like.

01:01:39.010 --> 01:01:41.170
Oh my look, here we are, table six.

01:01:42.190 --> 01:01:46.830
Well good evening gentlemen, Carolina says. And the three men

01:01:46.830 --> 01:01:48.850
stop their conversation and smile.

01:01:49.770 --> 01:01:53.490
Mrs Heath, one says, how good to see you again.

01:01:54.270 --> 01:01:56.550
Another evening of champagne and dancing?

01:01:57.550 --> 01:02:00.970
Every night Peter, my doctor tells me that I must.

01:02:01.710 --> 01:02:02.190
She laughs.

01:02:02.890 --> 01:02:06.210
Gentlemen, let me introduce you to my new friend, Miss

01:02:06.210 --> 01:02:06.930
Eleanor Chance.

01:02:07.910 --> 01:02:12.930
Eleanor only nods and smiles. And these Eleanor, well how

01:02:12.930 --> 01:02:13.870
to describe them?

01:02:14.290 --> 01:02:17.410
I suppose every ship needs some pirates. And these are

01:02:17.410 --> 01:02:20.270
they. Meet Peter, Edward and Michael.

01:02:21.250 --> 01:02:25.570
The men stand and nod politely. And Carolina is amused

01:02:25.570 --> 01:02:28.130
by the interested looks they give Eleanor

01:02:28.130 --> 01:02:35.350
Chance. Pirates, Eleanor asks. Well maybe not pirates. But you

01:02:35.350 --> 01:02:36.310
should still be careful.

01:02:37.150 --> 01:02:40.070
They are in fact writers. And I don't know which

01:02:40.070 --> 01:02:40.470
is worse.

01:02:41.250 --> 01:02:46.870
Writers, how interesting. Please sit down. Edward says with a

01:02:46.870 --> 01:02:48.950
smile that shows early signs of

01:02:48.950 --> 01:02:53.130
infatuation. No I can't, I must find the captain. He

01:02:53.130 --> 01:02:54.970
promised to tell me all about the new people

01:02:54.970 --> 01:02:58.230
on board today. You know how I must know who

01:02:58.230 --> 01:03:00.890
I'm sailing with. She looks at the men.

01:03:01.710 --> 01:03:04.130
Oh but can I trust you three to look after

01:03:04.130 --> 01:03:07.290
Eleanor? This is her first night and her first cruise.

01:03:08.250 --> 01:03:10.670
She does not need to hear any of your horrible

01:03:10.670 --> 01:03:12.650
stories or strange ideas.

01:03:13.570 --> 01:03:16.870
Oh well I suppose we can change the subject. But

01:03:16.870 --> 01:03:18.830
we are having a really interesting conversation.

01:03:19.610 --> 01:03:23.990
Carolina laughs. I don't want to know. Just be nice.

01:03:25.050 --> 01:03:26.530
And she smiles at Eleanor.

01:03:27.470 --> 01:03:30.210
If they scare you just scream and I can rescue

01:03:30.210 --> 01:03:32.850
you. Oh I think I can look after myself.

01:03:33.530 --> 01:03:37.990
responds Eleanor. And again Carolina thinks what a sweet lovely

01:03:37.990 --> 01:03:38.950
thing she is.

01:03:39.630 --> 01:03:43.950
She must be only 25 or 26. Her long blonde

01:03:43.950 --> 01:03:47.690
hair is elegant and her face full of classical beauty.

01:03:48.430 --> 01:03:54.450
And those eyes. Such innocent blue eyes. Yes a lovely

01:03:54.450 --> 01:03:56.890
new companion she thinks as she leaves.

01:03:57.850 --> 01:04:00.870
At the table Edward offers Eleanor a chair and Michael

01:04:00.870 --> 01:04:02.490
passes her a glass of champagne.

01:04:03.550 --> 01:04:08.450
So are you all writers? She asks. Yes says Peter.

01:04:09.270 --> 01:04:12.090
Of different types. I'm in film Edward

01:04:12.090 --> 01:04:16.930
here as a novelist and Michael writes plays. Fascinating. She

01:04:16.930 --> 01:04:19.170
says. And all three look happy

01:04:19.170 --> 01:04:22.970
that she thinks so. And what is this interesting conversation

01:04:22.970 --> 01:04:25.690
that I'm interrupting? Oh we can't

01:04:25.690 --> 01:04:28.510
bore you with that. Please tell us about yourself says

01:04:28.510 --> 01:04:28.750
Edward.

01:04:29.730 --> 01:04:33.930
Eleanor smiles shyly and moves the elegant white silk scarf

01:04:33.930 --> 01:04:35.290
that lies around her neck

01:04:35.290 --> 01:04:38.830
above her black dress. There is very little to say

01:04:38.830 --> 01:04:40.890
I'm sailing from here to Southampton

01:04:40.890 --> 01:04:43.470
then I intend to stay in England for some time.

01:04:44.230 --> 01:04:45.210
For the summer perhaps.

01:04:46.290 --> 01:04:49.210
Then she is quiet and the three men think how

01:04:49.210 --> 01:04:50.910
polite and gentle she seems.

01:04:51.750 --> 01:04:55.810
I see says Peter. Well this is a tradition of

01:04:55.810 --> 01:04:58.650
ours. Every year we take a cruise on old Mary.

01:04:59.490 --> 01:05:02.930
This is the sixth year. A good escape from editors

01:05:02.930 --> 01:05:03.590
and deadlines.

01:05:03.590 --> 01:05:09.110
And wives says Michael. Well for them not for me

01:05:09.110 --> 01:05:12.470
I'm not married says Edward. A little too quickly.

01:05:13.410 --> 01:05:16.850
For a moment there's an awkward silence and Peter and

01:05:16.850 --> 01:05:18.250
Michael exchange a smile.

01:05:18.910 --> 01:05:22.990
Well our conversation is about murder says Peter to fill

01:05:22.990 --> 01:05:23.510
the silence.

01:05:24.370 --> 01:05:30.370
The perfect murder. Eleanor smiles. I see. I'm sure she's

01:05:30.370 --> 01:05:32.410
not interested Pete says Edward.

01:05:33.150 --> 01:05:36.250
Oh but I am. Mrs. Heath is lovely but she

01:05:36.250 --> 01:05:38.250
only talks about scandal and gossip.

01:05:39.230 --> 01:05:44.890
See Edward? We can continue to argue. Michael jokes. You

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:46.930
see we all have very different ideas

01:05:46.930 --> 01:05:50.710
about what the perfect murder is. Peter thinks that for

01:05:50.710 --> 01:05:52.710
a film there must be something visual

01:05:52.710 --> 01:05:56.750
about the murder weapon. For me the important things are

01:05:56.750 --> 01:05:58.130
the character and the motive.

01:05:59.150 --> 01:06:03.130
And for me Edward says as he refills Eleanor's glass.

01:06:04.250 --> 01:06:05.850
The important thing is the twist.

01:06:06.750 --> 01:06:10.070
The twist. You know the surprise at the end of

01:06:10.070 --> 01:06:11.710
the story the thing you don't expect.

01:06:12.650 --> 01:06:16.750
Eleanor smiles and takes a drink. The statue of liberty

01:06:16.750 --> 01:06:18.430
is still visible in the distance

01:06:19.010 --> 01:06:21.290
but they will soon be alone on the dark ocean.

01:06:22.330 --> 01:06:25.270
You know I think you're all correct. In fact I

01:06:25.270 --> 01:06:27.930
have an idea for a story. An idea I think

01:06:27.930 --> 01:06:28.590
about occasionally.

01:06:29.230 --> 01:06:32.290
Really? Says Peter. Well you must tell us.

01:06:33.110 --> 01:06:37.090
Maybe she says with another shy smile. But you first.

01:06:37.790 --> 01:06:39.450
What's your idea for the perfect murder

01:06:39.450 --> 01:06:43.870
weapon? Peter laughs. Okay well it's not my idea and

01:06:43.870 --> 01:06:45.990
it's old but I think it's great for a film.

01:06:46.770 --> 01:06:50.910
It's an icicle. The other two men laugh. He always

01:06:50.910 --> 01:06:53.210
says this. Edward informs Eleanor.

01:06:53.950 --> 01:06:57.670
Because it's perfect. After the murderer kills the victim they

01:06:57.670 --> 01:06:58.510
just watch the

01:06:58.510 --> 01:07:03.090
weapon melt. No fingerprints. No evidence. What do you think

01:07:03.090 --> 01:07:04.470
Eleanor? She smiles.

01:07:05.470 --> 01:07:11.530
It's very clever. But well I prefer fire. Fire. Yes

01:07:11.530 --> 01:07:14.430
fire kills and it destroys the evidence.

01:07:15.350 --> 01:07:18.130
And also a fire can look like an accident. The

01:07:18.130 --> 01:07:19.190
icicle never can.

01:07:20.030 --> 01:07:25.310
Haha she's right. Laughs Michael. So what about characters and

01:07:25.310 --> 01:07:26.970
motive? He continues.

01:07:27.650 --> 01:07:30.710
A beautiful young couple who are happy and in love.

01:07:31.550 --> 01:07:34.590
What and he kills her? No she kills him.

01:07:35.390 --> 01:07:38.950
Let me guess they're rich. She wants his money. Eleanor

01:07:38.950 --> 01:07:39.910
takes another drink.

01:07:40.830 --> 01:07:45.170
No she's the rich one. So what's the motive? Michael

01:07:45.170 --> 01:07:45.510
asks.

01:07:46.110 --> 01:07:50.650
Wait a minute. Interrupts Peter. You say she kills him.

01:07:51.510 --> 01:07:53.030
With fire. How?

01:07:53.750 --> 01:07:55.930
She locks him in a room in a burning house?

01:07:56.770 --> 01:07:58.470
No because then he might escape.

01:07:59.290 --> 01:08:03.050
She drugs him with sleeping pills during dinner. She always

01:08:03.050 --> 01:08:04.610
goes for a run in the evening.

01:08:05.450 --> 01:08:08.230
But this time she waits until he falls asleep in

01:08:08.230 --> 01:08:09.110
a chair in the lounge.

01:08:09.870 --> 01:08:13.270
And she puts a candle to the curtains. Then she

01:08:13.270 --> 01:08:16.050
goes for her run and makes sure that many people

01:08:16.050 --> 01:08:20.850
see her. Peter nods his head. Interesting but a coroner

01:08:20.850 --> 01:08:23.490
will find traces of sleeping pills in

01:08:23.490 --> 01:08:26.690
the blood. They'll know. No not with this type of

01:08:26.690 --> 01:08:29.550
pill. At a certain temperature it completely

01:08:29.550 --> 01:08:32.930
burns away. Only a small trace of it can be

01:08:32.930 --> 01:08:36.210
detected. And if they are detected. So what?

01:08:36.770 --> 01:08:42.950
They are his pills. Peter laughs this time. Excellent. Very

01:08:42.950 --> 01:08:44.530
clever. Edward agrees.

01:08:45.210 --> 01:08:47.910
But unfortunately the wife is always a suspect in a

01:08:47.910 --> 01:08:48.130
murder.

01:08:49.030 --> 01:08:53.810
Normally yes says Eleanor. And all three men notice how

01:08:53.810 --> 01:08:55.690
her smile fades a little.

01:08:56.550 --> 01:08:59.350
But she has a plan for that. You see she

01:08:59.350 --> 01:09:01.470
runs until she hears the fire engines.

01:09:02.230 --> 01:09:05.930
Then she returns to the house. There are people there

01:09:05.930 --> 01:09:07.070
already. Neighbors.

01:09:07.570 --> 01:09:10.910
And this is just what she wants. They try to

01:09:10.910 --> 01:09:13.610
stop her but she runs into the burning building.

01:09:14.330 --> 01:09:17.990
No one follows her. They can't. They know it's too

01:09:17.990 --> 01:09:21.050
dangerous. And so she goes to her husband as

01:09:21.050 --> 01:09:25.150
the flames spread over his body and she watches. And

01:09:25.150 --> 01:09:27.590
while she watches she lets the flames touch

01:09:27.590 --> 01:09:31.070
her too. They reach out and they burn her back

01:09:31.070 --> 01:09:32.510
and her neck and her hair.

01:09:33.410 --> 01:09:35.870
And at this point she screams and runs from the

01:09:35.870 --> 01:09:37.270
building and falls to the floor.

01:09:38.530 --> 01:09:42.430
Eleanor stops speaking. And for a moment there is silence

01:09:42.430 --> 01:09:43.290
at the table.

01:09:44.630 --> 01:09:48.750
My god says Edward. She lets the flames burn her.

01:09:49.910 --> 01:09:52.150
Michael takes a moment to think about it

01:09:52.150 --> 01:09:56.690
and then nods. It's perfect. The perfect way to avoid

01:09:56.690 --> 01:09:56.970
suspicion.

01:09:58.110 --> 01:10:01.410
Everyone thinks it's an accident and that she is heartbroken

01:10:01.410 --> 01:10:02.290
says Peter.

01:10:03.070 --> 01:10:07.590
Yes. Eleanor says. And for a moment more there is

01:10:07.590 --> 01:10:08.390
silence again.

01:10:09.770 --> 01:10:13.330
Then the band starts to play a waltz and Eleanor

01:10:13.330 --> 01:10:16.250
looks at Edward. I don't suppose you dance Edward.

01:10:17.190 --> 01:10:20.210
And the writer goes a little red. Actually I do.

01:10:20.790 --> 01:10:21.750
Would you like to join me?

01:10:22.150 --> 01:10:26.530
Eleanor smiles and they both stand up. She adjusts the

01:10:26.530 --> 01:10:28.070
white scarf around her neck.

01:10:28.790 --> 01:10:33.170
But what about the woman's motive? Michael asks. Eleanor smiles.

01:10:34.070 --> 01:10:35.610
Yes that's the difficult part.

01:10:36.370 --> 01:10:39.530
And I'm afraid I just don't know. I suppose sometimes

01:10:39.530 --> 01:10:42.330
a person just enjoys murder.

01:10:43.590 --> 01:10:46.210
And as Eleanor and Edward move away to the dance

01:10:46.210 --> 01:10:49.230
floor Peter and Michael see her adjust the

01:10:49.230 --> 01:10:52.490
scarf around her neck one last time. And in the

01:10:52.490 --> 01:10:54.530
low romantic light of the ballroom

01:10:54.530 --> 01:10:57.790
they both think they see something strange on her back

01:10:57.790 --> 01:11:00.690
and neck. Something which makes them stop

01:11:01.150 --> 01:11:05.190
and look at each other. But no. It cannot be

01:11:05.190 --> 01:11:08.730
what they think it is. It cannot be burnt skin

01:11:08.730 --> 01:11:16.170
under the elegant white scarf. Can it? Case closed.

01:11:19.610 --> 01:11:25.410
Normally Nick likes his job but not today. Today he

01:11:25.410 --> 01:11:27.130
just wants to get out of the hot

01:11:27.130 --> 01:11:31.210
courtroom away from the serious lawyers in their black gowns

01:11:31.210 --> 01:11:33.570
and white wigs and go and enjoy the

01:11:33.570 --> 01:11:37.750
son. It's a good job he thinks. It's better than

01:11:37.750 --> 01:11:40.370
serving drinks in a pub or helping out at his

01:11:40.370 --> 01:11:40.810
dad's

01:11:40.810 --> 01:11:44.310
office. But only if it's a short day and only

01:11:44.310 --> 01:11:47.890
if the case is closed quickly. But today it's nearly

01:11:47.890 --> 01:11:52.090
three and the case is nowhere near closed. Still he

01:11:52.090 --> 01:11:53.550
likes the title of his job.

01:11:54.490 --> 01:11:59.570
Court reporter sounds good. It sounds important. And that is

01:11:59.570 --> 01:12:01.730
exactly how he describes it to any

01:12:01.730 --> 01:12:06.190
girl that asks. In reality however all he does is

01:12:06.190 --> 01:12:08.750
press play on the recording device and write

01:12:08.750 --> 01:12:11.690
down a few notes about when the judge enters, when

01:12:11.690 --> 01:12:14.450
the prosecution or defense speaks or what the

01:12:14.450 --> 01:12:19.310
final verdict is. And sometimes the cases are interesting. And

01:12:19.310 --> 01:12:20.390
he likes having some good

01:12:20.390 --> 01:12:23.330
stories to tell the guys in the pub. He also

01:12:23.330 --> 01:12:26.070
enjoys deciding who is innocent and who is guilty.

01:12:26.870 --> 01:12:30.470
But today that's too easy. So he looks out of

01:12:30.470 --> 01:12:33.590
the window and waits for the judge. Sometimes he

01:12:33.590 --> 01:12:37.170
looks across at the defendant's sister, a young woman with

01:12:37.170 --> 01:12:40.690
long dark hair and sad eyes. But only

01:12:40.690 --> 01:12:44.650
sometimes because the defendant and the rest of her family,

01:12:44.890 --> 01:12:48.410
the Lee family, are wild. And he does

01:12:48.410 --> 01:12:52.070
not want to make her or them angry. They have

01:12:52.070 --> 01:12:54.890
a terrible reputation in Bristol and there is not

01:12:54.890 --> 01:12:59.130
one of them that does not scare Nick. All rise.

01:13:00.150 --> 01:13:04.010
The court clerk says. And the jury, the lawyers and

01:13:04.010 --> 01:13:07.890
the family of the defendant all stand. Nick does too.

01:13:08.330 --> 01:13:10.290
And he remembers to press the button on the

01:13:10.290 --> 01:13:13.650
device. He forgot to do it once and they refused

01:13:13.650 --> 01:13:15.030
to pay him for the day.

01:13:15.990 --> 01:13:19.190
Please be seated, says the judge, a woman of about

01:13:19.190 --> 01:13:22.230
40 years of age with a serious face and tone.

01:13:23.110 --> 01:13:26.490
My summary of this case is brief. The jury know

01:13:26.490 --> 01:13:30.230
all the details. On Wednesday the 5th of January

01:13:30.230 --> 01:13:32.690
Mrs. Dawson went to the house of her sister, the

01:13:32.690 --> 01:13:35.830
defendant, Miss Lee. Mrs. Dawson was bleeding

01:13:35.830 --> 01:13:39.350
from her nose and mouth. She also had marks on

01:13:39.350 --> 01:13:42.710
her face. She says her husband, the deceased

01:13:42.710 --> 01:13:47.030
Mr. Dawson, hit her there several times. There are pictures

01:13:47.030 --> 01:13:48.770
of these injuries but there is no

01:13:48.770 --> 01:13:52.970
proof that Mr. Dawson hit Mrs. Dawson. However, that is

01:13:52.970 --> 01:13:55.470
not why you are here. You are here because

01:13:55.470 --> 01:13:58.270
when Miss Lee saw her young sister, she took a

01:13:58.270 --> 01:14:00.270
pair of scissors from her kitchen table,

01:14:00.270 --> 01:14:03.930
said something to her sister and left the house. The

01:14:03.930 --> 01:14:05.190
words, she said, were,

01:14:05.530 --> 01:14:08.790
I will kill him. But the defendant says she does

01:14:08.790 --> 01:14:09.690
not remember that.

01:14:10.270 --> 01:14:13.990
Several people saw the defendant walking around Bristol, looking for

01:14:13.990 --> 01:14:14.430
Mr. Dawson.

01:14:15.330 --> 01:14:19.030
She stopped twice. Once at the house of one of

01:14:19.030 --> 01:14:21.910
Mrs. Dawson's friends and once at a local pub,

01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:25.690
both times she had the scissors with her and both

01:14:25.690 --> 01:14:27.930
times witnesses testified that she said,

01:14:27.930 --> 01:14:31.370
I will kill him. At half past two in the

01:14:31.370 --> 01:14:34.250
afternoon on the 5th of January, Miss Stella Lee found

01:14:34.250 --> 01:14:34.730
Mr.

01:14:34.950 --> 01:14:39.030
Dawson. He was leaving a cafe with a friend. The

01:14:39.030 --> 01:14:42.250
friend, Mr. Harris, says that Miss Lee did not say

01:14:42.250 --> 01:14:45.730
anything to Mr. Dawson and that the only thing Mr.

01:14:45.970 --> 01:14:49.510
Dawson said was hello. Miss Lee then stabbed

01:14:49.510 --> 01:14:53.110
Mr. Dawson in the neck with the scissors and he

01:14:53.110 --> 01:14:56.910
died in seconds due to loss of blood. Miss Lee

01:14:56.910 --> 01:15:00.930
waited until the police came and was arrested. Ladies and

01:15:00.930 --> 01:15:02.830
gentlemen of the jury, you must decide

01:15:02.830 --> 01:15:06.750
only one thing. The defense says that this is not

01:15:06.750 --> 01:15:10.510
murder, but manslaughter. They say this is the

01:15:10.510 --> 01:15:12.990
case because Miss Lee was not in a sane state

01:15:12.990 --> 01:15:16.390
of mind when she killed Mr. Dawson. They say that

01:15:16.390 --> 01:15:19.930
this crime was in defense of her sister. The prosecution

01:15:19.930 --> 01:15:22.990
says this is not true. They say this

01:15:22.990 --> 01:15:26.290
is premeditated murder because for half an hour Miss Lee

01:15:26.290 --> 01:15:27.470
looked for Mr. Dawson.

01:15:28.430 --> 01:15:31.310
They also say she made her intention clear on three

01:15:31.310 --> 01:15:34.370
different occasions. Please leave us now

01:15:34.370 --> 01:15:38.950
and take some time to consider these events. All rise.

01:15:39.870 --> 01:15:41.170
The court clerk says again,

01:15:42.110 --> 01:15:45.390
the judge leaves, the jury returns to its room to

01:15:45.390 --> 01:15:46.950
make a verdict and the Lee family

01:15:46.950 --> 01:15:52.410
exit to wait in the lobby. Nick sighs. It is

01:15:52.410 --> 01:15:53.930
obvious what the decision will be,

01:15:54.430 --> 01:15:56.710
but it looks like he will be here until four

01:15:56.710 --> 01:15:59.790
now. Cigarette time then, he thinks,

01:16:00.230 --> 01:16:03.750
and he leaves the courtroom. He has at least 10

01:16:03.750 --> 01:16:06.890
minutes. No jury can make a decision in less

01:16:06.890 --> 01:16:10.850
than 10 minutes. He takes the back stairs, passes three

01:16:10.850 --> 01:16:12.950
or four lawyers in their black gowns and

01:16:12.950 --> 01:16:16.130
white wigs and feels sorry for them. It is so

01:16:16.130 --> 01:16:19.750
hot today. Then he pushes open a firedoor to his

01:16:19.750 --> 01:16:22.390
personal smoking area at the back of the court next

01:16:22.390 --> 01:16:24.270
to the bins and lights his cigarette.

01:16:25.410 --> 01:16:28.090
The feeling of the sun on his face is good

01:16:28.090 --> 01:16:31.610
and the taste of the smoke is even better.

01:16:32.810 --> 01:16:34.790
Tonight is a good night to go out for a

01:16:34.790 --> 01:16:38.130
few drinks, he thinks, and he is deciding whom to

01:16:38.130 --> 01:16:38.710
call when

01:16:38.710 --> 01:16:43.570
he hears a female voice. Yeah, everything is fine, perfect.

01:16:44.450 --> 01:16:46.310
No, no one has an idea,

01:16:46.890 --> 01:16:50.490
not the police, not my mental family. Of course it

01:16:50.490 --> 01:16:54.210
will be murder. What? Oh, who cares about her?

01:16:55.010 --> 01:16:58.650
She will probably like prison the crazy cow, more people

01:16:58.650 --> 01:17:01.270
for her to work. And then I get his money

01:17:01.270 --> 01:17:03.290
and you and I can get the L out of

01:17:03.290 --> 01:17:06.750
this city and out of this country. Nick walks to

01:17:06.750 --> 01:17:07.350
the bins and

01:17:07.350 --> 01:17:10.710
looks around them. On the other side is the sister

01:17:10.710 --> 01:17:13.770
of the defendant. In the courtroom she always

01:17:13.770 --> 01:17:18.670
looks sad and confused. Now, however, she looks only victorious.

01:17:19.970 --> 01:17:22.350
Jesus, Nick says before he can

01:17:22.350 --> 01:17:26.470
stop himself. And the girl sees him and closes the

01:17:26.470 --> 01:17:29.710
mobile phone in her hand. Nick looks at her for

01:17:29.710 --> 01:17:32.830
a second and then turns and runs back to the

01:17:32.830 --> 01:17:37.010
door. He walks back up the stairs feeling confused and

01:17:37.010 --> 01:17:41.670
uncertain. He has to say something to someone, but who?

01:17:42.670 --> 01:17:46.850
The judge? Maybe. He pushes the door to

01:17:46.850 --> 01:17:50.910
the court from open. No one is there. He moves

01:17:50.910 --> 01:17:53.230
towards another door and then hears someone else

01:17:53.230 --> 01:17:57.290
enter the court. Wait, Mrs. Dawson says, and she looks

01:17:57.290 --> 01:18:00.690
like she might cry. Please wait, I need to

01:18:00.690 --> 01:18:05.770
explain. Nick waits. Why not? What can she do to

01:18:05.770 --> 01:18:09.590
him in here? She stands near to him and he

01:18:09.590 --> 01:18:09.730
can

01:18:09.730 --> 01:18:12.510
see the tears in her eyes and the sad expression

01:18:12.510 --> 01:18:15.930
on her face. But this time he knows it's not

01:18:15.930 --> 01:18:16.270
real.

01:18:17.130 --> 01:18:21.510
I heard you. Your own sister. You wanted her to

01:18:21.510 --> 01:18:24.290
kill your husband. No, you don't understand.

01:18:24.290 --> 01:18:27.370
I don't know what you were, but I loved my

01:18:27.370 --> 01:18:30.550
sister and I used to love my husband. For a

01:18:30.550 --> 01:18:30.930
second

01:18:30.930 --> 01:18:35.170
only, Nick waits. Then he shakes his head and is

01:18:35.170 --> 01:18:39.330
about to turn. Look, she says, her voice different

01:18:39.330 --> 01:18:44.130
now. I saw you looking at me yesterday. Maybe there's

01:18:44.130 --> 01:18:46.310
something we can do to make you forget this?

01:18:47.230 --> 01:18:50.170
Maybe you can take me for a drink. Then she

01:18:50.170 --> 01:18:53.310
smiles and takes his hand. For a second,

01:18:53.310 --> 01:18:56.490
he does not know what to say. But he knows

01:18:56.490 --> 01:18:59.710
what to do. And he pulls his hand away and

01:18:59.710 --> 01:19:00.470
moves to the

01:19:00.470 --> 01:19:05.070
door. For a second, she is silent. But then she

01:19:05.070 --> 01:19:08.270
speaks again. Though this time her voice is hard

01:19:08.270 --> 01:19:11.710
and angry. Fine, go and tell them what you were.

01:19:12.210 --> 01:19:15.790
Do you have any proof? No, so you can tell

01:19:15.790 --> 01:19:15.910
them

01:19:15.910 --> 01:19:19.610
what you want, but they can do nothing. And you

01:19:19.610 --> 01:19:22.870
are still here in Bristol. And so is my family.

01:19:23.590 --> 01:19:26.970
And they will not like what you say. Do you

01:19:26.970 --> 01:19:30.750
understand me? Nick stops. He understands.

01:19:32.050 --> 01:19:36.830
And she's right. There's nothing he can do. That's right,

01:19:36.830 --> 01:19:39.050
little boy. Keep quiet and you're

01:19:39.050 --> 01:19:42.650
going to be okay. I never hurt anyone. She did.

01:19:43.370 --> 01:19:46.490
Is it my fault she's so stupid? So easy to

01:19:46.490 --> 01:19:46.650
manipulate.

01:19:46.650 --> 01:19:50.110
A little bit of blood on my face. A few

01:19:50.110 --> 01:19:54.130
tears. A fake story about him hitting me. It was

01:19:54.130 --> 01:19:54.750
so easy.

01:19:55.450 --> 01:19:58.210
And if you tell anyone, it's going to be just

01:19:58.210 --> 01:20:00.350
as easy to finish you. Understand?

01:20:01.490 --> 01:20:05.130
Then the door opens and the lawyers return. And Mrs.

01:20:05.470 --> 01:20:07.310
Dawson's expression of sadness returns.

01:20:08.410 --> 01:20:12.050
Slowly they all come back in. And Nick knows he

01:20:12.050 --> 01:20:13.310
has to say something.

01:20:13.310 --> 01:20:18.230
He has to do something. But there's no time. And

01:20:18.230 --> 01:20:19.310
there's nothing he can do.

01:20:20.290 --> 01:20:23.350
The Lee family is back in the room now. And

01:20:23.350 --> 01:20:25.590
he looks at them. They are savage,

01:20:26.190 --> 01:20:30.790
terrible people who love violence. So he moves back to

01:20:30.790 --> 01:20:32.910
his desk and he sits down in the seat

01:20:32.910 --> 01:20:38.050
and feels defeated. He wants to say something. But without

01:20:38.050 --> 01:20:40.590
proof, he has nothing and the judge

01:20:40.590 --> 01:20:43.770
can do nothing. And he hears the door to the

01:20:43.770 --> 01:20:45.010
judge's chamber open.

01:20:46.150 --> 01:20:51.170
All rise. John says and Nick knows it's too late

01:20:51.170 --> 01:20:54.910
now. He stands and is about to press the button

01:20:54.910 --> 01:20:55.070
on

01:20:55.070 --> 01:20:58.310
the recording device when he sees the red light flashing.

01:20:59.170 --> 01:21:02.670
The red light. The red light means

01:21:02.670 --> 01:21:11.890
it's recording. It's recording. It was recording. It recorded. Stop,

01:21:12.490 --> 01:21:13.010
Nick shouts.

01:21:14.190 --> 01:21:16.850
And he hands the recording device to the court clerk.

01:21:17.810 --> 01:21:20.530
I think the judge needs to listen to this first.

01:21:21.370 --> 01:21:24.050
He says and he looks back at the beautiful Mrs.

01:21:24.370 --> 01:21:28.050
Dawson and sees that she is not sad now and

01:21:28.050 --> 01:21:31.130
that she is not victorious and not angry.

01:21:31.710 --> 01:21:35.310
And he smiles at her because he thinks this expression

01:21:35.310 --> 01:21:37.870
suits her best. Yes,

01:21:38.410 --> 01:21:42.570
he thinks Mrs. Dawson looks best when she is scared.

01:21:43.950 --> 01:21:44.910
Don't move.

01:21:52.010 --> 01:21:57.110
It feels like ice cold water. One moment you are

01:21:57.110 --> 01:21:57.450
asleep.

01:21:58.230 --> 01:22:02.310
Your dreams calm and gentle and your body warm in

01:22:02.310 --> 01:22:03.470
the blankets of your bed.

01:22:04.430 --> 01:22:08.870
The next moment you are awake. A horrible sensation filling

01:22:08.870 --> 01:22:09.610
your body.

01:22:10.410 --> 01:22:13.310
And you are sure that ice cold water is covering

01:22:13.310 --> 01:22:15.330
you. But it's not.

01:22:16.110 --> 01:22:21.750
No, it's something much worse. Something that makes your heart

01:22:21.750 --> 01:22:22.570
beat faster.

01:22:23.370 --> 01:22:26.870
Something that makes the hairs on your arms stand up

01:22:26.870 --> 01:22:28.670
and that makes your eyes search the

01:22:28.670 --> 01:22:33.550
horrible complete darkness of your room. No, it's not ice

01:22:33.550 --> 01:22:36.110
cold water. It's fear.

01:22:37.130 --> 01:22:39.950
And for a few moments you are so afraid that

01:22:39.950 --> 01:22:43.290
you cannot think. You know you are still in

01:22:43.290 --> 01:22:47.230
your bed, still in your house, still in your quiet

01:22:47.230 --> 01:22:48.910
street in the north of Manchester.

01:22:49.630 --> 01:22:54.130
And you want to tell yourself to relax. That everything

01:22:54.130 --> 01:22:54.830
is okay.

01:22:56.030 --> 01:22:58.870
And to close your eyes and return to your calm

01:22:58.870 --> 01:23:02.290
and gentle dreams. But you cannot.

01:23:03.130 --> 01:23:07.010
No, you cannot because you know that everything is not

01:23:07.010 --> 01:23:07.490
okay.

01:23:08.310 --> 01:23:11.590
You know that you are awake because something woke you.

01:23:12.290 --> 01:23:12.930
Some noise.

01:23:13.570 --> 01:23:18.890
Some movement. Somebody. And you try to remember what it

01:23:18.890 --> 01:23:19.170
was.

01:23:19.950 --> 01:23:23.990
But you cannot. So you lie there and you let

01:23:23.990 --> 01:23:25.870
your eyes adjust to the dark.

01:23:26.710 --> 01:23:30.370
And you do not tell yourself to relax. You do

01:23:30.370 --> 01:23:32.410
not tell yourself that everything is okay.

01:23:33.290 --> 01:23:35.970
And you do not tell yourself to return to your

01:23:35.970 --> 01:23:37.390
calm and gentle dreams.

01:23:38.010 --> 01:23:43.750
You tell yourself this. Don't move. The blanket of your

01:23:43.750 --> 01:23:45.330
bed is covering all of you

01:23:45.330 --> 01:23:48.530
except for your head. And part of you thinks that

01:23:48.530 --> 01:23:49.230
this is good.

01:23:49.970 --> 01:23:53.210
Part of you wants to cover your head too. To

01:23:53.210 --> 01:23:56.770
hide. To be completely silent and to wait.

01:23:57.670 --> 01:24:01.810
But another part of you wants to know. Needs to

01:24:01.810 --> 01:24:05.330
know. So you listen. And you look.

01:24:05.330 --> 01:24:08.650
And you try to remember what it was that woke

01:24:08.650 --> 01:24:11.390
you. A dog outside in the street.

01:24:12.370 --> 01:24:15.670
The alarm of a car. A baby crying in the

01:24:15.670 --> 01:24:21.110
next house. Or something closer. Something inside the

01:24:21.110 --> 01:24:25.990
house. The sound of breaking glass. The noise of the

01:24:25.990 --> 01:24:29.070
front door opening. A voice in the dark.

01:24:29.950 --> 01:24:33.450
So you do not move. But you let your eyes

01:24:33.450 --> 01:24:37.430
adjust. And soon the complete darkness is not so complete.

01:24:38.390 --> 01:24:41.150
And you can see your room now. Though everything seems

01:24:41.150 --> 01:24:43.450
strange and different. And

01:24:43.450 --> 01:24:47.150
everything makes you feel more afraid. The door of your

01:24:47.150 --> 01:24:49.950
wardrobe is open. And the clothes inside

01:24:49.950 --> 01:24:54.890
look like three or four small burglars watching you. The

01:24:54.890 --> 01:24:57.070
lamp in the corner of the room looks like

01:24:57.070 --> 01:25:00.950
the tall silent figure of a murderer. And the coat

01:25:00.950 --> 01:25:03.370
on the back of your door has hands that almost

01:25:03.370 --> 01:25:07.570
touch you. But this is just your imagination. Your fear.

01:25:08.130 --> 01:25:10.730
And you know that. And try to stay calm

01:25:10.730 --> 01:25:15.370
and focused. So you listen. And you think that everything

01:25:15.370 --> 01:25:18.430
seems to be normal. Inside the room

01:25:18.430 --> 01:25:22.410
everything is silent. Apart from the slow and constant tick

01:25:22.410 --> 01:25:24.030
of the small clock on the wall.

01:25:24.550 --> 01:25:28.470
And the fast irregular beat of your heart. You try

01:25:28.470 --> 01:25:31.250
to see the clock in the dark. But it's

01:25:31.250 --> 01:25:34.530
impossible. And you think that it must be somewhere between

01:25:34.530 --> 01:25:37.830
four and six o'clock. The darkest hours

01:25:37.830 --> 01:25:40.850
of the night when even the lively and vibrant city

01:25:40.850 --> 01:25:44.330
of Manchester sleeps. Yes outside the house

01:25:44.330 --> 01:25:48.050
the streets are silent. There are no shouts or loud

01:25:48.050 --> 01:25:50.590
voices coming from university students

01:25:50.590 --> 01:25:54.470
returning home from the pubs and bars. There is not

01:25:54.470 --> 01:25:56.670
yet the sound of the milk van or rubbish

01:25:56.670 --> 01:26:00.050
collectors. And there is no bird song to let you

01:26:00.050 --> 01:26:02.510
know that the sun and the new day are nearly

01:26:02.510 --> 01:26:02.990
here.

01:26:03.910 --> 01:26:08.550
You can imagine the street outside. Twenty terraced houses stretching

01:26:08.550 --> 01:26:09.550
down the road.

01:26:10.310 --> 01:26:14.350
Small houses with neither rich nor poor people inside them.

01:26:15.250 --> 01:26:17.350
All with tidy and ordinary gardens

01:26:17.350 --> 01:26:23.790
and ordinary cars. All silent and all dark. You think

01:26:23.790 --> 01:26:26.610
that if you scream someone will hear you.

01:26:27.190 --> 01:26:31.790
But you are not sure. Not completely sure. And so

01:26:31.790 --> 01:26:36.010
you wait. And you listen. And you look.

01:26:36.770 --> 01:26:43.050
And you tell yourself one more time. Don't move. After

01:26:43.050 --> 01:26:45.530
a few more moments you begin to feel a little

01:26:45.530 --> 01:26:50.370
more relaxed. The street is silent. And the house is

01:26:50.370 --> 01:26:54.010
too. Maybe it was only a bad dream that woke

01:26:54.010 --> 01:26:57.670
you. Maybe it was a text on your mobile phone.

01:26:58.510 --> 01:27:01.350
Maybe it was an animal in the garden. And then

01:27:01.350 --> 01:27:05.450
you think of Sophie. Your cat. But you know that

01:27:05.450 --> 01:27:08.670
the noise was not her. You know that Sophie is

01:27:08.670 --> 01:27:11.290
sleeping in her usual position at the top of the

01:27:11.290 --> 01:27:14.130
stairs. And that she never makes a noise in the

01:27:14.130 --> 01:27:17.790
night. And you wish for the first time that you

01:27:17.790 --> 01:27:21.370
also had a dog. A large brave dog to bark

01:27:21.370 --> 01:27:25.770
and growl at any intruders. Yes a brave dog to

01:27:25.770 --> 01:27:29.090
protect you instead of just a lazy cat that lies

01:27:29.090 --> 01:27:33.770
in dangerous places. And you almost smile. And you relax

01:27:33.770 --> 01:27:37.390
a little more. It was just a bad dream.

01:27:37.390 --> 01:27:42.010
You think. And your heart slows. And the sensation of

01:27:42.010 --> 01:27:44.590
ice cold fear begins to leave you.

01:27:45.170 --> 01:27:48.890
And now you move. You pull the covers down to

01:27:48.890 --> 01:27:51.110
your chest and make yourself comfortable again.

01:27:51.910 --> 01:27:55.110
And you know that you can rest now. Everything is

01:27:55.110 --> 01:27:59.010
okay. And your eyes close. And you feel sleep

01:27:59.010 --> 01:28:03.090
begin to take you. And then you hear it. There.

01:28:03.450 --> 01:28:07.430
A sound. Not a dream. But movement in the spare

01:28:07.430 --> 01:28:12.350
room. Where you keep the computer. Don't move. Part of

01:28:12.350 --> 01:28:14.850
you says the part that feels the sensation

01:28:14.850 --> 01:28:18.630
of cold water on your skin again. But there is

01:28:18.630 --> 01:28:21.810
another part of you now. And it's not cold with

01:28:21.810 --> 01:28:22.150
fear.

01:28:22.150 --> 01:28:28.010
It is hot. Hot with anger. Because you know now

01:28:28.010 --> 01:28:31.490
that someone is in your house. A burglar.

01:28:31.990 --> 01:28:37.330
Someone is here to steal your things. Don't move. Part

01:28:37.330 --> 01:28:39.850
of you says again. But you do.

01:28:41.150 --> 01:28:43.990
Quietly you move the blankets from your body and you

01:28:43.990 --> 01:28:45.810
take the dressing gown from the end of your

01:28:45.810 --> 01:28:48.510
bed and you put it on. You know you should

01:28:48.510 --> 01:28:51.110
call the police but you need to do something more.

01:28:51.110 --> 01:28:54.530
Something quick. At the side of your bed there is

01:28:54.530 --> 01:28:57.150
a table. And on the table there is a small

01:28:57.150 --> 01:28:57.670
statue.

01:28:58.790 --> 01:29:02.150
It's a statue of a woman. And it's your favorite

01:29:02.150 --> 01:29:06.790
statue. It's also a very heavy statue. You pick

01:29:06.790 --> 01:29:09.910
it up. Hold it like a club and swing it.

01:29:10.570 --> 01:29:14.110
Yes. It's heavy enough. One hit to the head.

01:29:14.890 --> 01:29:18.970
But can you do it? Can you hit someone? Can

01:29:18.970 --> 01:29:22.810
you hit a burglar? Then you hear another noise from

01:29:22.810 --> 01:29:27.650
the spare room. My computer you think. My new computer.

01:29:28.630 --> 01:29:30.930
And then you know that yes you can do

01:29:30.930 --> 01:29:34.130
it if you need to. If you have to. If

01:29:34.130 --> 01:29:36.410
there is someone in the next room trying to steal

01:29:36.410 --> 01:29:36.730
your

01:29:36.730 --> 01:29:40.590
new computer. Someone who thinks they can enter your house

01:29:40.590 --> 01:29:41.670
in the middle of the night.

01:29:42.670 --> 01:29:48.150
What if there are two people. Two burglars. Or three.

01:29:49.250 --> 01:29:52.530
Don't move. The scared part of you says.

01:29:53.490 --> 01:29:57.210
But you must. You walk silently to the door of

01:29:57.210 --> 01:30:01.110
your room. You quietly open it just a little

01:30:01.110 --> 01:30:04.750
so you can see the dark landing. Now you can

01:30:04.750 --> 01:30:08.170
hear the movement more easily. There are no voices.

01:30:08.830 --> 01:30:11.410
No reason for you to think that there is more

01:30:11.410 --> 01:30:15.010
than one burglar. You open the door a little more

01:30:15.010 --> 01:30:19.290
and step out onto the landing. It's colder here but

01:30:19.290 --> 01:30:22.270
you do not feel it. Your heart is beating so

01:30:22.270 --> 01:30:25.270
fast that you do not feel anything but the strange

01:30:25.270 --> 01:30:29.530
mixture of fear and anger. You move quietly.

01:30:30.610 --> 01:30:33.710
You're back to the wall. The light switch is not

01:30:33.710 --> 01:30:36.430
near your door but halfway to the stairs.

01:30:36.430 --> 01:30:40.850
The door to the spare room is half open. And

01:30:40.850 --> 01:30:42.750
you can hear the sound of the wind outside.

01:30:43.970 --> 01:30:46.610
You know now that the window to the spare room

01:30:46.610 --> 01:30:50.110
is open. And you know this is how the burglar

01:30:50.110 --> 01:30:50.410
entered.

01:30:51.350 --> 01:30:54.870
You take one more step to the door. Your hand

01:30:54.870 --> 01:30:56.990
is nearly on the light switch when you hear

01:30:56.990 --> 01:31:00.910
another noise from the room. Then the door begins to

01:31:00.910 --> 01:31:04.850
open slowly and quietly. You want to turn back

01:31:04.850 --> 01:31:07.110
and run to your room and hide under the blanket

01:31:07.110 --> 01:31:09.550
and be completely silent and not move.

01:31:10.610 --> 01:31:14.210
But this is your house. And you know you must

01:31:14.210 --> 01:31:18.210
stay. Then standing right in front of you in the

01:31:18.210 --> 01:31:18.510
dark

01:31:18.510 --> 01:31:22.310
you see the burglar. And he looks back at you

01:31:22.310 --> 01:31:25.810
and shouts. You turn on the lights and swing the

01:31:25.810 --> 01:31:29.690
heavy statue in his direction. But you cannot see him

01:31:29.690 --> 01:31:31.330
now because the light is so bright.

01:31:31.990 --> 01:31:35.270
You hear your new computer fall to the floor and

01:31:35.270 --> 01:31:37.630
break and the burglar shouts again.

01:31:38.630 --> 01:31:41.910
And then you can see his face. And you realize

01:31:41.910 --> 01:31:44.550
that he looks more afraid than you do.

01:31:45.330 --> 01:31:49.010
And he is stepping quickly backwards to the stairs. He

01:31:49.010 --> 01:31:53.010
is young. Just a kid. Just a stupid kid.

01:31:54.010 --> 01:31:57.370
Then you see Sophie in her normal place at the

01:31:57.370 --> 01:32:00.490
top of the stairs. And you see how near the

01:32:00.490 --> 01:32:05.450
burglaries. You only have time to shout two words. Don't

01:32:05.450 --> 01:32:07.950
move. But it is too late.

01:32:08.810 --> 01:32:15.630
And he does move. And then he falls. God is

01:32:15.630 --> 01:32:16.330
in the detail.

01:32:17.970 --> 01:32:21.890
The back streets of Dublin are quiet and the sun

01:32:21.890 --> 01:32:23.870
is slowly setting on the old city.

01:32:24.830 --> 01:32:27.890
Barry Brennan stands in the doorway of an empty shop

01:32:27.890 --> 01:32:31.630
and waits. He smokes his cigarettes continuously

01:32:32.170 --> 01:32:36.510
and enjoys the taste of each one. He enjoys another

01:32:36.510 --> 01:32:37.990
sweeter taste too.

01:32:39.130 --> 01:32:42.690
The taste of freedom. But he has to be careful.

01:32:43.490 --> 01:32:46.230
He knows that. The garden are everywhere.

01:32:47.230 --> 01:32:49.770
And they are looking for him. And if he wants

01:32:49.770 --> 01:32:52.630
to keep his freedom he has to be clever.

01:32:53.430 --> 01:32:56.790
He has to be patient. And so he watches the

01:32:56.790 --> 01:32:59.790
street. And the small red brick houses.

01:33:00.790 --> 01:33:05.790
Most importantly though he watches the church. His own parish

01:33:05.790 --> 01:33:08.790
church. The church of his childhood.

01:33:09.730 --> 01:33:14.030
St. Anthony's. How long ago was his last visit to

01:33:14.030 --> 01:33:18.070
this cold stone building? More than 20 years?

01:33:18.910 --> 01:33:23.990
Well that's not important at the moment. No. The only

01:33:23.990 --> 01:33:26.210
thing that's important is something that the

01:33:26.210 --> 01:33:29.550
church can offer him right now. The one thing he

01:33:29.550 --> 01:33:31.970
needs if he wants to keep his freedom and get

01:33:31.970 --> 01:33:36.290
the suitcase that's buried in his brother's old garage. The

01:33:36.290 --> 01:33:38.230
suitcase that can help him escape

01:33:38.230 --> 01:33:41.130
the country and live the rest of his life on

01:33:41.130 --> 01:33:44.790
a tropical island in the Bahamas. Sanctuary.

01:33:45.590 --> 01:33:50.670
And so he waits. And the evening becomes darker. And

01:33:50.670 --> 01:33:52.650
he thinks that there are now only one or two

01:33:52.650 --> 01:33:56.850
people left in the small old church. He decides that

01:33:56.850 --> 01:34:00.030
it's time. He pulls the collar of his stolen

01:34:00.030 --> 01:34:03.690
coat up to cover his face. And he checks that

01:34:03.690 --> 01:34:06.790
no one can see the grey prison uniform that he's

01:34:06.790 --> 01:34:11.390
still wearing beneath it. He finishes his last cigarette and

01:34:11.390 --> 01:34:14.350
stops to listen. In the distance

01:34:14.350 --> 01:34:17.070
he can hear the siren of a gardy car in

01:34:17.070 --> 01:34:20.230
the city centre. But he's sure it's not for him.

01:34:21.050 --> 01:34:25.270
So he crosses the road slowly and casually. Walks up

01:34:25.270 --> 01:34:27.290
the stone steps of the church and looks

01:34:27.290 --> 01:34:30.930
around once more before he pushes open the wooden doors

01:34:30.930 --> 01:34:34.230
and goes inside. St. Anthony's.

01:34:34.930 --> 01:34:39.390
It smells no different he thinks as he enters. And

01:34:39.390 --> 01:34:43.410
it looks identical too. The same cold grey

01:34:43.410 --> 01:34:48.730
walls. The same uncomfortable heavy pews. And the same weak

01:34:48.730 --> 01:34:51.130
candles to light up the dark room.

01:34:52.210 --> 01:34:56.550
He was right. There are a few people inside. Two

01:34:56.550 --> 01:34:58.770
women sitting together on the front pew.

01:34:59.310 --> 01:35:03.530
Their eyes closed and heads down. And an old man

01:35:03.530 --> 01:35:06.150
who looks at Barry for a moment before returning

01:35:06.150 --> 01:35:09.410
to his prayers. But not one of them is interested

01:35:09.410 --> 01:35:14.550
in him. Good. Barry thinks. The place is practically

01:35:14.550 --> 01:35:17.970
empty. He looks to the right wall and sees what

01:35:17.970 --> 01:35:21.290
he's looking for. A large wooden box with two

01:35:21.290 --> 01:35:25.730
doors. Quietly he walks past the pews and stops near

01:35:25.730 --> 01:35:29.250
the box. He pauses for a moment to try and

01:35:29.250 --> 01:35:32.490
remember what he has to do next. But then the

01:35:32.490 --> 01:35:35.770
door to the church opens again and three women enter.

01:35:36.490 --> 01:35:38.950
As he does not want them to see his face

01:35:38.950 --> 01:35:41.530
he pulls open the left door to the box and

01:35:41.530 --> 01:35:41.930
enters.

01:35:43.410 --> 01:35:47.290
A confessional. As soon as he's inside he hates it.

01:35:47.990 --> 01:35:51.270
It's small, so small and it reminds him of his

01:35:51.270 --> 01:35:57.490
prison cell back in the joy. Father. He says. But

01:35:57.490 --> 01:36:06.130
there is no reply and he can see no movement

01:36:06.130 --> 01:36:09.490
self comfortable on the small chair. But after a few

01:36:09.490 --> 01:36:11.930
minutes he realizes how tired he is.

01:36:12.470 --> 01:36:14.690
And he thinks that maybe he can close his eyes

01:36:14.690 --> 01:36:17.570
for a moment and even rest his head against the

01:36:17.570 --> 01:36:23.250
grill. But he mustn't sleep. He tells himself. He mustn't.

01:36:24.070 --> 01:36:26.950
But he does. And he dreams of the

01:36:26.950 --> 01:36:31.230
suitcase buried under his brother's old garage. And he dreams

01:36:31.230 --> 01:36:33.390
of the money inside and the

01:36:33.390 --> 01:36:36.370
paradise in the Bahamas. Hello?

01:36:37.350 --> 01:36:40.950
Says a voice. And Barry wakes up and looks around

01:36:40.950 --> 01:36:42.290
in confusion and fear.

01:36:43.350 --> 01:36:48.310
Is there someone there? Says the voice. Barry remembers where

01:36:48.310 --> 01:36:48.810
he is.

01:36:49.470 --> 01:36:53.570
Yes, I'm here. He says. And for a moment there

01:36:53.570 --> 01:36:56.110
is silence before he remembers what to say.

01:36:56.710 --> 01:37:00.410
Bless me, Father, for I have sinned. And again there

01:37:00.410 --> 01:37:03.830
is a long silence. Barry tries to see

01:37:03.830 --> 01:37:06.690
the face through the grill. But there is only a

01:37:06.690 --> 01:37:09.830
dark shape. Finally, the voice replies.

01:37:11.270 --> 01:37:16.530
I see. Go on. First, Father, I need to know

01:37:16.530 --> 01:37:20.070
something. I need to know that anything I say here

01:37:20.070 --> 01:37:20.450
is not

01:37:20.450 --> 01:37:23.550
to be repeated. That's how this works, isn't it?

01:37:24.670 --> 01:37:31.290
That is true. My son. The voice says. And Barry

01:37:31.290 --> 01:37:33.790
thinks that it's a calm and honest voice.

01:37:34.970 --> 01:37:38.750
Is that Father O'Connor? He asks, remembering his old

01:37:38.750 --> 01:37:40.890
priest. O'Connor?

01:37:42.190 --> 01:37:47.030
No, son. My name is Keen. I believe Father O

01:37:47.030 --> 01:37:49.690
'Connor passed away nearly ten years ago.

01:37:50.610 --> 01:37:54.710
Barry nods in the dark space. But does it matter

01:37:54.710 --> 01:37:57.830
that you're not my priest? Can you still listen?

01:37:58.770 --> 01:38:03.790
Any man can listen, says the quiet voice. But can

01:38:03.790 --> 01:38:05.530
you promise not to tell anyone?

01:38:06.310 --> 01:38:10.930
I promise, my son. I will not tell a soul.

01:38:11.950 --> 01:38:14.750
And Barry nods again and feels ready to speak.

01:38:15.630 --> 01:38:19.130
Father, I need to ask for something from you. I

01:38:19.130 --> 01:38:20.290
need to ask for sanctuary.

01:38:21.370 --> 01:38:25.470
Sanctuary? Yes, Father. I need somewhere to hide for a

01:38:25.470 --> 01:38:28.210
few days, a week maybe. Can you do that?

01:38:28.790 --> 01:38:31.690
Can you help me hide here in the church? There

01:38:31.690 --> 01:38:32.510
is another silence.

01:38:33.890 --> 01:38:38.770
Maybe. But why, my son? I can only help you

01:38:38.770 --> 01:38:39.750
if you tell me why.

01:38:40.770 --> 01:38:44.750
God, you see, is in the detail. If you want

01:38:44.750 --> 01:38:47.090
to confess and receive God's forgiveness,

01:38:47.990 --> 01:38:52.810
you must tell me everything. Okay, Father. But remember, you

01:38:52.810 --> 01:38:54.010
promise not to tell a soul?

01:38:55.210 --> 01:39:01.570
I do. Barry nods. My name is Barry Brennan. Do

01:39:01.570 --> 01:39:03.890
you know the name? Another pause.

01:39:03.890 --> 01:39:09.270
I do, my son. It's on every radio and every

01:39:09.270 --> 01:39:12.930
television. You are the prisoner, the one that

01:39:12.930 --> 01:39:17.470
escaped from Mount Joy Prison. My son, you should let

01:39:17.470 --> 01:39:21.010
me take you to the guards. No, Barry shouts.

01:39:21.910 --> 01:39:25.930
You promised, Father. No one can know. Then you must

01:39:25.930 --> 01:39:26.850
tell me everything.

01:39:26.850 --> 01:39:31.830
Everything. There's not much to tell. I escaped from the

01:39:31.830 --> 01:39:33.310
guardie van that was taking me to

01:39:33.310 --> 01:39:35.670
hospital. I told him I had a pain in my

01:39:35.670 --> 01:39:37.870
side and the doctors thought it was my appendix.

01:39:38.790 --> 01:39:41.230
When I was in the van, it stopped and I

01:39:41.230 --> 01:39:43.590
hit one of the guards, took his keys and ran.

01:39:44.630 --> 01:39:48.990
That was two days ago. Well, God will judge you

01:39:48.990 --> 01:39:50.170
for this, my son.

01:39:51.430 --> 01:39:53.930
But tell me, why did you stay in the city?

01:39:54.550 --> 01:39:56.030
Why not run for the countryside?

01:39:56.850 --> 01:40:00.510
Or hop on a ferry out of here? Well, Father,

01:40:00.790 --> 01:40:05.210
there's something I need to get before I can go.

01:40:05.990 --> 01:40:09.570
And that's why I'm here. I need to wait for

01:40:09.570 --> 01:40:11.930
a few days until they think I'm miles from the

01:40:11.930 --> 01:40:12.170
city.

01:40:13.170 --> 01:40:16.330
Then I can get this thing and I can go.

01:40:17.130 --> 01:40:20.930
And I promise, Father, after this, I will never commit

01:40:20.930 --> 01:40:25.050
another crime again. I will lead a quiet and honest

01:40:25.050 --> 01:40:29.050
life. And Barry imagines the beaches of the

01:40:29.050 --> 01:40:34.930
Bahamas. I see, says the voice, I want to help

01:40:34.930 --> 01:40:37.710
you. And if you confess all your sins to me,

01:40:37.870 --> 01:40:41.690
then maybe I can. But, like I say, God is

01:40:41.690 --> 01:40:45.450
in the detail. What is this thing you need?

01:40:46.750 --> 01:40:52.190
Barry hesitates. He thinks about lying, but why? The priest

01:40:52.190 --> 01:40:54.010
promises not to tell a soul.

01:40:55.330 --> 01:40:59.110
It's a suitcase, Father, and inside there is half a

01:40:59.110 --> 01:41:02.310
million euros. And yes, it is stolen,

01:41:02.690 --> 01:41:06.070
but I promise, Father, no one needed now. I stole

01:41:06.070 --> 01:41:08.170
it more than eight years ago from a bank

01:41:08.170 --> 01:41:11.770
security van, a bank, Father, and they have insurance and

01:41:11.770 --> 01:41:13.070
all that, so they don't need it.

01:41:13.070 --> 01:41:16.810
No one needs it now, apart from me. And this

01:41:16.810 --> 01:41:19.250
time the silence is heavy and tense.

01:41:20.450 --> 01:41:22.790
And Barry can hear the voices of the women as

01:41:22.790 --> 01:41:25.570
they leave the church. He wonders if there

01:41:25.570 --> 01:41:28.910
are still any people there. But he thinks there are

01:41:28.910 --> 01:41:29.150
not.

01:41:31.010 --> 01:41:36.470
Well, says the quiet voice. I understand, my son. And

01:41:36.470 --> 01:41:37.450
I will help you.

01:41:38.150 --> 01:41:40.390
I can let you sleep here for a few days,

01:41:40.770 --> 01:41:42.050
and I can bring you some food.

01:41:42.850 --> 01:41:46.830
Oh, Father, thank you, Father. But, like I say, God

01:41:46.830 --> 01:41:47.830
is in the detail.

01:41:48.830 --> 01:41:56.230
Where exactly is this suitcase? What? Why? Why? Because I

01:41:56.230 --> 01:41:58.170
need to know that you aren't going to

01:41:58.170 --> 01:42:03.030
hurt anyone to get it. The voice says seriously. Barry

01:42:03.030 --> 01:42:05.610
loves. Oh, no, Father, I promise.

01:42:05.610 --> 01:42:08.570
It's in an old garage of my brother. On a

01:42:08.570 --> 01:42:11.250
bit of land next to the house road. I can

01:42:11.250 --> 01:42:11.690
go at night,

01:42:12.070 --> 01:42:15.370
dig up the concrete, and get it no problem. Well,

01:42:15.550 --> 01:42:18.010
I tell you what, you wait here.

01:42:18.830 --> 01:42:22.090
I'm going to close the church. Then maybe I can

01:42:22.090 --> 01:42:24.310
find you that bit of food and some other clothes.

01:42:25.330 --> 01:42:28.170
And for the first time in two days, Barry Brennan

01:42:28.170 --> 01:42:32.350
feels relief. He can really taste the freedom now.

01:42:33.130 --> 01:42:35.330
Ah, thank you, Father. Thank you.

01:42:35.930 --> 01:42:38.370
You know, I'm sure there's a bit of spare money

01:42:38.370 --> 01:42:40.570
for the church. 3,000 maybe.

01:42:41.110 --> 01:42:44.470
What do you think? But there is no answer. There

01:42:44.470 --> 01:42:48.230
is, however, a strange noise. Something moving

01:42:48.230 --> 01:42:53.790
against the door of the confessional. Something heavy. Something like

01:42:53.790 --> 01:42:55.310
one of the heavy pews.

01:42:55.950 --> 01:42:59.590
And Barry tries to push the door open. But he

01:42:59.590 --> 01:43:02.970
cannot. And before Barry Brennan begins to

01:43:02.970 --> 01:43:06.550
shout and scream to the empty church, he hears the

01:43:06.550 --> 01:43:08.370
soft voice one more time.

01:43:09.310 --> 01:43:12.670
Now, Son, I told you that any man can listen,

01:43:12.910 --> 01:43:16.230
didn't I? It says. And I also told you that

01:43:16.230 --> 01:43:16.510
God

01:43:16.510 --> 01:43:20.730
is in the detail. And an important detail, a very

01:43:20.730 --> 01:43:24.350
important detail. Is that you're in the wrong

01:43:24.350 --> 01:43:28.250
side of the confessional? I just stopped in to confess

01:43:28.250 --> 01:43:30.210
about stealing another bottle of whiskey

01:43:30.210 --> 01:43:33.550
from the shop. But you know, I think I can

01:43:33.550 --> 01:43:36.750
do that next time. Yes, I think I might have

01:43:36.750 --> 01:43:37.370
a lot more

01:43:37.370 --> 01:43:42.650
to confess tomorrow. No, you did say howth road. And

01:43:42.650 --> 01:43:45.310
then there is only the sound of Barry Brennan's

01:43:45.310 --> 01:43:48.650
shouts. And there is no one in the church to

01:43:48.650 --> 01:43:52.870
hear those. Well, apart from God, I suppose.

01:43:55.830 --> 01:44:02.050
Route 66. The car is big and old, but it's

01:44:02.050 --> 01:44:05.590
a classic. And it moves along the road like a

01:44:05.590 --> 01:44:05.850
shark,

01:44:06.930 --> 01:44:11.190
the evening sun reflecting off the red paint. The roof

01:44:11.190 --> 01:44:15.270
is down. And Dan enjoys the feeling of the

01:44:15.270 --> 01:44:18.970
wind in his hair. It calls him and helps him

01:44:18.970 --> 01:44:24.010
to stay awake. He's tired, very tired, and he still

01:44:24.010 --> 01:44:27.190
feels sick from the beer and whiskey of last night.

01:44:28.090 --> 01:44:32.090
Soon he can stop, find a quiet area off the

01:44:32.090 --> 01:44:32.350
road

01:44:32.350 --> 01:44:36.170
and push back the chair and sleep. But not yet.

01:44:37.170 --> 01:44:40.030
The Mojave desert is still all around him with

01:44:40.030 --> 01:44:45.030
its flat orange sands and dead bushes. The plan was

01:44:45.030 --> 01:44:47.730
to get to Flagstaff, but it's too many miles

01:44:47.730 --> 01:44:51.370
away. So instead he just wants to get as far

01:44:51.370 --> 01:44:54.590
from the town called Needles as he can before the

01:44:54.590 --> 01:44:54.770
night

01:44:54.770 --> 01:45:02.090
comes. Needles. He hates that town. And that girl. He

01:45:02.090 --> 01:45:04.230
looks at his right hand on the steering wheel.

01:45:04.810 --> 01:45:09.130
The skin is raw, and he tries to remember exactly

01:45:09.130 --> 01:45:13.550
what happened last night, but he cannot. And maybe

01:45:13.550 --> 01:45:19.330
he should not. Stupid girl. But anyway, why think about

01:45:19.330 --> 01:45:23.350
it? Just drive, get a few more miles from the

01:45:23.350 --> 01:45:23.650
town

01:45:23.650 --> 01:45:27.290
and from her. He hits the button for the radio,

01:45:27.950 --> 01:45:30.830
and an old song fills the silence of the desert.

01:45:30.830 --> 01:45:35.930
A good song, he thinks. A real song. All guitars

01:45:35.930 --> 01:45:39.510
and rock and roll. He feels a little better.

01:45:40.410 --> 01:45:42.770
Maybe it's time for the first drink of the day

01:45:42.770 --> 01:45:46.150
after all, and he takes the small flask from the

01:45:46.150 --> 01:45:50.030
pocket of his denim jacket, removes the lid, and swallows.

01:45:50.730 --> 01:45:53.250
For a second, the taste is foul.

01:45:54.030 --> 01:45:58.310
A horrible reminder of last night, of the girl and

01:45:58.310 --> 01:46:01.370
of the hotel room. But then the hot whiskey

01:46:01.370 --> 01:46:05.390
starts to fill him, and he smiles, puts his head

01:46:05.390 --> 01:46:07.750
back and laughs loudly into the desert.

01:46:08.490 --> 01:46:12.750
Route 66! He shouts, and he turns the volume of

01:46:12.750 --> 01:46:15.810
the radio up. He can forget about last night,

01:46:16.210 --> 01:46:19.610
about the girl. His shirt has a little blood on

01:46:19.610 --> 01:46:22.590
it, and his hand is sore. But he can get

01:46:22.590 --> 01:46:22.910
a new

01:46:22.910 --> 01:46:26.790
shirt, and the whiskey will help the pain. No, this

01:46:26.790 --> 01:46:29.510
is his holiday, his escape from all those

01:46:29.510 --> 01:46:34.090
idiots back in California. Forget needles and forget the girl.

01:46:34.930 --> 01:46:37.090
Just relax and enjoy it.

01:46:37.790 --> 01:46:40.530
She was not the first girl, and he knows she

01:46:40.530 --> 01:46:43.730
will not be the last. Maybe there's one waiting for

01:46:43.730 --> 01:46:47.710
him in Flagstaff, and this one, he hopes, will have

01:46:47.710 --> 01:46:50.610
a little more respect for him and won't laugh at

01:46:50.610 --> 01:46:54.870
him. So he drives, and for a while he feels

01:46:54.870 --> 01:46:57.970
better. The sun is lower in the sky now.

01:46:58.510 --> 01:47:01.030
It's a little less hot, and the radio keeps him

01:47:01.030 --> 01:47:03.710
company with old songs about love and women,

01:47:04.270 --> 01:47:09.130
rock and roll and country music, real music. But then

01:47:09.130 --> 01:47:12.330
the songs stop, and the news report starts.

01:47:13.230 --> 01:47:17.310
There's something about needles, something about trouble on Route 66,

01:47:18.070 --> 01:47:19.110
and he tries to listen,

01:47:19.110 --> 01:47:23.610
but the signal is weak. A young, dead, the police

01:47:23.610 --> 01:47:25.910
are looking, a man, probably alone,

01:47:26.190 --> 01:47:30.210
and thought to be extremely dangerous, any information call, and

01:47:30.210 --> 01:47:31.190
then the signal fails,

01:47:31.850 --> 01:47:33.950
and there is only the sound of the old classic

01:47:33.950 --> 01:47:35.750
engine and the silence of the desert.

01:47:37.470 --> 01:47:41.010
Dead? No, no, it can't be her. He looks at

01:47:41.010 --> 01:47:43.190
his hand again and tries to make a fist,

01:47:43.810 --> 01:47:47.270
but it hurts. And he thinks of the white shirt

01:47:47.270 --> 01:47:50.470
in the trunk of the car, the white shirt with

01:47:50.470 --> 01:47:50.810
blood

01:47:50.810 --> 01:47:55.010
on it. What did he do last night? He tries

01:47:55.010 --> 01:47:58.890
to remember, he tries to remember exactly what happened.

01:47:59.630 --> 01:48:03.330
He remembers the bar clearly, he remembers buying her a

01:48:03.330 --> 01:48:05.690
drink, and then another, and another.

01:48:06.350 --> 01:48:09.230
He remembers that afterwards they were in the hotel room,

01:48:09.510 --> 01:48:11.710
kissing. But then something happened,

01:48:11.710 --> 01:48:15.630
and she laughed. She laughed at him, but he cannot

01:48:15.630 --> 01:48:18.170
remember why. It was something stupid,

01:48:18.710 --> 01:48:22.970
something he said or did. And then? But the rest

01:48:22.970 --> 01:48:24.290
is impossible to remember.

01:48:25.190 --> 01:48:27.490
He woke up late in the hotel room and was

01:48:27.490 --> 01:48:30.950
alone. He saw the blood, but there was only a

01:48:30.950 --> 01:48:31.210
little,

01:48:31.530 --> 01:48:37.370
and his hand hurt. And he knew. Yeah, he could

01:48:37.370 --> 01:48:39.470
not remember, but he knew.

01:48:40.290 --> 01:48:42.690
And he thinks of all the times he watched his

01:48:42.690 --> 01:48:44.090
father hit his mother.

01:48:44.870 --> 01:48:48.810
Jesus! He says, and he does not feel tired anymore.

01:48:49.770 --> 01:48:51.350
He puts his foot on the accelerator,

01:48:51.350 --> 01:48:54.470
and the car starts to speed along the old road.

01:48:55.430 --> 01:48:58.050
Forget sleeping. Forget Flagstaff.

01:48:58.850 --> 01:49:02.030
He needs to find another route and a motel to

01:49:02.030 --> 01:49:03.210
stay in for a few days.

01:49:03.210 --> 01:49:06.710
A cheap motel, where they only want a name and

01:49:06.710 --> 01:49:09.750
some cash. The sun is almost down now.

01:49:10.310 --> 01:49:13.570
The sky a deep orange and red. And the road

01:49:13.570 --> 01:49:17.610
is empty. Or it is until he speeds past the

01:49:17.610 --> 01:49:17.890
large

01:49:17.890 --> 01:49:22.950
billboard. Then suddenly the road is not empty. There is

01:49:22.950 --> 01:49:26.250
a car behind him. Its red and blue lights

01:49:26.250 --> 01:49:29.850
fill the evening. And the sound of the siren fills

01:49:29.850 --> 01:49:30.510
his ears.

01:49:31.490 --> 01:49:35.210
No! He groans as he sees it in the mirror.

01:49:36.110 --> 01:49:38.490
And he thinks for a moment about not stopping.

01:49:39.370 --> 01:49:43.390
But there is nowhere for him to go. Jesus, just

01:49:43.390 --> 01:49:45.410
stay cool down, just stay cool.

01:49:46.050 --> 01:49:48.430
He tries to tell himself as the red car slows

01:49:48.430 --> 01:49:51.870
down. So he stops on the edge of the desert,

01:49:52.670 --> 01:49:55.270
hides the flask of whiskey under the seat and lights

01:49:55.270 --> 01:49:57.070
a cigarette to cover the smell.

01:49:57.730 --> 01:50:01.510
God, he wishes he could remember last night. Not just

01:50:01.510 --> 01:50:03.670
the girl's expression when he hit her.

01:50:04.370 --> 01:50:07.690
But everything. In the mirror he sees the cop car

01:50:07.690 --> 01:50:08.870
park behind him,

01:50:09.270 --> 01:50:12.690
and he watches a young tall cop get out. Just

01:50:12.690 --> 01:50:16.230
one. Good. If things get serious then maybe he

01:50:16.230 --> 01:50:19.830
can manage if there's just one. He watches the cop

01:50:19.830 --> 01:50:21.310
walk slowly to the car.

01:50:22.310 --> 01:50:26.510
The guy's eyes are covered by silver sunglasses. And there's

01:50:26.510 --> 01:50:28.370
something strange about his uniform.

01:50:29.330 --> 01:50:32.990
Dan thinks. But before he can decide what, the cop

01:50:32.990 --> 01:50:35.390
is at the door and Dan drops his cigarette.

01:50:36.130 --> 01:50:40.490
Evening officer, he says, and tries to look sorry. I

01:50:40.490 --> 01:50:41.710
know I was going a little too fast,

01:50:41.710 --> 01:50:45.590
I'm sorry. The cop looks at him and nods, but

01:50:45.590 --> 01:50:49.110
says nothing. Dan wants to see the eyes behind

01:50:49.110 --> 01:50:54.190
the glasses, but cannot. I suppose it's this road. The

01:50:54.190 --> 01:50:56.130
desert makes it easy to forget to

01:50:56.130 --> 01:50:58.890
watch your speed. He says, and he thinks he sees

01:50:58.890 --> 01:51:02.990
the cop look at his hand. Jesus. Is this it?

01:51:03.750 --> 01:51:07.170
Did he really do something to that girl? More than

01:51:07.170 --> 01:51:07.810
hit her once.

01:51:08.530 --> 01:51:11.550
Did he do what they said on the radio? Was

01:51:11.550 --> 01:51:12.050
she dead?

01:51:13.590 --> 01:51:18.290
Yep, the cop says. These roads are funny like that.

01:51:19.090 --> 01:51:21.290
Lots of people have problems out here.

01:51:22.210 --> 01:51:28.670
This is a nice car. A classic. Yours? And his

01:51:28.670 --> 01:51:32.510
voice is slow. Yes sir, I have my license here

01:51:32.510 --> 01:51:32.670
in

01:51:32.670 --> 01:51:35.950
the registration. The cop nods, but does not take them.

01:51:36.770 --> 01:51:38.670
I need to ask you to get out of the

01:51:38.670 --> 01:51:38.930
car.

01:51:39.790 --> 01:51:44.070
Dan tries to smile. Is there a problem officer? And

01:51:44.070 --> 01:51:45.890
he looks at the gun on the cop's belt.

01:51:46.610 --> 01:51:48.590
If he can get the gun, then he can escape.

01:51:49.550 --> 01:51:53.510
Forget California, go north to Canada or Alaska.

01:51:54.530 --> 01:51:58.070
But he waits. Maybe this is something else, a routine

01:51:58.070 --> 01:51:59.530
check, a formality.

01:52:00.230 --> 01:52:04.650
Be cool, Dan. He tells himself. Just get out of

01:52:04.650 --> 01:52:07.290
the car, please. The cop repeats.

01:52:08.370 --> 01:52:12.670
Dan nods and gets out. And he thinks again that

01:52:12.670 --> 01:52:15.150
there is something strange about the cop's uniform.

01:52:16.330 --> 01:52:19.790
It's small. Too small for a tall man like him.

01:52:20.970 --> 01:52:23.230
I need to see in the trunk of the car,

01:52:23.490 --> 01:52:23.670
sir.

01:52:24.770 --> 01:52:29.210
Jesus. The shirt. The shirt is in the trunk. Is

01:52:29.210 --> 01:52:32.670
that what he wants? The trunk? Can I ask why?

01:52:33.550 --> 01:52:39.870
Just routine. Just routine. Maybe it is. And the shirt

01:52:39.870 --> 01:52:42.110
is in his bag at the bottom where it cannot

01:52:42.110 --> 01:52:42.610
be seen.

01:52:43.430 --> 01:52:47.730
Okay? He walks around to the trunk. The cop behind

01:52:47.730 --> 01:52:50.530
him. And he pushes the button.

01:52:51.150 --> 01:52:54.810
For a moment, he does nothing. He remembers the baseball

01:52:54.810 --> 01:52:57.810
bat he keeps in there. If the cop asks

01:52:57.810 --> 01:53:00.450
to look in his bag, he can reach in, grab

01:53:00.450 --> 01:53:03.370
the bat and take a swing. Maybe it can work.

01:53:04.990 --> 01:53:10.950
Sir? The cop says. Sure. And Dan starts to lift

01:53:10.950 --> 01:53:14.050
the lid of the trunk. But in the reflection of

01:53:14.050 --> 01:53:17.530
the red paint, he sees the cop raise his hand.

01:53:18.450 --> 01:53:21.370
And in the soft evening light, he sees the knife.

01:53:22.330 --> 01:53:25.750
And for a moment, he does not understand. But then

01:53:25.750 --> 01:53:28.510
he moves. He is almost quick enough.

01:53:29.350 --> 01:53:31.970
But the knife still cuts him and he screams and

01:53:31.970 --> 01:53:35.150
falls to the floor. The cop falls too and there

01:53:35.150 --> 01:53:38.770
is a moment of confusion. But then Dan pushes himself

01:53:38.770 --> 01:53:42.130
up onto his feet and runs. He sees the

01:53:42.130 --> 01:53:44.410
cop car and runs to it and pulls open the

01:53:44.410 --> 01:53:47.190
door. That's when he sees the bodies.

01:53:48.190 --> 01:53:51.570
One is clearly a police woman. But the other, a

01:53:51.570 --> 01:53:53.170
short man, has no uniform.

01:53:54.210 --> 01:53:58.350
Jesus! He screams and he remembers the news story on

01:53:58.350 --> 01:53:58.710
the radio.

01:53:59.750 --> 01:54:03.850
A young, dead, the police are looking a man, probably

01:54:03.850 --> 01:54:06.090
alone and thought to be extremely dangerous.

01:54:06.090 --> 01:54:10.210
Any information, call. And he starts to run again, not

01:54:10.210 --> 01:54:11.870
on the road now, but into the desert.

01:54:12.710 --> 01:54:14.890
He wants to turn to look back to see if

01:54:14.890 --> 01:54:17.290
the man is following him. But he does not dare.

01:54:18.050 --> 01:54:20.570
He thinks that if he keeps running, he can escape

01:54:20.570 --> 01:54:23.450
and find help. Find the real police.

01:54:24.390 --> 01:54:27.830
But the sun is gone now and darkness is all

01:54:27.830 --> 01:54:30.790
around him. Now everything from last night

01:54:30.790 --> 01:54:34.590
is coming back to him. He remembers hitting the girl.

01:54:35.170 --> 01:54:36.790
He remembers her shouting at him

01:54:36.790 --> 01:54:40.390
and he remembers telling her to get out. And he

01:54:40.390 --> 01:54:43.070
remembers the last thing she said before she

01:54:43.070 --> 01:54:45.010
closed the door to the hotel room.

01:54:45.790 --> 01:54:49.430
I hope you die and rot in the desert, she

01:54:49.430 --> 01:54:51.730
shouted, blood still on her face.

01:54:52.530 --> 01:54:56.410
And he almost laughs in disbelief. But then he hears

01:54:56.410 --> 01:54:59.230
someone running behind him and he screams

01:54:59.230 --> 01:55:00.070
instead.

01:55:01.950 --> 01:55:02.690
The Fall

01:55:04.930 --> 01:55:08.190
Brandon tries not to think as he walks through the

01:55:08.190 --> 01:55:10.010
snow that reaches up to his waist.

01:55:11.210 --> 01:55:15.270
He is confused and weak. He tries not to remember

01:55:15.270 --> 01:55:17.670
the expression on Greg's face as the

01:55:17.670 --> 01:55:21.150
bullet hit him in the back. You said it was

01:55:21.150 --> 01:55:25.070
easy. Brandon calls out into the forest of

01:55:25.070 --> 01:55:29.230
silent trees that surround him, his voice full of emotion.

01:55:30.310 --> 01:55:32.010
You said no one could get hurt.

01:55:33.010 --> 01:55:37.330
But someone did get hurt. And now Brandon is alone

01:55:37.330 --> 01:55:40.030
and he feels tired and lost.

01:55:41.090 --> 01:55:43.150
And he knows that the man in the dark winter

01:55:43.150 --> 01:55:45.010
coat and black hat is near.

01:55:45.890 --> 01:55:48.650
And he thinks that the next bullet is for him.

01:55:49.370 --> 01:55:51.890
He tries to move faster through the snow,

01:55:52.390 --> 01:55:57.210
but it's so deep. And it is so cold. His

01:55:57.210 --> 01:55:59.550
clothes are wet and his skin frozen.

01:56:00.630 --> 01:56:02.690
He wants to put his hand in his coat pocket,

01:56:03.190 --> 01:56:05.170
but he has to keep the grey pistol ready.

01:56:06.130 --> 01:56:09.970
He remembers the way that Greg fell. One moment they

01:56:09.970 --> 01:56:12.050
were running, the next there was the sound

01:56:12.050 --> 01:56:15.170
of the gun and a scream. Then Greg was on

01:56:15.170 --> 01:56:18.550
the floor. Brandon wanted to stop and help him.

01:56:18.550 --> 01:56:22.290
But Greg told him to run, to escape and to

01:56:22.290 --> 01:56:23.870
not say anything to anyone.

01:56:24.990 --> 01:56:28.230
And then Brandon heard another gunshot, so he ran and

01:56:28.230 --> 01:56:30.710
left his brother in the snow to die alone.

01:56:31.650 --> 01:56:35.690
You said it was easy. He shouts again and recalls

01:56:35.690 --> 01:56:38.230
the first time his brother had told him about

01:56:38.230 --> 01:56:42.110
the plan. Listen to me. His brother said at a

01:56:42.110 --> 01:56:44.830
dark table in the corner at the lake Louise Inn.

01:56:45.590 --> 01:56:49.490
It's easy, Bran. I know exactly what to do. Brandon

01:56:49.490 --> 01:56:50.590
put his beer down.

01:56:51.330 --> 01:56:53.790
But a kid, Greg. I don't want to hurt a

01:56:53.790 --> 01:56:54.050
kid.

01:56:55.470 --> 01:56:59.350
What? His brother said, his eyes full of anger. You

01:56:59.350 --> 01:56:59.990
think I do?

01:57:00.750 --> 01:57:04.270
Idiot, we won't hurt anyone. We just take the kid

01:57:04.270 --> 01:57:04.790
in the truck.

01:57:05.650 --> 01:57:08.630
Then we phone the hotel. We tell them to tell

01:57:08.630 --> 01:57:10.790
the parents they can have the kid when they leave

01:57:10.790 --> 01:57:14.290
us the money. It's easy. No one can get hurt.

01:57:15.010 --> 01:57:16.590
But Brandon was not so sure.

01:57:17.330 --> 01:57:20.430
He knew his brother was a criminal. He knew that

01:57:20.430 --> 01:57:23.410
he brewed illegal beer to sell and that he drove

01:57:23.410 --> 01:57:27.930
drugs across Alberta and British Columbia. But Brandon did not

01:57:27.930 --> 01:57:30.530
do that. He did not do any of that.

01:57:31.310 --> 01:57:35.030
He worked in the lumberyard. And he tried to do

01:57:35.030 --> 01:57:38.450
things right. He tried to be better than that.

01:57:39.150 --> 01:57:39.670
But no.

01:57:40.990 --> 01:57:45.110
Brandon, his brother, said, I know you need the money.

01:57:45.650 --> 01:57:47.430
You don't have a job. Your truck is in

01:57:47.430 --> 01:57:51.570
pieces. You can't find work if you can't drive. What

01:57:51.570 --> 01:57:54.330
does Sally say? Brandon shook his head.

01:57:55.330 --> 01:57:59.650
Sally left me last month. He said, and he called

01:57:59.650 --> 01:58:01.030
the waiter for another beer.

01:58:01.770 --> 01:58:04.830
Tell me again. Tell me everything again.

01:58:04.830 --> 01:58:08.330
Now alone in the forest, he thinks he can hear

01:58:08.330 --> 01:58:10.750
the sound of feet in the snow behind him.

01:58:11.410 --> 01:58:14.910
And he tries to move faster. There is another sound

01:58:14.910 --> 01:58:18.930
too. A sound that he recognises. A sound

01:58:18.930 --> 01:58:22.790
that's getting nearer. It's like constant thunder in the distance.

01:58:23.810 --> 01:58:25.250
And he pushes through the snow

01:58:25.250 --> 01:58:27.890
and he thinks that maybe, if he can get to

01:58:27.890 --> 01:58:30.570
the sound, he can flee into the mountains and never

01:58:30.570 --> 01:58:31.150
come back.

01:58:31.950 --> 01:58:36.830
Look, every year, Greg said, hundreds of tourists come here,

01:58:36.950 --> 01:58:38.770
right? Most of them are rich.

01:58:39.590 --> 01:58:42.570
And some of them are very rich. They want to

01:58:42.570 --> 01:58:45.030
ski in the spring, hike in the summer,

01:58:45.250 --> 01:58:47.590
and spend their money in the hotel bar in the

01:58:47.590 --> 01:58:51.390
spa. Some of these people are millionaires, Brandon.

01:58:52.890 --> 01:58:56.870
Millionaires? Think about that. Greg drank some more of his

01:58:56.870 --> 01:58:58.230
beer and looked around the bar.

01:58:58.230 --> 01:59:02.310
Look at them. Their clothes are better than ours. Their

01:59:02.310 --> 01:59:03.910
cars and trucks are better.

01:59:04.510 --> 01:59:07.710
Everything they have is better. And listen, I don't hate

01:59:07.710 --> 01:59:08.910
them for that. I don't.

01:59:09.490 --> 01:59:11.690
I just know that if we ask them for a

01:59:11.690 --> 01:59:15.250
small amount, then they can pay. I mean, 20,000.

01:59:15.550 --> 01:59:15.810
No more.

01:59:16.670 --> 01:59:19.150
If you ask for more, you have to wait. And

01:59:19.150 --> 01:59:21.530
then there's the risk that they contact the police.

01:59:22.290 --> 01:59:24.390
They can get 20,000 from the bank at bank.

01:59:25.030 --> 01:59:27.230
We tell them they only have six hours.

01:59:27.910 --> 01:59:29.990
We tell them to leave the money where we say,

01:59:30.410 --> 01:59:33.290
or, or what, Greg? Or what?

01:59:34.150 --> 01:59:37.290
On that first day, Brandon said no to the plan.

01:59:38.090 --> 01:59:39.930
On the second day, he said no again.

01:59:40.990 --> 01:59:43.550
On the third day, his truck stopped on the highway.

01:59:44.430 --> 01:59:46.950
He had about 300 bucks left in the world.

01:59:48.030 --> 01:59:51.590
Sally was gone. Their cabin by the lake was cold

01:59:51.590 --> 01:59:54.470
and empty. There were no jobs for him

01:59:54.470 --> 01:59:58.370
anywhere. So on the fourth day, he said yes.

01:59:59.690 --> 02:00:03.330
The sound is louder now. Yes, it's a sound he

02:00:03.330 --> 02:00:05.850
knows. A sound he knows well.

02:00:06.750 --> 02:00:09.470
He can see nothing because of the trees, but he

02:00:09.470 --> 02:00:13.090
knows he is very near. He feels warmer now,

02:00:13.370 --> 02:00:17.150
and this scares him. In Canada, in the mountains, when

02:00:17.150 --> 02:00:20.330
you're cold, you're okay. But when you're warm,

02:00:21.090 --> 02:00:25.110
you were in trouble. What time is it now? He

02:00:25.110 --> 02:00:27.910
does not know. He only knows that it was

02:00:27.910 --> 02:00:30.630
three in the afternoon when they first heard the sound

02:00:30.630 --> 02:00:31.710
of the police sirens.

02:00:32.790 --> 02:00:35.050
We have to go. Brandon shouted.

02:00:36.110 --> 02:00:40.390
How? How can they know we're here? Said Greg. Brandon

02:00:40.390 --> 02:00:42.190
pulled him from the old deserted cabin

02:00:42.190 --> 02:00:45.390
and they ran for Greg's truck. The sound of the

02:00:45.390 --> 02:00:46.990
sirens was still in the distance,

02:00:46.990 --> 02:00:50.270
and Brandon thought that maybe they were still okay and

02:00:50.270 --> 02:00:52.850
that maybe they could leave. Maybe they

02:00:52.850 --> 02:00:57.270
could escape together. But then there was that gunshot, and

02:00:57.270 --> 02:00:59.410
the man in the dark winter coat and

02:00:59.410 --> 02:01:03.370
black hat who appeared from behind the trees. So Brandon

02:01:03.370 --> 02:01:06.610
ran, and he got to the truck and managed

02:01:06.610 --> 02:01:09.450
to drive to the road, where for a few minutes

02:01:09.450 --> 02:01:12.510
he thought he was free. But then another truck

02:01:12.510 --> 02:01:14.050
appeared on the road behind him.

02:01:15.270 --> 02:01:19.470
But which kid? Brandon asked, as they planned everything in

02:01:19.470 --> 02:01:20.130
Greg's cabin.

02:01:21.030 --> 02:01:23.470
There is a family who comes here maybe three or

02:01:23.470 --> 02:01:26.310
four times a year. The wife is a pretty little

02:01:26.310 --> 02:01:29.670
thing with red hair. I think she has family here,

02:01:29.670 --> 02:01:32.390
or maybe she comes from the area. I don't know.

02:01:33.070 --> 02:01:38.170
The husband is rich, very rich, and American. The kid

02:01:38.170 --> 02:01:41.090
looks about eleven, and they let him walk

02:01:41.090 --> 02:01:45.070
into the town from the hotel sometimes. So we watch,

02:01:45.610 --> 02:01:47.810
and we wait. When he's alone,

02:01:48.250 --> 02:01:52.890
we take him. I phone the hotel. Six hours, that's

02:01:52.890 --> 02:01:55.690
it. That's enough time for them to get the money

02:01:55.690 --> 02:01:59.130
from Banff. But not enough to do anything else like

02:01:59.130 --> 02:02:02.670
phone the cops. It's easy. So that's what

02:02:02.670 --> 02:02:05.670
they did. They took the kid as he walked into

02:02:05.670 --> 02:02:09.770
town. There was no one on the snowy road. No

02:02:09.770 --> 02:02:10.270
one saw

02:02:10.270 --> 02:02:13.670
them. But they covered Greg's plates to be sure, and

02:02:13.670 --> 02:02:16.830
they wore masks. The kids screamed at first,

02:02:17.270 --> 02:02:20.430
but they gagged him and tied his hands. Greg made

02:02:20.430 --> 02:02:22.770
the call to the hotel, and they drove to the

02:02:22.770 --> 02:02:27.030
cabin in the Yoho National Park. Then they waited. Six

02:02:27.030 --> 02:02:29.750
hours to leave them the money in a safe place.

02:02:30.610 --> 02:02:34.330
No police or the kid dies. That's what Greg told

02:02:34.330 --> 02:02:37.250
the hotel. Even if that part of it was not

02:02:37.250 --> 02:02:37.590
true.

02:02:38.150 --> 02:02:41.510
So how did it all go wrong? There are fewer

02:02:41.510 --> 02:02:45.350
trees now, and the sound is louder, much louder,

02:02:46.010 --> 02:02:50.970
like the shouting of a giant. The tachychor waterfalls. Brandon

02:02:50.970 --> 02:02:53.310
watches the clear water tumble onto the

02:02:53.310 --> 02:02:57.110
rocks, through the snow and down to the frozen forest

02:02:57.110 --> 02:03:02.670
below. Why here? He doesn't know. He tried

02:03:02.670 --> 02:03:04.810
to escape from the truck that chased him, but he

02:03:04.810 --> 02:03:07.850
crashed on the highway. The next thing he knew,

02:03:07.950 --> 02:03:10.970
he was holding his shoulder and walking confused and weak.

02:03:12.050 --> 02:03:16.430
The falls. So beautiful. Just like when

02:03:16.430 --> 02:03:19.610
he and Greg were kids. He wants to sit down

02:03:19.610 --> 02:03:22.290
to look at them, and moves closer to the edge.

02:03:23.270 --> 02:03:26.410
But no, he cannot sit down. He's sure that the

02:03:26.410 --> 02:03:28.990
man with the gun is near. So instead,

02:03:28.990 --> 02:03:33.250
he stands on the edge. He feels warm and weak,

02:03:33.970 --> 02:03:35.030
and his shoulder hurts.

02:03:36.090 --> 02:03:39.530
And he can't remember where Greg is. He said it

02:03:39.530 --> 02:03:41.550
was easy. He says.

02:03:42.830 --> 02:03:47.510
But it wasn't. A voice replies. And Brandon turns and

02:03:47.510 --> 02:03:48.710
sees the dark coat.

02:03:49.350 --> 02:03:52.690
Only this time there is no black hat. Just long

02:03:52.690 --> 02:03:55.090
red hair. And a rifle.

02:03:57.930 --> 02:04:01.410
How? How did you find us? You only had a

02:04:01.410 --> 02:04:04.910
few hours to get the money. My husband went for

02:04:04.910 --> 02:04:05.310
the money,

02:04:05.570 --> 02:04:08.510
says the woman, rifling one hand's black hat in the

02:04:08.510 --> 02:04:11.230
other. But I went to the road where you

02:04:11.230 --> 02:04:14.470
took my son. I saw the tracks from your truck.

02:04:15.410 --> 02:04:18.330
And I told the police. But I made sure I

02:04:18.330 --> 02:04:18.590
found

02:04:18.590 --> 02:04:22.470
the cabin first. I know these mountains better than they

02:04:22.470 --> 02:04:24.350
do, and better than you.

02:04:25.170 --> 02:04:31.970
I'm sorry, Brandon says. I really am sorry. The boy

02:04:31.970 --> 02:04:34.710
is okay. He's in the back room of the cabin.

02:04:35.430 --> 02:04:39.870
I know, the woman says. Are you going to shoot

02:04:39.870 --> 02:04:44.410
me? He asks. There is only the sound of the

02:04:44.410 --> 02:04:48.410
waterfall for a moment. Then the woman turns and moves

02:04:48.410 --> 02:04:51.570
back into the trees. He feels his leg

02:04:51.570 --> 02:04:55.230
shake and falls down onto the red and white snow

02:04:55.230 --> 02:05:00.130
by the waterfall. I already did. She calls back

02:05:00.130 --> 02:05:04.490
to him as she slowly disappears from sight. The old

02:05:04.490 --> 02:05:14.390
school tie. The police car stops in the

02:05:14.390 --> 02:05:18.630
detective Smith is older. His hair a mixture of black

02:05:18.630 --> 02:05:21.190
and gray, his stomach large, and his

02:05:21.190 --> 02:05:27.010
expression usually unhappy. The other detective West is younger and

02:05:27.010 --> 02:05:28.770
thinner, but with an empty

02:05:28.770 --> 02:05:33.570
look in his eye. Look at this place, says Smith.

02:05:34.470 --> 02:05:36.230
In the distance, the church towers,

02:05:36.370 --> 02:05:40.210
cathedral and university buildings of the city of Oxford are

02:05:40.210 --> 02:05:40.730
all visible.

02:05:41.570 --> 02:05:45.850
Around the old but impressive school, there are green gardens

02:05:45.850 --> 02:05:48.430
and grounds that continue for miles.

02:05:49.910 --> 02:05:52.090
And at the windows of the building, there are the

02:05:52.090 --> 02:05:54.910
thirty faces of serious young men who watch

02:05:54.910 --> 02:05:59.430
them strangely. God, what kind of kid goes to a

02:05:59.430 --> 02:06:03.570
school like this? West nods, but does not say

02:06:03.570 --> 02:06:07.810
anything. After only two weeks of working with Smith, he

02:06:07.810 --> 02:06:10.490
already knows that it's best to just

02:06:10.490 --> 02:06:15.650
nod. Come on, Smith says, and they walk to the

02:06:15.650 --> 02:06:19.750
entrance. Inside, the school smells of wood and

02:06:19.750 --> 02:06:23.170
polish, and on the walls there are antique pictures of

02:06:23.170 --> 02:06:25.310
old teachers and respected students.

02:06:26.030 --> 02:06:31.250
Not like my school. Sir? I went to a real

02:06:31.250 --> 02:06:34.650
school. A comprehensive. You?

02:06:35.490 --> 02:06:39.630
A grammar school, sir. And Smith nods his head and

02:06:39.630 --> 02:06:40.370
says nothing.

02:06:41.270 --> 02:06:45.030
The secretary outside the headmaster's room tells them they can

02:06:45.030 --> 02:06:46.730
enter, but Smith stops.

02:06:47.650 --> 02:06:51.610
Listen, West, I do the talking. You make the notes.

02:06:52.790 --> 02:06:54.770
The best thing a good detective can do

02:06:54.770 --> 02:07:01.130
is listen and observe. Write that down. Yes, sir? The

02:07:01.130 --> 02:07:03.750
headmaster is a man about the same age as Smith.

02:07:04.650 --> 02:07:10.290
But there the comparison ends. Smith looks tired, old, and

02:07:10.290 --> 02:07:10.790
unhappy.

02:07:12.030 --> 02:07:16.010
The headmaster, Mr. Bowen, does not exactly look happy, but

02:07:16.010 --> 02:07:16.770
he looks content.

02:07:17.810 --> 02:07:21.910
Content with his job, his life, his expensive house, and

02:07:21.910 --> 02:07:23.530
his two expensive cars.

02:07:24.590 --> 02:07:29.750
Smith hates him instantly. The secretary, a young and pretty

02:07:29.750 --> 02:07:32.450
blonde, enters the room and sits by the

02:07:32.450 --> 02:07:35.710
table. The headmaster tells them to sit in the same

02:07:35.710 --> 02:07:37.250
voice he uses for his students.

02:07:38.710 --> 02:07:40.910
Miss White here is to take notes and give you

02:07:40.910 --> 02:07:42.490
some more details about Mr. Fletcher.

02:07:43.550 --> 02:07:50.070
Mr. Fletcher asks Smith. Yes, Bowen stands by the large

02:07:50.070 --> 02:07:51.710
windows and does not look at them.

02:07:52.590 --> 02:07:56.610
He's why you're here, don't you know that? No, the

02:07:56.610 --> 02:07:58.330
chief inspector told us to come,

02:07:58.330 --> 02:08:02.710
but he didn't say why. Ah, yes, James. We play

02:08:02.710 --> 02:08:04.050
golf together. Good man.

02:08:04.990 --> 02:08:07.990
Well, the problem is that we can't find one of

02:08:07.990 --> 02:08:09.790
our members of staff, Mr. Fletcher.

02:08:11.090 --> 02:08:15.890
A missing person. I see. When did you last see

02:08:15.890 --> 02:08:20.830
him? Miss White? His last class was yesterday at four.

02:08:21.650 --> 02:08:24.810
He was teaching the upper sixth form boys, geometry. They

02:08:24.810 --> 02:08:26.850
say he finished class at five and left as

02:08:26.850 --> 02:08:32.790
normal. I see. Then he went home? Mr. Fletcher lives

02:08:32.790 --> 02:08:34.950
on the grounds of the school several of the

02:08:34.950 --> 02:08:38.350
older teachers do. He lives alone on the second floor

02:08:38.350 --> 02:08:40.830
in the east wing. Two other teachers live

02:08:40.830 --> 02:08:44.390
there, but neither saw him. Smith is about to speak

02:08:44.390 --> 02:08:46.690
when a loud hammering sound starts,

02:08:47.170 --> 02:08:51.430
and Bowen shakes his head. Sorry about that building work.

02:08:51.990 --> 02:08:53.510
Several areas in the school are

02:08:53.510 --> 02:08:58.490
being renovated. Smith speaks up. And did he leave the

02:08:58.490 --> 02:09:01.250
school last night? We don't know.

02:09:01.410 --> 02:09:03.910
He normally doesn't. He takes his meals in the room,

02:09:04.110 --> 02:09:05.850
but last night he didn't call for anything.

02:09:06.650 --> 02:09:11.510
Is that strange? Not uncommon. Sometimes he prefers to have

02:09:11.510 --> 02:09:13.610
a sherry under cigar and nothing more,

02:09:14.130 --> 02:09:16.450
but when he didn't come to breakfast this morning, we

02:09:16.450 --> 02:09:19.290
began to worry. Smith looks at the clock.

02:09:20.030 --> 02:09:23.930
Mr. Bowen, normally we need to wait 48 hours until

02:09:23.930 --> 02:09:25.950
we can start a missing person investigation.

02:09:26.990 --> 02:09:30.470
Bowen turns from the window and gives Smith an annoyed

02:09:30.470 --> 02:09:33.250
look. Your chief inspector said you could

02:09:33.250 --> 02:09:37.730
help. Was he wrong? Smith sighs and shakes his head.

02:09:38.590 --> 02:09:41.290
Does Mr. Fletcher have any good friends here?

02:09:41.290 --> 02:09:47.250
Or more importantly, enemies. He is a solitary man. But

02:09:47.250 --> 02:09:50.010
respected. He is the oldest teacher at

02:09:50.010 --> 02:09:54.570
Barnaby's, practically part of the building. Bowen stops and thinks.

02:09:55.530 --> 02:09:57.130
He doesn't like our new music

02:09:57.130 --> 02:09:59.730
teacher, Mr. Cliff. Didn't they have some sort of fight

02:09:59.730 --> 02:10:02.610
recently, Miss White? I don't think so.

02:10:03.370 --> 02:10:08.270
She says quietly. And what about the students? Smith asks

02:10:08.270 --> 02:10:08.830
them both.

02:10:09.710 --> 02:10:16.330
The students replies Bowen in an insulted tone. Detective, the

02:10:16.330 --> 02:10:18.490
young men at this school are very clever

02:10:18.490 --> 02:10:22.070
and come from very important families. In a few years

02:10:22.070 --> 02:10:24.510
they will be politicians, judges or doctors.

02:10:25.430 --> 02:10:29.510
They are not criminals. Smith breathes out with a puff.

02:10:30.510 --> 02:10:33.830
No. Well, I suppose we could have a look

02:10:33.830 --> 02:10:38.950
around the school. Good, says Bowen. Show them out, Miss

02:10:38.950 --> 02:10:41.390
White. And the headmaster does not look

02:10:41.390 --> 02:10:46.890
at them again. Jesus, says Smith in the corridor. Who

02:10:46.890 --> 02:10:49.910
does he think he is? Just because he plays

02:10:49.910 --> 02:10:53.990
golf with the chief inspector? Waste of bloody time this

02:10:53.990 --> 02:11:02.870
is West. Did you hear him? This

02:11:02.870 --> 02:11:07.970
pub in the city. And West nods again. They walk

02:11:07.970 --> 02:11:09.710
along the corridors for five minutes

02:11:09.710 --> 02:11:14.090
and reach an internal courtyard. Outside they can see the

02:11:14.090 --> 02:11:17.110
renovation work. There's scaffolding on

02:11:17.110 --> 02:11:19.750
the face of the old building, a new wall on

02:11:19.750 --> 02:11:21.790
the side of it and three or four workmen are

02:11:21.790 --> 02:11:22.030
sitting

02:11:22.030 --> 02:11:26.810
on a bench eating lunch. They cross the courtyard. And

02:11:26.810 --> 02:11:29.570
Smith stops to pick up a school tie on the

02:11:29.570 --> 02:11:34.230
floor by the new wall. Politicians and doctors, they can't

02:11:34.230 --> 02:11:35.110
even dress themselves.

02:11:36.610 --> 02:11:40.170
And Smith puts the tie in his pocket. Sir, look.

02:11:40.890 --> 02:11:43.390
West says and points to the top of a tower.

02:11:44.050 --> 02:11:49.590
What? There are two people watching us, sir. And? Well,

02:11:49.770 --> 02:11:59.550
just observing, sir. Maybe there's a

02:11:59.550 --> 02:12:02.150
one we go. We can also check one or two

02:12:02.150 --> 02:12:03.910
of the local pubs on the way back to the

02:12:03.910 --> 02:12:04.170
city.

02:12:05.010 --> 02:12:08.150
The door to the tower is in another corridor. And

02:12:08.150 --> 02:12:10.350
when they open it, they hear footsteps on the

02:12:10.350 --> 02:12:16.130
stairs. Who's that? Smith shouts. The footsteps stop and Miss

02:12:16.130 --> 02:12:18.610
White steps into view. You?

02:12:19.610 --> 02:12:23.510
Were you watching us from the roof? No, well, not

02:12:23.510 --> 02:12:25.690
really. The secretary says quietly.

02:12:26.590 --> 02:12:32.950
Who else is with you? Mr. Fletcher. What? No. Be

02:12:32.950 --> 02:12:35.150
honest now or there might be trouble for you.

02:12:36.230 --> 02:12:39.410
It's my fault. A voice says and a young man

02:12:39.410 --> 02:12:42.570
steps forward. Miss White came to speak to me.

02:12:43.490 --> 02:12:47.010
Oh, really? And who are you? I'm the music teacher,

02:12:47.290 --> 02:12:47.710
Mr. Cliff.

02:12:48.810 --> 02:12:53.310
Ah, well, isn't that interesting? No, it's not what you

02:12:53.310 --> 02:12:53.530
think.

02:12:54.210 --> 02:12:56.630
I came here to tell Mr. Cliff what the headmaster

02:12:56.630 --> 02:12:57.810
said about the argument.

02:12:58.830 --> 02:13:04.370
Go on. Look, says Cliff. It was nothing, really. Only

02:13:04.370 --> 02:13:06.130
Fletcher said something about Miss White,

02:13:06.470 --> 02:13:09.530
something no gentleman should say. I told him to apologize,

02:13:09.530 --> 02:13:12.090
and then we argued. But the last time

02:13:12.090 --> 02:13:16.570
I saw him was yesterday morning. It's true. Ads, Miss

02:13:16.570 --> 02:13:19.130
White. Well, we might need to talk to you

02:13:19.130 --> 02:13:22.590
again at another time. Smith says and turns to go

02:13:22.590 --> 02:13:25.170
back to the courtyard. But then he stops.

02:13:26.110 --> 02:13:29.010
How did you know Mr. Cliff was here, Miss White?

02:13:29.990 --> 02:13:33.270
The secretary blushes. We meet here,

02:13:33.530 --> 02:13:39.610
sometimes, for lunch. Ah, I see. Then the hammering they

02:13:39.610 --> 02:13:41.830
heard in the headmaster's office starts again.

02:13:41.830 --> 02:13:44.410
And the policeman go to the door.

02:13:45.130 --> 02:13:49.430
Detective, says the secretary. You asked about the students.

02:13:50.090 --> 02:13:53.790
They hate Mr. Fletcher. They say he punishes them for

02:13:53.790 --> 02:13:54.630
every mistake.

02:13:55.570 --> 02:13:58.350
Well, students normally don't like teachers, do they?

02:13:59.130 --> 02:14:04.810
Fletcher is worse, says Cliff. He's a dinosaur. I think

02:14:04.810 --> 02:14:07.850
he hits the boys sometimes, but I can't prove it.

02:14:08.450 --> 02:14:12.790
Smith nods. I'm sure it's nothing. Back in the courtyard,

02:14:13.230 --> 02:14:14.790
Smith stops by the workman,

02:14:15.250 --> 02:14:18.930
who are still sitting and eating their lunch. Listen and

02:14:18.930 --> 02:14:21.990
observe, West. I suppose you didn't

02:14:21.990 --> 02:14:24.590
notice, but those two are having some sort of romantic

02:14:24.590 --> 02:14:28.370
affair. Oh, well, yes, I did notice, sir.

02:14:29.450 --> 02:14:33.670
You did? Good. I can teach you a few things,

02:14:33.710 --> 02:14:36.770
I think, West. And Smith nods to the workman.

02:14:37.850 --> 02:14:41.690
Should we speak to the students, sir? West asks as

02:14:41.690 --> 02:14:42.930
they walk back to the car.

02:14:43.950 --> 02:14:48.030
What for? Well, to see if they know anything. Smith

02:14:48.030 --> 02:14:49.510
takes the tie from his pocket.

02:14:50.350 --> 02:14:54.030
Their children, West, they can't even put a tie on.

02:14:54.590 --> 02:14:55.950
Let's get back to the city.

02:14:56.890 --> 02:14:59.970
And he throws the tie on the floor. West nods.

02:15:01.130 --> 02:15:04.870
It's best to just nod. But there is something that

02:15:04.870 --> 02:15:10.490
does not make sense. The hammering noise. They heard it

02:15:10.490 --> 02:15:11.550
in the headmaster's office.

02:15:12.550 --> 02:15:14.690
And they heard it in the corridor with Miss White

02:15:14.690 --> 02:15:15.450
and Mr Cliff.

02:15:16.430 --> 02:15:18.830
And he looks back at the workman, who were enjoying

02:15:18.830 --> 02:15:23.110
a slow lunch. But if these men are not hammering.

02:15:23.690 --> 02:15:29.850
Come on, West! Smith shouts. And West nods. Yes, it's

02:15:29.850 --> 02:15:32.850
best to just nod. And somewhere in the dark,

02:15:32.850 --> 02:15:36.230
Mr Fletcher stops hammering his foot against the new wall.

02:15:37.390 --> 02:15:40.010
He is tired now. Very tired.

02:15:41.290 --> 02:15:45.450
He tries to remember exactly what happened. He remembers hitting

02:15:45.450 --> 02:15:47.210
that idiot of a boy Harris

02:15:47.210 --> 02:15:50.830
because he made a mistake in the geometry class. He

02:15:50.830 --> 02:15:52.850
remembers another boy telling him to stop,

02:15:53.650 --> 02:15:56.910
then another boy, and another. And then they were all

02:15:56.910 --> 02:15:59.990
on top of him. At first they only hit him.

02:15:59.990 --> 02:16:03.150
But then he felt school ties being wrapped around his

02:16:03.150 --> 02:16:04.430
hands and feet and mouth.

02:16:05.390 --> 02:16:07.430
And they lifted him up and carried him to the

02:16:07.430 --> 02:16:08.930
new wall which was nearly finished.

02:16:09.790 --> 02:16:12.990
And they put him behind it in a deep, dark

02:16:12.990 --> 02:16:15.150
corner when no one could see him.

02:16:15.890 --> 02:16:18.930
And the light disappeared as they put the last bricks

02:16:18.930 --> 02:16:19.670
in place.

02:16:20.650 --> 02:16:25.730
He tried desperately to shout. But he could not. And

02:16:25.730 --> 02:16:28.330
he tried to move. But he could not.

02:16:29.050 --> 02:16:31.650
And for a while he thought that he would die

02:16:31.650 --> 02:16:33.910
in the deep, dark corner behind the wall.

02:16:34.990 --> 02:16:39.550
But everything will be okay now, he knows. Because after

02:16:39.550 --> 02:16:41.750
hours of struggling, his foot is now

02:16:41.750 --> 02:16:45.710
finally free to move. And the police will be here

02:16:45.710 --> 02:16:48.450
soon. He is sure. And they will hear.

02:16:49.370 --> 02:16:52.290
So he continues to hammer his foot against the wall.

02:16:53.510 --> 02:16:56.110
And he hopes that someone hears him soon.

02:17:00.190 --> 02:17:01.370
The Poachers

02:17:04.970 --> 02:17:09.670
My God, just look at that, Junior. Owen says with

02:17:09.670 --> 02:17:11.630
a smile and he points to the valley and

02:17:11.630 --> 02:17:17.110
green forest below them. Abutru wherean forest, what a beauty,

02:17:17.510 --> 02:17:19.710
Alad. And he looks to his son,

02:17:20.210 --> 02:17:23.610
Owen Junior. And he wants to see a smile on

02:17:23.610 --> 02:17:26.510
the boy's pale face. But like always,

02:17:26.510 --> 02:17:31.870
there's nothing but disinterest. We saw it last year, Junior

02:17:31.870 --> 02:17:32.230
says.

02:17:33.150 --> 02:17:38.210
It just looks the same. The same? Well, I suppose,

02:17:38.530 --> 02:17:41.030
but look at its son. Look at how beautiful it

02:17:41.030 --> 02:17:41.350
is.

02:17:42.030 --> 02:17:45.630
Can there be a finer place in Wales? I don't

02:17:45.630 --> 02:17:48.810
think so. But Junior only shrugs.

02:17:49.430 --> 02:17:53.470
Owen shakes his head. He remembers when he came here

02:17:53.470 --> 02:17:55.970
with his father to poach a few rabbits as a

02:17:55.970 --> 02:17:59.230
child. He loved the walk up from the town of

02:17:59.230 --> 02:18:02.350
Sennybridge. He loved the hours of walking and

02:18:02.350 --> 02:18:07.010
hunting in the forests and valley. But not Junior. Junior

02:18:07.010 --> 02:18:09.570
said that to walk there was stupid because

02:18:09.570 --> 02:18:12.710
they had a car. And despite all of Owen's arguments,

02:18:13.030 --> 02:18:14.950
the teenager did not change his mind.

02:18:16.010 --> 02:18:18.290
Owen looks back at the car and hopes that no

02:18:18.290 --> 02:18:21.150
one can see it from the main road. He lifts

02:18:21.150 --> 02:18:21.890
the two

02:18:21.890 --> 02:18:24.630
gunbags onto his shoulder and starts to walk.

02:18:25.550 --> 02:18:29.010
Come on, son. This is going to be great fun,

02:18:29.830 --> 02:18:33.350
he says. And Junior follows him but says nothing.

02:18:34.470 --> 02:18:39.050
The forest is alive with life. It's the second week

02:18:39.050 --> 02:18:41.650
of April and spring is certainly here.

02:18:42.390 --> 02:18:45.890
The grass below their feet is green and fresh. The

02:18:45.890 --> 02:18:48.530
trees are heavy with leaves and the air smells

02:18:48.530 --> 02:18:53.090
so good that Owen forgets about Junior's mood. Smell that,

02:18:53.330 --> 02:18:56.250
son. Good, eh? That's the scent of life,

02:18:56.690 --> 02:19:00.510
the scent of the real whales. Junior lifts his head.

02:19:01.350 --> 02:19:02.470
I can't smell anything.

02:19:03.110 --> 02:19:09.290
What? The flowers, the trees, spring. Oh, that. And the

02:19:09.290 --> 02:19:11.150
boy pulls something out of his pocket

02:19:11.750 --> 02:19:14.650
and Owen sees that it's his MP3 player.

02:19:15.310 --> 02:19:19.170
Whoa, whoa, whoa. He says, wait a minute, son. You

02:19:19.170 --> 02:19:20.290
don't need that today.

02:19:20.890 --> 02:19:24.810
What? But I want to listen to my music. Music?

02:19:25.550 --> 02:19:29.010
Listen to the forest lad. Listen to the birds in

02:19:29.010 --> 02:19:29.270
the wind.

02:19:30.110 --> 02:19:33.690
No, you don't need that today. He repeats and he

02:19:33.690 --> 02:19:36.130
takes the MP3 player from the boy's hands.

02:19:36.810 --> 02:19:39.130
And he tries to avoid the angry look in the

02:19:39.130 --> 02:19:40.150
boy's dark eyes.

02:19:41.110 --> 02:19:45.810
Dark eyes, just like his mothers. And dark hair, too.

02:19:46.610 --> 02:19:47.590
Just like his mothers.

02:19:48.490 --> 02:19:52.010
Owen is tall and fair, with blue eyes and a

02:19:52.010 --> 02:19:54.890
healthy complexion from years of work and activity

02:19:54.890 --> 02:20:00.030
outside. Junior is short for his age. Short and thin

02:20:00.030 --> 02:20:02.470
with a pale and unhealthy complexion from

02:20:02.470 --> 02:20:05.790
hours of playing his computer games and watching television.

02:20:06.890 --> 02:20:10.390
When Owen was a boy of fourteen, he played rugby

02:20:10.390 --> 02:20:13.690
or football every day. He ran to the

02:20:13.690 --> 02:20:16.670
school in the village just for fun. And he spent

02:20:16.670 --> 02:20:19.410
every Sunday in the forests with his dad.

02:20:20.210 --> 02:20:24.230
Junior does not like sports. He does not run. And

02:20:24.230 --> 02:20:26.170
the last time he came to the forest with Owen,

02:20:26.690 --> 02:20:28.510
he said that it was too cold and that the

02:20:28.510 --> 02:20:29.370
forest was boring.

02:20:30.150 --> 02:20:32.550
But Owen does not like to think about that too

02:20:32.550 --> 02:20:32.870
much.

02:20:33.690 --> 02:20:36.670
His wife, Rhea, is a good woman and pretty, too.

02:20:37.250 --> 02:20:39.410
But sometimes he cannot help but look at

02:20:39.410 --> 02:20:43.170
Junior and wonder. So he tries not to think about

02:20:43.170 --> 02:20:45.830
it. Rhea says that it's just his age

02:20:45.830 --> 02:20:49.810
and that all teenage boys prefer computer games and television

02:20:49.810 --> 02:20:51.050
to walks in the forest.

02:20:51.890 --> 02:20:54.130
And yes, the last time they came to the forest

02:20:54.130 --> 02:20:56.610
it was a bit cold and they had nothing to

02:20:56.610 --> 02:20:56.830
do.

02:20:57.510 --> 02:21:01.470
But not this time. No, this time the sun is

02:21:01.470 --> 02:21:05.130
high and hot. And this time Owen has his old

02:21:05.130 --> 02:21:05.450
guns

02:21:05.450 --> 02:21:09.270
over his shoulder. And he remembers the way that Junior's

02:21:09.270 --> 02:21:11.530
expressionless face changed when he

02:21:11.530 --> 02:21:15.390
saw them the night before. These were your grandad's guns,

02:21:15.990 --> 02:21:17.090
he said to him in the kitchen,

02:21:17.710 --> 02:21:19.730
and one day they can be yours if you want.

02:21:20.410 --> 02:21:24.110
Really? And I can shoot things? Animals and things?

02:21:24.750 --> 02:21:27.470
Of course, lad. But I need to show you how

02:21:27.470 --> 02:21:30.610
first. But I know how. You do?

02:21:31.230 --> 02:21:34.590
Yeah, I saw how in films and on television. Oh,

02:21:34.650 --> 02:21:37.250
in laughed. Oh, well, I need to show you

02:21:37.250 --> 02:21:39.950
how to do it safely. So we need to go

02:21:39.950 --> 02:21:44.150
up to the old Abattrawaran forest. And Owen knew the

02:21:44.150 --> 02:21:44.370
boy

02:21:44.370 --> 02:21:47.570
was interested then. And for the first time in a

02:21:47.570 --> 02:21:49.530
long time he thought that maybe there was

02:21:49.530 --> 02:21:53.790
something they could do together. Father and son, the way

02:21:53.790 --> 02:21:56.450
it should be. But now, in the forest,

02:21:56.850 --> 02:22:01.270
he's not so sure. The boy looks bored already. And

02:22:01.270 --> 02:22:03.150
he's not looking at the gun bags with interest

02:22:03.150 --> 02:22:07.790
anymore. Well, maybe when he gets to shoot one. Soon

02:22:07.790 --> 02:22:10.650
they are deep in the forest. And Owen finds

02:22:10.650 --> 02:22:13.850
a small clearing. He puts the guns next to a

02:22:13.850 --> 02:22:15.950
tree and takes them out of the bags carefully.

02:22:16.510 --> 02:22:19.650
And yes, there is the interest in the boy's eyes.

02:22:20.470 --> 02:22:23.070
So what can we shoot? Junior asks.

02:22:24.090 --> 02:22:25.810
At this time of year we want to look for

02:22:25.810 --> 02:22:28.050
rabbit's son. But if we can get a hair,

02:22:28.550 --> 02:22:33.190
even better. What about deer? Can we shoot them? Deer?

02:22:34.110 --> 02:22:36.970
No, son. They're too big. We don't want

02:22:36.970 --> 02:22:39.630
to carry a deer back to the car. Someone might

02:22:39.630 --> 02:22:43.510
see us. So? And Owen realises that the boy does

02:22:43.510 --> 02:22:47.990
not understand what poaching is. Well, you see, really, we

02:22:47.990 --> 02:22:49.250
aren't supposed to be here.

02:22:49.890 --> 02:22:54.510
What? Junior says, a scared look in his eyes. Why

02:22:54.510 --> 02:22:57.670
not? Well, to some people, shooting here is

02:22:57.670 --> 02:23:02.950
illegal. They call it poaching. Which people? Well, the police,

02:23:03.090 --> 02:23:04.650
for example, and the forestry

02:23:04.650 --> 02:23:09.230
commission. Junior looks around the forest. You mean it's a

02:23:09.230 --> 02:23:12.510
crime? It's illegal. Owen thinks

02:23:12.510 --> 02:23:16.190
about what to say. Well, it is, son. But only

02:23:16.190 --> 02:23:18.470
like downloading films for free.

02:23:19.170 --> 02:23:22.750
That's a crime. That's illegal. But you still do that,

02:23:22.930 --> 02:23:23.370
don't you?

02:23:23.890 --> 02:23:27.050
Well, this is just like that. No one gets hurt.

02:23:27.830 --> 02:23:29.850
We take one or two rabbits home and we have

02:23:29.850 --> 02:23:29.930
a

02:23:29.930 --> 02:23:34.830
little fun. That's okay, isn't it? Junior nods. I suppose

02:23:34.830 --> 02:23:37.170
so. But what if someone sees us?

02:23:37.750 --> 02:23:41.770
Ah, good question, son. Now, not many people come to

02:23:41.770 --> 02:23:43.570
this side of the forest at this time of the

02:23:43.570 --> 02:23:46.410
year. But if you see someone, you just put the

02:23:46.410 --> 02:23:48.990
gun down gently in a bush or under some leaves.

02:23:49.990 --> 02:23:52.270
Remember to do it nice and gently and to say

02:23:52.270 --> 02:23:55.210
hello. If you have no gun, then there's no problem.

02:23:55.950 --> 02:23:58.670
We can come back for the gun another day. Okay?

02:23:59.430 --> 02:24:07.150
So remember, if you see or hear someone,

02:24:07.150 --> 02:24:10.450
Junior looks a bit happier now. And for 20 minutes,

02:24:10.750 --> 02:24:12.930
Owen talks to him about how to hold the gun

02:24:13.530 --> 02:24:16.410
and how to walk with it. While his son listens

02:24:16.410 --> 02:24:19.370
carefully and asks sensible questions that show

02:24:19.370 --> 02:24:22.970
a real interest. For the first time in many years,

02:24:23.390 --> 02:24:26.270
Owen and Junior seem to be exactly what they are,

02:24:26.750 --> 02:24:30.310
father and son. And Owen notices that the boy actually

02:24:30.310 --> 02:24:32.370
looks a little bit like him after all.

02:24:33.010 --> 02:24:37.010
And that he also smiles sometimes. Sure, he likes films

02:24:37.010 --> 02:24:38.750
and television and not sports.

02:24:39.570 --> 02:24:42.190
That maybe this can be their thing. It doesn't have

02:24:42.190 --> 02:24:44.490
to be every weekend if Junior doesn't want to.

02:24:45.110 --> 02:24:48.370
But occasionally, then maybe in a few years, they can

02:24:48.370 --> 02:24:51.210
start to go for a pint like Owen and his

02:24:51.210 --> 02:24:51.510
father

02:24:51.510 --> 02:24:56.810
did. Right then, son, he says, feeling extremely happy and

02:24:56.810 --> 02:24:58.870
enjoying the excitement in the boy's

02:24:58.870 --> 02:25:02.310
eyes. Now, I'm going to load the guns, then we

02:25:02.310 --> 02:25:04.270
can follow the path there into the forest.

02:25:05.230 --> 02:25:08.250
Do you remember the rules about the gun, son? Yes,

02:25:08.350 --> 02:25:11.430
dad. Keep the gun pointed down to the ground

02:25:11.430 --> 02:25:14.370
unless I see a rabbit. Never point the gun at

02:25:14.370 --> 02:25:17.990
you or anyone else. Keep to your left, but not

02:25:17.990 --> 02:25:21.370
directly behind you. Don't shoot in us. I can clearly

02:25:21.370 --> 02:25:23.050
see that there's no one near the target.

02:25:23.990 --> 02:25:26.250
And don't forget there are two shots and that I

02:25:26.250 --> 02:25:28.190
should empty the gun before I give it back to

02:25:28.190 --> 02:25:28.390
you.

02:25:28.970 --> 02:25:33.670
Exactly, says Owen. And he feels full of pride and

02:25:33.670 --> 02:25:35.770
thinks what a wonderful day this is,

02:25:36.170 --> 02:25:38.670
out in the beauty of the Welsh countryside with his

02:25:38.670 --> 02:25:40.870
son, and for a while they walk.

02:25:41.730 --> 02:25:44.570
And he's happy about how carefully Junior holds the gun

02:25:44.570 --> 02:25:47.490
and how he listens and does exactly what

02:25:47.490 --> 02:25:50.730
he should. But then they reach another clearing and they

02:25:50.730 --> 02:25:52.210
hear something behind the trees.

02:25:52.910 --> 02:25:58.370
Dad, Junior whispers, and he looks scared. What's that noise?

02:25:59.410 --> 02:25:59.990
Is it the police?

02:26:00.970 --> 02:26:04.350
And Owen signals him to be quiet. He tries to

02:26:04.350 --> 02:26:06.130
see through the trees, but he cannot.

02:26:07.050 --> 02:26:10.950
He thinks there is someone or something moving. And it's

02:26:10.950 --> 02:26:13.710
big, bigger than a rabbit or a hair,

02:26:14.290 --> 02:26:16.310
but he does not think it can be a person.

02:26:16.850 --> 02:26:18.930
He never sees people up here at this time of

02:26:18.930 --> 02:26:19.150
year.

02:26:19.810 --> 02:26:22.710
In the summer maybe, but not now. Could it be

02:26:22.710 --> 02:26:24.630
a park ranger from the Forestry Commission?

02:26:25.470 --> 02:26:27.950
Did someone see the car parked in the trees and

02:26:27.950 --> 02:26:30.950
called the police? There is a snap from behind

02:26:30.950 --> 02:26:33.990
the trees, and Owen thinks that maybe he should put

02:26:33.990 --> 02:26:36.810
his gun down in a bush nice and carefully

02:26:36.810 --> 02:26:39.870
like he told Junior to do. Behind him he can

02:26:39.870 --> 02:26:43.370
hear Junior, who sounds like he is very scared.

02:26:44.180 --> 02:26:48.470
But then Owen sees what is behind the trees. Brown

02:26:48.470 --> 02:26:52.470
hair, big gentle eyes. He laughs and turns

02:26:52.470 --> 02:26:55.570
back to Junior to tell him to stay calm. But

02:26:55.570 --> 02:26:58.350
before he can do this, Junior, who does not know

02:26:58.350 --> 02:27:02.330
what is making the noise, remembers his dad's words. If

02:27:02.330 --> 02:27:04.610
you have no gun, then there's no problem.

02:27:05.590 --> 02:27:08.430
But he does not remember the other words. Put it

02:27:08.430 --> 02:27:12.330
down gently. Owen sees the boy throw the

02:27:12.330 --> 02:27:14.510
gun and tries to shout that it's just a deer,

02:27:15.150 --> 02:27:18.230
but it's too late. There is a loud bang.

02:27:19.090 --> 02:27:22.450
Owen feels an incredible pain in his behind, and he

02:27:22.450 --> 02:27:24.330
screams and falls to the floor.

02:27:25.050 --> 02:27:28.170
As he lies there, shouting and screaming and trying to

02:27:28.170 --> 02:27:30.190
pull the pieces of shot from his skin,

02:27:31.070 --> 02:27:33.890
he looks up at the beautiful blue sky and green

02:27:33.890 --> 02:27:35.970
trees and magnificent forest.

02:27:36.970 --> 02:27:39.890
And he thinks that maybe next time they should just

02:27:39.890 --> 02:27:41.590
go to the cinema instead.

02:27:42.330 --> 02:27:46.450
Or maybe play a computer game or watch television.

02:27:49.410 --> 02:27:50.270
The card chalk.

02:27:53.730 --> 02:27:58.710
Are you sitting comfortably? Good. I want to tell you

02:27:58.710 --> 02:28:00.190
a little story that I know.

02:28:00.890 --> 02:28:04.530
Now it's not a very nice story, and I can't

02:28:04.530 --> 02:28:07.170
promise you that there will be a very happy ending.

02:28:07.950 --> 02:28:11.650
But it's a true story. And that's something that's very

02:28:11.650 --> 02:28:12.790
important to me.

02:28:13.510 --> 02:28:16.670
And I want you to remember that. Yeah, you need

02:28:16.670 --> 02:28:19.250
to remember that the truth is important to me.

02:28:19.990 --> 02:28:23.510
And you know what? It's something that's very important to

02:28:23.510 --> 02:28:26.230
you too. Or it should be.

02:28:27.350 --> 02:28:31.570
So relax a little and listen. See, there was once

02:28:31.570 --> 02:28:33.310
a young man called Jimmy Lane,

02:28:33.310 --> 02:28:38.070
an Englishman from the great city of London. Well, Jimmy

02:28:38.070 --> 02:28:40.010
was a nobody in many ways.

02:28:41.330 --> 02:28:43.250
You know what I mean when I say a nobody.

02:28:44.170 --> 02:28:46.610
I mean, Jimmy wasn't rich, and he wasn't too

02:28:46.610 --> 02:28:50.890
bright, you know? Not very clever, really. And he wasn't

02:28:50.890 --> 02:28:52.830
a funny guy, and he didn't have much luck

02:28:52.830 --> 02:28:56.190
with the ladies. I know all this to be true.

02:28:56.890 --> 02:29:00.110
I know it because I can read people. And I

02:29:00.110 --> 02:29:00.250
could

02:29:00.250 --> 02:29:03.570
see all this when I look to Jimmy Lane. However,

02:29:03.850 --> 02:29:07.710
Jimmy had a talent, a skill, an ability.

02:29:08.630 --> 02:29:13.550
You see, Jimmy could play cards. Poker, Blackjack, Rummy, you

02:29:13.550 --> 02:29:15.530
name the game, and Jimmy could play it.

02:29:16.310 --> 02:29:20.250
Though he especially liked poker. With a deck of cards

02:29:20.250 --> 02:29:22.270
in his hands, Jimmy was like a magician.

02:29:23.490 --> 02:29:26.270
He could cut and shuffle the deck like he had

02:29:26.270 --> 02:29:27.650
eight arms instead of two.

02:29:28.310 --> 02:29:31.330
And he could remember every card he saw in a

02:29:31.330 --> 02:29:34.770
split second and could use his fingers and little

02:29:34.770 --> 02:29:37.090
tricks to put the cards where he wanted them in

02:29:37.090 --> 02:29:41.950
the deck. Oh boy, what a talent. What a skill

02:29:41.950 --> 02:29:42.310
Jimmy

02:29:42.310 --> 02:29:46.830
had. And he had something else too. He had a

02:29:46.830 --> 02:29:50.750
choice, a choice about what to do with this talent.

02:29:51.550 --> 02:29:53.510
You see, there are two things you can do with

02:29:53.510 --> 02:29:56.590
a talent like that. You can either play the game

02:29:56.590 --> 02:30:00.650
right. You play it straight. This way you enter the

02:30:00.650 --> 02:30:03.190
competitions. You play your best.

02:30:04.110 --> 02:30:07.650
And you play by the rules. Then slowly you win

02:30:07.650 --> 02:30:10.650
respect. And slowly you make a name for yourself.

02:30:11.870 --> 02:30:15.690
Or there's the other thing you can do. You can

02:30:15.690 --> 02:30:18.190
cheat. Do you know what I mean when I say

02:30:18.190 --> 02:30:18.570
cheat?

02:30:19.470 --> 02:30:22.850
I mean you use the little tricks, the fast fingers,

02:30:23.010 --> 02:30:26.190
and the good memory. But you use it to break

02:30:26.190 --> 02:30:26.530
the

02:30:26.530 --> 02:30:29.250
rules of the game. And do you know what choice

02:30:29.250 --> 02:30:33.830
Jimmy Lane made? You got it. He decided to cheat.

02:30:34.730 --> 02:30:38.470
He decided to come to the biggest, richest, most important

02:30:38.470 --> 02:30:40.230
gambling city in the world.

02:30:41.170 --> 02:30:45.570
And he decided to cheat. That's right. He couldn't wait.

02:30:46.170 --> 02:30:49.410
He wanted everything now. He wanted money.

02:30:49.410 --> 02:30:53.270
He wanted to be famous and he wanted respect. So

02:30:53.270 --> 02:30:56.310
yeah, he came here to Las Vegas.

02:30:57.210 --> 02:31:01.790
Vegas. Wow. What a city. The lights, the music, the

02:31:01.790 --> 02:31:05.070
atmosphere. And Jimmy thought he could take it

02:31:05.070 --> 02:31:10.790
all. Huh. What a kid. What a dumb, stupid kid.

02:31:11.830 --> 02:31:14.270
You see, you don't take from Las Vegas.

02:31:15.550 --> 02:31:21.230
Vegas takes from you. But Jimmy, poor, stupid Jimmy, didn't

02:31:21.230 --> 02:31:23.790
know that. So he found a casino,

02:31:24.770 --> 02:31:27.990
a real casino. One of the best in the city.

02:31:29.150 --> 02:31:30.630
And he thought he could do it quickly.

02:31:31.750 --> 02:31:34.370
Play the game, get the money, and run before anyone

02:31:34.370 --> 02:31:37.830
knew he was there. But he picked the wrong casino.

02:31:38.950 --> 02:31:44.430
He picked my casino. That was a bad decision. But

02:31:44.430 --> 02:31:46.150
worse than that was his next decision.

02:31:47.150 --> 02:31:49.770
That was when he decided he was good enough and

02:31:49.770 --> 02:31:52.210
clever enough and lucky enough to play

02:31:52.210 --> 02:31:57.930
at my table. To enter my golden chip competition. A

02:31:57.930 --> 02:32:00.470
competition where only the best of the best

02:32:00.470 --> 02:32:03.990
get to play. How he made the money to enter,

02:32:04.070 --> 02:32:07.610
I don't know. I think he probably cheated to get

02:32:07.610 --> 02:32:11.850
that too. But he entered my competition and he used

02:32:11.850 --> 02:32:14.730
his tricks and his fast fingers and he won

02:32:14.730 --> 02:32:20.750
every game until it came to the final. Hank wins,

02:32:20.890 --> 02:32:23.890
stops talking and puts his cigar back in his mouth.

02:32:24.570 --> 02:32:29.650
He looks calm. Happy almost. But there is something very

02:32:29.650 --> 02:32:31.590
dangerous about Hank win when

02:32:31.590 --> 02:32:35.170
he looks calm and happy. Some people say that the

02:32:35.170 --> 02:32:37.630
reason his casino is called shark pool

02:32:37.630 --> 02:32:41.590
is because Hank looks a little like a shark. He

02:32:41.590 --> 02:32:45.490
always wears a gray suit. He always walks in a

02:32:45.490 --> 02:32:50.010
slow manner. And his eyes are always cold and dark.

02:32:50.990 --> 02:32:53.190
But maybe there's another reason for the name

02:32:53.190 --> 02:32:57.830
of the casino. The truth Jimmy. And Hank throws the

02:32:57.830 --> 02:32:59.910
end of the cigar into the pool in front of

02:32:59.910 --> 02:33:00.050
him.

02:33:00.970 --> 02:33:03.830
It is night time. And around the roof of the

02:33:03.830 --> 02:33:05.610
30 floor casino and hotel,

02:33:06.430 --> 02:33:10.450
the city of Las Vegas is alive with color. There

02:33:10.450 --> 02:33:13.790
are people everywhere. But here on the roof there

02:33:13.790 --> 02:33:17.130
are only four people. There is Hank win and his

02:33:17.130 --> 02:33:19.610
assistants and bodyguards Kenny and Clive.

02:33:20.410 --> 02:33:24.650
Who stand patiently and listen to his speech. And there

02:33:24.650 --> 02:33:27.950
is Jimmy Lane. Jimmy Lane does not stand.

02:33:28.770 --> 02:33:33.170
Jimmy Lane cannot stand. His hands are tied. His legs

02:33:33.170 --> 02:33:35.730
are tied. And his mouth is gagged.

02:33:36.510 --> 02:33:40.490
And there is blood on Jimmy Lane. Small cuts on

02:33:40.490 --> 02:33:44.050
his arms and chest. And he's naked apart from his

02:33:44.050 --> 02:33:44.270
trousers.

02:33:46.170 --> 02:33:49.490
Now I'm not a cruel man Jimmy. I'm really not.

02:33:49.950 --> 02:33:51.790
I'm a businessman, not a gangster.

02:33:52.490 --> 02:33:56.230
But this city is cruel Jimmy. And sometimes I have

02:33:56.230 --> 02:33:58.230
to do things to protect my business.

02:33:59.110 --> 02:34:03.270
Do you understand that Jimmy? Do you know how many

02:34:03.270 --> 02:34:05.250
kids like you come into my casino?

02:34:05.250 --> 02:34:13.230
No? Hundreds. Thousands. They all think they can win. They

02:34:13.230 --> 02:34:15.890
all think they can cheat and beat the casino.

02:34:16.950 --> 02:34:19.390
And Jimmy Lane shakes his head and tries to say

02:34:19.390 --> 02:34:21.970
something. And his blue eyes are wet.

02:34:22.890 --> 02:34:26.610
Wait a moment Jimmy. Wait one moment. Hank says and

02:34:26.610 --> 02:34:28.290
he puts his hand on Jimmy's head.

02:34:29.150 --> 02:34:32.510
And Jimmy tries to move away. I don't want you

02:34:32.510 --> 02:34:34.130
to say anything stupid Jimmy.

02:34:34.980 --> 02:34:38.970
Because this is your last chance. He looks across the

02:34:38.970 --> 02:34:39.910
pool to his assistant.

02:34:40.990 --> 02:34:44.950
When did they last eat Clive? Last week Mr. When.

02:34:45.710 --> 02:34:48.510
You remember the Mexican? The one stealing from the bar?

02:34:49.350 --> 02:34:54.690
Ah yes. A week. Did you hear that Jimmy? So

02:34:54.690 --> 02:34:57.050
before I take this gag out of your mouth.

02:34:58.030 --> 02:35:01.770
And before you think about saying something stupid again. Think

02:35:01.770 --> 02:35:02.510
about this.

02:35:03.350 --> 02:35:06.470
Did you really not think that we were watching you?

02:35:07.270 --> 02:35:08.310
We knew you were cheating.

02:35:09.310 --> 02:35:11.390
We knew you were using your little tricks.

02:35:12.530 --> 02:35:14.930
The only reason you got to the final table to

02:35:14.930 --> 02:35:18.170
my table Jimmy is because I let you.

02:35:18.930 --> 02:35:21.190
And Hank takes Jimmy's face in his hands.

02:35:22.110 --> 02:35:26.330
The truth Jimmy. I want the truth. It's very important

02:35:26.330 --> 02:35:29.670
to me. And right now it's very important to you.

02:35:30.330 --> 02:35:33.890
And he takes the gag from Jimmy's mouth. For a

02:35:33.890 --> 02:35:35.150
moment Jimmy is silent.

02:35:36.050 --> 02:35:37.990
Then he shouts as loud as he can.

02:35:38.830 --> 02:35:41.490
Help me. Somebody we're on the roof. Help me.

02:35:42.190 --> 02:35:45.590
And for a moment Hank is silent. Then he laughs.

02:35:46.510 --> 02:35:47.770
And the two assistants laugh.

02:35:48.810 --> 02:35:51.690
And then the back of Hank's hand slaps Jimmy's face

02:35:51.690 --> 02:35:52.110
hard.

02:35:53.150 --> 02:35:56.750
Oh Jimmy you really are a stupid kid. We're miles

02:35:56.750 --> 02:35:59.430
up above one of the loudest cities in the world.

02:35:59.670 --> 02:36:03.190
No one can hear you. No one but me and

02:36:03.190 --> 02:36:03.570
the boys.

02:36:04.430 --> 02:36:08.990
So Jimmy. One last chance. Tell me. Tell me the

02:36:08.990 --> 02:36:09.250
truth.

02:36:10.390 --> 02:36:12.810
And Jimmy looks at the pool and the clear water.

02:36:13.710 --> 02:36:14.070
And he nods.

02:36:15.230 --> 02:36:18.310
Okay okay you're right Mr. Win. Everything you say about

02:36:18.310 --> 02:36:19.510
me is right. I was a nobody.

02:36:19.910 --> 02:36:22.130
I was never rich. I was never too clever. But

02:36:22.130 --> 02:36:23.210
I can play cards.

02:36:23.990 --> 02:36:26.170
I started playing when I was seven or eight with

02:36:26.170 --> 02:36:29.050
friends at school online in local competitions.

02:36:29.670 --> 02:36:32.690
And I'm good. I mean I'm really good. And yeah

02:36:32.690 --> 02:36:34.530
that's why I came here. I wanted to win.

02:36:35.110 --> 02:36:37.670
I wanted the respect you talked about. Is that a

02:36:37.670 --> 02:36:38.770
crime? Is that wrong?

02:36:39.590 --> 02:36:43.570
Hank slaps him again. No Jimmy but cheating in my

02:36:43.570 --> 02:36:44.470
casino is.

02:36:45.110 --> 02:36:49.650
I didn't cheat. Jimmy shouts and he's angry now. I

02:36:49.650 --> 02:36:50.390
never cheat.

02:36:50.630 --> 02:36:52.370
You can hit me or you can try to scare

02:36:52.370 --> 02:36:55.670
me but I never cheat. Hank Win laughs.

02:36:56.370 --> 02:36:59.450
Ha ha. Scare you. You think we want to scare

02:36:59.450 --> 02:36:59.790
you.

02:37:01.230 --> 02:37:03.890
Clive let them out. He says.

02:37:04.810 --> 02:37:07.810
Clive nods and pushes a button on the control panel

02:37:07.810 --> 02:37:08.750
next to the pool.

02:37:09.490 --> 02:37:13.430
Below the water a metal door slides open. For a

02:37:13.430 --> 02:37:14.630
moment there is nothing.

02:37:15.470 --> 02:37:18.790
But then two long gray shapes appear in the clear

02:37:18.790 --> 02:37:19.190
water.

02:37:20.270 --> 02:37:21.890
And Jimmy starts to shout again.

02:37:22.490 --> 02:37:25.510
You cheated Jimmy. Four aces?

02:37:26.190 --> 02:37:28.870
I know you put those cards in. I don't know

02:37:28.870 --> 02:37:29.790
how but I know.

02:37:30.490 --> 02:37:33.070
No Mr. Win. I didn't. I promise. I didn't. I

02:37:33.070 --> 02:37:34.630
don't cheat. I never cheat.

02:37:35.410 --> 02:37:39.370
For a moment Hank Win stops and maybe there's a

02:37:39.370 --> 02:37:42.210
second where he believes poor Jimmy Lane.

02:37:43.130 --> 02:37:46.210
But then the second is over and he kicks Jimmy

02:37:46.210 --> 02:37:49.130
in the back and Jimmy falls into the pool with

02:37:49.130 --> 02:37:49.230
a

02:37:49.230 --> 02:37:53.070
screen. Hank Win does not stop to watch what happens

02:37:53.070 --> 02:37:57.210
next. He never does. You see he's not a

02:37:57.210 --> 02:38:01.010
cruel man but he sometimes has to do cruel things.

02:38:01.850 --> 02:38:05.330
Come on. He says to Clive and Kenny and they

02:38:05.330 --> 02:38:05.530
move

02:38:05.530 --> 02:38:09.590
back to the stairs. But Mr. Win how did you

02:38:09.590 --> 02:38:12.870
know he cheated? We didn't see anything on the cameras.

02:38:13.510 --> 02:38:16.250
Clive asks. Hank shakes his head.

02:38:16.910 --> 02:38:20.850
Idiot. I always take the aces out of the pack

02:38:20.850 --> 02:38:22.710
and make sure that I get the kings.

02:38:23.270 --> 02:38:25.970
He says and he goes back into the casino to

02:38:25.970 --> 02:38:26.930
play another game.

02:38:27.770 --> 02:38:31.630
But for a moment Clive and Kenny wait. Stepping backwards

02:38:31.630 --> 02:38:34.350
so that the waves caused by the feeding

02:38:34.350 --> 02:38:37.710
frenzy do not get at them. For a moment Clive

02:38:37.710 --> 02:38:42.670
is silent. Then he slowly says something as if he

02:38:42.670 --> 02:38:48.070
what he's saying. I changed the pack of cards before

02:38:48.070 --> 02:38:48.970
the last game.

02:38:49.990 --> 02:38:55.730
I never told Mr. Win. You mean Clive nods. The

02:38:55.730 --> 02:38:58.970
aces were in the pack and for a little while

02:38:58.970 --> 02:39:02.470
more they wait until the surface of the pool is

02:39:02.470 --> 02:39:06.010
calm again. I guess he was telling the truth then

02:39:06.550 --> 02:39:09.430
and they shut the door on what remains of Jimmy

02:39:09.430 --> 02:39:09.770
Lane.

02:39:12.150 --> 02:39:13.170
The Tube

02:39:15.210 --> 02:39:18.990
The air of the tube platform is hot and dry

02:39:18.990 --> 02:39:23.110
and the lights weak and unnatural. Sarah considers

02:39:23.110 --> 02:39:25.490
sitting in one of the seats by the wall of

02:39:25.490 --> 02:39:28.630
the tunnel. But she's so tired that she thinks that

02:39:28.630 --> 02:39:32.590
maybe she'll fall asleep if she rests. So she stands

02:39:32.590 --> 02:39:35.530
and she looks around at her fellow commuters

02:39:35.530 --> 02:39:41.750
and other passengers. 20 tired faces. Some talking but most

02:39:41.750 --> 02:39:44.050
are silent and waiting like her.

02:39:44.890 --> 02:39:48.570
She looks at the electronic clock. It is 7.36.

02:39:49.770 --> 02:39:52.070
Her train should be here in two minutes.

02:39:53.030 --> 02:39:55.670
For a moment she thinks about how quiet the platform

02:39:55.670 --> 02:39:58.770
is and how normally she has to fight to get

02:39:58.770 --> 02:39:58.910
on

02:39:58.910 --> 02:40:01.550
the train in the evening. But there will be no

02:40:01.550 --> 02:40:04.690
fighting today. The few people that are here

02:40:04.690 --> 02:40:08.250
look half dead, exhausted from a long day at work

02:40:08.250 --> 02:40:10.850
and made passive by the slow journey home.

02:40:12.190 --> 02:40:17.450
Home. Sarah thinks about her cozy sofa and the Chinese

02:40:17.450 --> 02:40:19.870
takeaway she will eat while watching TV.

02:40:20.890 --> 02:40:23.590
She can get it as she passes the restaurant, buy

02:40:23.590 --> 02:40:25.970
a bottle of wine from the local shop and be

02:40:25.970 --> 02:40:26.110
in

02:40:26.110 --> 02:40:29.930
bed by 10 o'clock. It is a comforting but

02:40:29.930 --> 02:40:33.250
also rather depressing thought. But that's life.

02:40:33.970 --> 02:40:39.010
Work. Eat. Sleep. She hears the train in the dark

02:40:39.010 --> 02:40:40.930
tunnel and tells herself to wake up

02:40:40.930 --> 02:40:45.090
and to focus for another 40 minutes. The 40 minutes

02:40:45.090 --> 02:40:47.470
from Liverpool Street to North Acton.

02:40:48.150 --> 02:40:51.570
The train speeds out of the tunnel and she enjoys

02:40:51.570 --> 02:40:54.270
the feeling of the wind in her dark brown hair.

02:40:55.210 --> 02:40:58.330
As it stops she sees her reflection in the mirror

02:40:58.330 --> 02:40:58.930
of the carriage.

02:40:59.670 --> 02:41:02.490
I look like death. She thinks.

02:41:03.530 --> 02:41:06.410
The doors of the carriage is open. A few people

02:41:06.410 --> 02:41:08.810
get off and Sarah and the commuters get on.

02:41:09.530 --> 02:41:12.410
Inside the carriage it's even hotter than on the platform.

02:41:13.370 --> 02:41:14.770
But it's almost empty too.

02:41:15.530 --> 02:41:19.650
She finds a seat and sits down. Do not fall

02:41:19.650 --> 02:41:21.650
asleep. She tells herself.

02:41:22.590 --> 02:41:25.930
She looks around the carriage. There are only eight other

02:41:25.930 --> 02:41:26.590
people there.

02:41:26.590 --> 02:41:30.450
A young couple holding hands and talking quietly on the

02:41:30.450 --> 02:41:31.330
seat opposite her.

02:41:32.030 --> 02:41:35.150
Two businessmen a few seats to her right. An old

02:41:35.150 --> 02:41:36.770
lady two seats to her left.

02:41:37.650 --> 02:41:39.390
A mother and son at the far end of the

02:41:39.390 --> 02:41:43.070
carriage. And a strange looking man in a coat in

02:41:43.070 --> 02:41:43.410
the corner.

02:41:44.450 --> 02:41:49.490
A strange man. Is he strange? Or are you just

02:41:49.490 --> 02:41:51.910
being silly? She looks at him.

02:41:52.550 --> 02:41:54.930
She cannot see his face because he has the hood

02:41:54.930 --> 02:41:56.170
of his sports jacket up.

02:41:56.590 --> 02:41:59.930
But he seems to be asleep. And there's something about

02:41:59.930 --> 02:42:01.550
his face that she does not like.

02:42:02.350 --> 02:42:06.350
He has a short beard and pale unhealthy skin. And

02:42:06.350 --> 02:42:08.830
she thinks that his eyes are probably unkind.

02:42:09.990 --> 02:42:12.910
The train starts. And she shakes her head.

02:42:13.790 --> 02:42:17.010
You are an idiot. She tells herself and pulls a

02:42:17.010 --> 02:42:17.990
book out of her bag.

02:42:18.750 --> 02:42:20.950
On the front there's a picture of a man with

02:42:20.950 --> 02:42:24.110
a short beard and pale skin and unkind eyes.

02:42:24.930 --> 02:42:26.290
She almost laughs.

02:42:27.270 --> 02:42:30.450
You need to stop reading this rubbish. You're losing your

02:42:30.450 --> 02:42:30.890
mind.

02:42:31.670 --> 02:42:32.430
She tells herself.

02:42:33.330 --> 02:42:35.610
The man in the corner is probably just a normal

02:42:35.610 --> 02:42:38.630
guy and not some horrible character from one of her

02:42:38.630 --> 02:42:39.230
thrillers.

02:42:39.850 --> 02:42:43.530
For ten minutes, she reads her crime novel. She starts

02:42:43.530 --> 02:42:44.450
to feel better.

02:42:45.410 --> 02:42:48.610
More relaxed and less concerned about the reason why the

02:42:48.610 --> 02:42:50.090
tube is so quiet today.

02:42:51.070 --> 02:42:52.790
Then the train stops at another station.

02:42:53.570 --> 02:42:56.690
There are loud voices on the platform and Sarah knows

02:42:56.690 --> 02:42:56.990
why.

02:42:58.130 --> 02:43:01.950
The doors slide open and ten or twelve students from

02:43:01.950 --> 02:43:04.030
Chancery High School enter the carriage.

02:43:05.310 --> 02:43:07.430
The old woman two seats away from her does not

02:43:07.430 --> 02:43:10.070
look happy and she moves to sit in the seat

02:43:10.070 --> 02:43:10.830
next to Sarah.

02:43:11.610 --> 02:43:13.090
Do you mind, dear?

02:43:13.870 --> 02:43:16.330
No, of course not, Sarah says and smiles.

02:43:17.410 --> 02:43:19.810
The poor old woman must not feel too comfortable next

02:43:19.810 --> 02:43:20.830
to the noisy kids.

02:43:21.390 --> 02:43:23.430
But Sarah knows that they're okay.

02:43:24.330 --> 02:43:26.610
She can spot the bad kids from a mile away.

02:43:27.350 --> 02:43:29.090
She is, after all, a teacher.

02:43:30.030 --> 02:43:33.430
No, these kids are okay, but they are loud and

02:43:33.430 --> 02:43:35.730
it's impossible for Sarah not to hear their conversation.

02:43:37.030 --> 02:43:39.230
And when she hears the topic that they are talking

02:43:39.230 --> 02:43:41.490
about, she suddenly feels cold.

02:43:42.470 --> 02:43:44.310
Yeah, he killed another one, didn't he?

02:43:44.650 --> 02:43:45.610
Last Friday they reckon?

02:43:46.210 --> 02:43:47.430
The tallest of the kids says,

02:43:48.070 --> 02:43:49.510
I know, sick, isn't it?

02:43:49.890 --> 02:43:51.210
I mean, how many is that now?

02:43:51.830 --> 02:43:52.610
asks another.

02:43:53.570 --> 02:43:54.010
Six?

02:43:54.790 --> 02:43:55.790
No, man, seven.

02:43:56.590 --> 02:43:57.090
Is it?

02:43:57.890 --> 02:43:59.670
Man, you know, the sick thing is that no one

02:43:59.670 --> 02:44:00.530
knows who it is.

02:44:01.230 --> 02:44:03.190
I don't know if it's a man, a woman, some

02:44:03.190 --> 02:44:04.230
kid, you get me?

02:44:04.830 --> 02:44:07.170
No, the sick thing is the way he kills them.

02:44:07.750 --> 02:44:11.750
He uses something strange, not a knife, but something long

02:44:11.750 --> 02:44:12.370
and thin,

02:44:12.590 --> 02:44:14.910
and he stabs them again and again and they just

02:44:14.910 --> 02:44:15.890
bleed and bleed.

02:44:15.890 --> 02:44:18.590
Yeah, but the weird thing is none of them try

02:44:18.590 --> 02:44:20.730
to fight, says the tall kid.

02:44:21.490 --> 02:44:22.290
How do you know that?

02:44:22.870 --> 02:44:24.190
Because the newspapers said it.

02:44:24.730 --> 02:44:26.950
They said none of the victims looked like they tried

02:44:26.950 --> 02:44:27.470
to fight.

02:44:28.390 --> 02:44:31.310
They just, I don't know, let this guy stab them

02:44:31.310 --> 02:44:32.190
again and again.

02:44:32.970 --> 02:44:34.830
And now there is silence in the carriage.

02:44:35.870 --> 02:44:38.610
And Sarah sees that everyone is listening to the conversation,

02:44:39.670 --> 02:44:41.190
but she does not want to listen.

02:44:41.910 --> 02:44:45.210
And she takes her MP3 player from her bag and

02:44:45.210 --> 02:44:46.390
puts her headphones in.

02:44:47.150 --> 02:44:49.910
She does not want to think about their conversation or

02:44:49.910 --> 02:44:51.470
the horrible reason why the

02:44:51.470 --> 02:44:52.550
tube is so quiet.

02:44:53.570 --> 02:44:55.890
She does not want to think about the stories in

02:44:55.890 --> 02:44:56.270
the newspapers.

02:44:57.370 --> 02:44:59.530
She does not want to think about what the police

02:44:59.530 --> 02:45:01.610
are calling the tube murders.

02:45:02.670 --> 02:45:05.190
She closes her eyes and thinks about her sofa.

02:45:06.450 --> 02:45:08.350
Her Chinese takeaway and her bed.

02:45:09.090 --> 02:45:12.470
After a few more minutes, she feels the train stop

02:45:12.470 --> 02:45:14.930
and she is aware of the kids getting off.

02:45:15.950 --> 02:45:19.910
Just listen to the music, she tells herself, relax and

02:45:19.910 --> 02:45:20.290
rest.

02:45:21.170 --> 02:45:22.210
But don't sleep.

02:45:23.730 --> 02:45:24.370
Don't?

02:45:25.110 --> 02:45:28.830
But she is exhausted and her head begins to drop.

02:45:29.710 --> 02:45:31.790
And she feels herself falling asleep.

02:45:32.910 --> 02:45:36.830
And she dreams about dark tunnels and strange men watching

02:45:36.830 --> 02:45:37.150
her.

02:45:37.710 --> 02:45:40.150
Then she feels a sharp pain in her arm.

02:45:40.830 --> 02:45:41.950
And she almost screams.

02:45:42.910 --> 02:45:45.370
She looks to see what the pain is and pulls

02:45:45.370 --> 02:45:46.870
her headphones from her ears.

02:45:47.730 --> 02:45:50.610
I'm sorry, dear, the old woman says.

02:45:51.530 --> 02:45:54.510
And Sarah sees that the woman's cloth bag is touching

02:45:54.510 --> 02:45:55.130
her arm.

02:45:55.750 --> 02:45:56.910
Did I wake you up?

02:45:57.650 --> 02:45:59.230
It must be something in my bag.

02:45:59.710 --> 02:46:01.370
I have all my knitting things in here.

02:46:01.910 --> 02:46:04.630
The old woman looks very upset and apologetic.

02:46:05.350 --> 02:46:07.810
It's okay, Sarah says and smiles.

02:46:08.610 --> 02:46:09.530
I was just surprised.

02:46:10.370 --> 02:46:11.910
Oh, you poor thing.

02:46:12.450 --> 02:46:13.130
You look exhausted.

02:46:14.070 --> 02:46:15.750
I'll move my bags so you can sleep.

02:46:16.310 --> 02:46:16.970
It's okay.

02:46:17.310 --> 02:46:18.210
I don't want to sleep.

02:46:18.850 --> 02:46:19.810
No, you relax.

02:46:20.850 --> 02:46:21.910
The old woman says.

02:46:22.730 --> 02:46:25.270
And Sarah thinks the old lady has a kind smile.

02:46:26.130 --> 02:46:28.890
Sarah nods and is about to put her headphones back

02:46:28.890 --> 02:46:31.350
in her ears when she feels someone watching her.

02:46:32.050 --> 02:46:34.010
And she looks at the corner of the carriage.

02:46:34.630 --> 02:46:35.950
The strange man.

02:46:36.790 --> 02:46:39.690
The man who looks like the evil character from her

02:46:39.690 --> 02:46:40.050
thriller.

02:46:40.830 --> 02:46:42.130
His eyes are open now.

02:46:42.950 --> 02:46:44.350
And they are watching her.

02:46:45.110 --> 02:46:47.970
She feels a cold shiver move over her body.

02:46:48.790 --> 02:46:51.190
And suddenly she thinks that she feels a little ill.

02:46:51.990 --> 02:46:52.970
Is he watching her?

02:46:53.610 --> 02:46:54.290
She looks again.

02:46:55.270 --> 02:46:57.790
And yes, his hood is still covering his face,

02:46:57.790 --> 02:47:00.570
but she is sure that his eyes are focused on

02:47:00.570 --> 02:47:00.850
her.

02:47:01.550 --> 02:47:03.110
She tries to stay calm.

02:47:03.110 --> 02:47:05.790
There are still several people in the carriage.

02:47:06.730 --> 02:47:08.830
The young couple is still there and the two businessmen.

02:47:09.710 --> 02:47:12.890
And the next station is North Acton, her station.

02:47:13.570 --> 02:47:15.450
You just need to get home.

02:47:16.130 --> 02:47:16.950
She tells herself.

02:47:17.890 --> 02:47:20.130
And she feels the train slow down.

02:47:20.870 --> 02:47:22.570
And she knows she must get up.

02:47:23.350 --> 02:47:24.730
Is this your stop, dear?

02:47:25.530 --> 02:47:26.490
The old woman asks.

02:47:27.310 --> 02:47:27.930
Sarah nods.

02:47:28.930 --> 02:47:29.530
Oh, good.

02:47:30.410 --> 02:47:31.210
You're nearly home.

02:47:31.790 --> 02:47:33.790
Nearly time to get some sleep.

02:47:34.930 --> 02:47:36.090
Sarah tries to smile.

02:47:36.890 --> 02:47:38.010
Are you okay, dear?

02:47:38.810 --> 02:47:39.790
You look a little pale.

02:47:40.490 --> 02:47:42.050
Yes, just tired.

02:47:42.910 --> 02:47:44.790
You should put some water on your face.

02:47:45.170 --> 02:47:45.850
You'll feel better.

02:47:46.670 --> 02:47:47.350
Sarah nods.

02:47:48.170 --> 02:47:49.170
I will, thank you.

02:47:49.890 --> 02:47:51.210
I will, she thinks.

02:47:52.110 --> 02:47:54.950
But only if the strange man stays on the train.

02:47:55.790 --> 02:47:58.350
If he follows me, I will shout and scream for

02:47:58.350 --> 02:47:58.570
help.

02:47:59.370 --> 02:48:01.790
She stands up and looks in the corner of the

02:48:01.790 --> 02:48:02.990
carriage one more time.

02:48:03.950 --> 02:48:05.610
But it looks like the man is asleep.

02:48:06.630 --> 02:48:08.650
Go, go now, she tells herself.

02:48:09.650 --> 02:48:12.550
The door's open and she quickly walks through them.

02:48:13.250 --> 02:48:16.030
For a few seconds, she walks and then turns back

02:48:16.030 --> 02:48:17.290
to look at the tube train.

02:48:18.270 --> 02:48:19.050
No one is there.

02:48:20.070 --> 02:48:22.570
No one gets off, apart from her, she is sure.

02:48:23.430 --> 02:48:26.110
The train starts again and she relaxes a little.

02:48:26.710 --> 02:48:28.950
The platform at North Acton is quiet.

02:48:29.790 --> 02:48:31.650
But it always is at this time of the evening.

02:48:32.570 --> 02:48:34.630
She can see the stairs to the street and she

02:48:34.630 --> 02:48:35.610
wants to walk to them.

02:48:36.210 --> 02:48:37.650
But she feels so weak.

02:48:38.490 --> 02:48:40.490
She decides to go into the station toilets.

02:48:41.730 --> 02:48:43.090
All she needs is a little water.

02:48:43.990 --> 02:48:46.270
She enters the ladies and stands in front of the

02:48:46.270 --> 02:48:46.450
mirror.

02:48:47.390 --> 02:48:48.170
Her arm hurts.

02:48:49.270 --> 02:48:50.690
So she takes her jacket off.

02:48:51.630 --> 02:48:53.890
And in the mirror, she can see a small drop

02:48:53.890 --> 02:48:55.230
of blood on her skin.

02:48:56.110 --> 02:48:57.090
It's okay, dear.

02:48:57.410 --> 02:48:58.610
You'll feel better in a moment.

02:48:59.210 --> 02:49:01.350
I gave you a little medicine to help you sleep.

02:49:02.110 --> 02:49:04.070
Sarah jumps at the sound of the voice.

02:49:04.850 --> 02:49:07.050
And in the mirror, she sees the reflection of the

02:49:07.050 --> 02:49:07.530
old woman.

02:49:08.410 --> 02:49:08.930
What?

02:49:09.770 --> 02:49:12.630
She tries to say, but then she falls to the

02:49:12.630 --> 02:49:12.890
floor.

02:49:14.030 --> 02:49:17.350
Help me, she says, in a weak voice.

02:49:18.430 --> 02:49:19.710
The old woman smiles.

02:49:21.050 --> 02:49:22.210
But it is a horrible smile.

02:49:23.050 --> 02:49:24.410
I am helping you, dear.

02:49:24.950 --> 02:49:26.030
You poor thing.

02:49:26.810 --> 02:49:29.070
So tired, so exhausted.

02:49:30.030 --> 02:49:31.390
You can't live like that.

02:49:32.130 --> 02:49:33.270
But it's okay now.

02:49:34.050 --> 02:49:35.290
I'm here to help you.

02:49:35.950 --> 02:49:39.370
And the old woman takes a long, thin knitting needle

02:49:39.370 --> 02:49:40.350
from her bag.

02:49:41.450 --> 02:49:44.090
And Sarah remembers what the kid said on the tube.

02:49:44.870 --> 02:49:46.570
He uses something strange.

02:49:47.730 --> 02:49:50.270
Not a knife, but something long and thin.

02:49:51.090 --> 02:49:53.310
And he stabs them again and again.

02:49:53.310 --> 02:49:56.430
And they just bleed and bleed.

02:49:57.790 --> 02:49:59.010
She tries to scream.

02:50:00.630 --> 02:50:01.890
But it is too late.

02:50:03.950 --> 02:50:06.130
I'll feed her her by audible.

